{"title_page": "Derek Jeter", "text_new": "{{short description|American baseball player}}\n{{pp-semi-blp|small=yes}}\n{{Infobox baseball biography\n|name=Derek Jeter\n|image=Derek Jeter batting stance allison.jpg\n|width=250\n|caption=Jeter in 2008\n|alt=A man in a grey baseball uniform with a navy helmet prepares to swing at a pitch\n|position=[[Shortstop]]\n|bats=Right\n|throws=Right\n|birth_date={{birth date and age|mf=yes|1974|6|26}}\n|birth_place=[[Pequannock Township, New Jersey]]\n|debutleague = MLB\n|debutdate=May 29\n|debutyear=1995\n|debutteam=New York Yankees\n|finalleague = MLB\n|finaldate=September 28\n|finalyear=2014\n|finalteam=New York Yankees\n|statleague = MLB\n|stat1label=[[Batting average (baseball)|Batting average]]\n|stat1value=.310\n|stat2label=[[Hit (baseball)|Hits]]\n|stat2value=3,465\n|stat3label=[[Home run]]s\n|stat3value=260\n|stat4label=[[Run batted in|Runs batted in]]\n|stat4value=1,311\n|teams =\n* [[New York Yankees]] (1995\u20132014)\n|awards =\n* 14\u00d7 [[Major League Baseball All-Star Game|All-Star]] ([[1998 MLB All-Star Game|1998]]\u2013[[2002 MLB All-Star Game|2002]], [[2004 MLB All-Star Game|2004]], [[2006 MLB All-Star Game|2006]]\u2013[[2012 MLB All-Star Game|2012]], [[2014 MLB All-Star Game|2014]])\n* 5\u00d7 [[World Series]] champion ({{wsy|1996}}, {{wsy|1998}}\u2013{{wsy|2000}}, {{wsy|2009}})\n* [[World Series MVP]] (2000)\n* [[AL Rookie of the Year]] (1996)\n* 5\u00d7 [[Rawlings Gold Glove Award|Gold Glove Award]] (2004\u20132006, 2009\u20132010)\n* 5\u00d7 [[Silver Slugger Award]] (2006\u20132009, 2012)\n* 2\u00d7 [[AL Hank Aaron Award]] (2006, 2009)\n* [[Roberto Clemente Award]] (2009)\n* [[List of New York Yankees team captains|New York Yankees captain]] (2003\u20132014)\n* [[New York Yankees#Retired numbers|New York Yankees No. 2]] retired\n* [[Monument Park (Yankee Stadium)|Monument Park]] honoree\n|hoflink = National Baseball Hall of Fame and Museum\n|hoftype = National\n|hofdate = [[2020 Baseball Hall of Fame balloting|2020]]\n|hofvote = 99.75% (first ballot)\n|hoffuture = true<!--this prepends \"Incoming\" in the infobox text, do not delete until HOF induction in July 2020-->\n}}\n\n'''Derek Sanderson Jeter''' ({{IPAc-en|\u02c8|d\u0292|i\u02d0|t|\u0259r}} {{Respell|JEE|t\u0259r}}; born June 26, 1974) is an American former professional [[baseball]] [[shortstop]], businessman, and baseball executive. He has been the [[chief executive officer]] (CEO) and part owner of the [[Miami Marlins]] of [[Major League Baseball]] (MLB) since September 2017. As a player, Jeter spent his entire 20-year MLB career with the [[New York Yankees]]. He was elected to the [[Baseball Hall of Fame]] in his first year of eligibility in [[2020 Baseball Hall of Fame balloting|2020]]; he received 396 of 397 possible votes (99.75%), the second-highest percentage in MLB history and the highest by a position player.\n\nA five-time [[World Series]] champion, Jeter is regarded as one of the primary contributors to the Yankees' success of the late 1990s and early 2000s for his hitting, base-running, fielding, and leadership. He is the Yankees' all-time career leader in [[Hit (baseball)|hits]] (3,465), [[Double (baseball)|doubles]] (544), games played (2,747), [[stolen base]]s (358), [[times on base]] (4,716), [[plate appearance]]s (12,602) and [[at bat]]s (11,195).<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/players/j/jeterde01.shtml |title=Derek Jeter |publisher=[[Sports Reference]] |date=May 25, 2014}}</ref> His accolades include 14 [[Major League Baseball All-Star Game|All-Star]] selections, five [[Rawlings Gold Glove Award|Gold Glove Awards]], five [[Silver Slugger Award]]s, two [[Hank Aaron Award]]s, and a [[Roberto Clemente Award]]. Jeter was the 28th player to reach [[3,000 hit club|3,000 hits]] and finished his career ranked sixth in MLB history in career hits and first among shortstops. In 2017, the Yankees [[List of Major League Baseball retired numbers|retired]] his uniform number 2.\n\nThe Yankees drafted Jeter out of high school in [[1992 Major League Baseball draft|1992]], and he debuted in the major leagues at age 20 in 1995. The following year, he became the Yankees' starting shortstop, won the [[Major League Baseball Rookie of the Year Award|Rookie of the Year Award]], and helped push the team to win the [[1996 World Series]]. Jeter continued to play during the team's championship seasons of 1998\u20132000; he finished third in voting for the [[American League]] (AL) [[Major League Baseball Most Valuable Player Award|Most Valuable Player (MVP) Award]] in 1998, recorded multiple career-high numbers in 1999, and won both the [[Major League Baseball All-Star Game Most Valuable Player Award|All-Star Game MVP]] and [[World Series Most Valuable Player Award|World Series MVP Awards]] in 2000. He consistently placed among the AL leaders in hits and runs scored for most of his career, and served as the Yankees' [[captain (baseball)|team captain]] from 2003 until his retirement in 2014. Throughout his career, Jeter contributed reliably to the Yankees' franchise successes. He holds many [[Major League Baseball postseason|postseason]] records, and has a .321&nbsp;[[batting average (baseball)|batting average]] in the World Series. Jeter has earned the nicknames \"Captain Clutch\" and \"Mr. November\" due to his outstanding play in the postseason.\n\nJeter was one of the most heavily marketed athletes of his generation and is involved in numerous product endorsements. As a celebrity, his personal life and relationships with other celebrities has drawn the attention of the media.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://espn.go.com/mlb/story/_/id/9227155/new-york-yankees-shortstop-derek-jeter-greatness-goes-numbers-espn-magazine|title= New York Yankees shortstop Derek Jeter's greatness goes beyond the numbers|first=Howard|last=Bryant|work=[[ESPN The Magazine]]|publisher=ESPN|date=May 7, 2013|accessdate=August 19, 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\n[[File:Derek Jeter and Dave Winfield.jpg|thumb|Jeter with his boyhood idol [[Dave Winfield]] at [[Dodger Stadium]], June 2010|alt=A man in a navy blue and grey windbreaker with the word \"New\" visible stands on the left facing a man in a navy blue polo shirt who is looking away.]]\n\nDerek Sanderson Jeter was born on June 26, 1974, in [[Pequannock Township, New Jersey]], the son of accountant Dorothy (n\u00e9e Connors) and substance abuse counselor Sanderson Charles Jeter. His mother is of [[English people|English]], [[Germans|German]], and [[Irish people|Irish]] ancestry, while his father is [[African Americans|African-American]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.chinapost.com.tw/sports/baseball/2011/07/11/309405/Derek-Jeter.htm |title=Derek Jeter rises to join Yankee greats |date=July 11, 2011|accessdate=July 11, 2011|newspaper=[[The China Post]]|first=Larry|last=Fine|agency=Reuters|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120930091142/http://www.chinapost.com.tw/sports/baseball/2011/07/11/309405/Derek-Jeter.htm|archivedate=September 30, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/derekjetercaptai0000robi|url-access=registration|title=Derek Jeter: Captain on and Off the Field|first=Tom|last=Robinson|publisher=Enslow Publishers, Inc.|isbn=978-0-7660-2819-7|year=2006|page=[https://archive.org/details/derekjetercaptai0000robi/page/18 18]}}</ref><ref>Stated on ''Finding Your Roots'', PBS, September 23, 2014</ref> They met while serving in the [[United States Army]] in Germany.<ref name=usatoday>{{cite news|title=For Yanks' Jeter, life is beautiful|newspaper=Westchester Journal News|first=Ian|last=O'Connor|date=October 26, 1999}}</ref> His father played baseball at [[Fisk University]] in Tennessee as a [[shortstop]],<ref name=\"kalamazookid\">{{cite journal|last=Jeter|first=Derek|title=Kalamazoo Kid|journal=Sports Illustrated|date=February 9, 2004|url=https://www.si.com/vault/2004/02/09/361522/kalamazoo-kid-the-yankees-shortstop-still-carries-a-torch-for--and-a-key-to--his-home-city|volume=100|issue=6|accessdate=August 21, 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140904085148/http://www.si.com/vault/2004/02/09/361522/kalamazoo-kid-the-yankees-shortstop-still-carries-a-torch-for--and-a-key-to--his-home-city|archivedate=September 4, 2014}}</ref> and holds a  PhD. When Jeter was a child, his parents made him sign a contract every year that defined acceptable and unacceptable forms of behavior.<ref name=60minutes/> Dorothy instilled a positive attitude in her son, insisting that he not use the word \"can't\".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/new-york/mlb/columns/story?columnist=howard_johnette&id=6742913|title=Don't forget what got Derek Jeter here|publisher=ESPN New York|first=Johnette|last=Howard|date=July 8, 2011|accessdate=October 31, 2011}}</ref> It was a baseball family, and Jeter's younger sister Sharlee (born {{circa}} 1979) was a [[softball]] star in high school.<ref name=usatoday/>\n\nThe Jeters lived in New Jersey until Derek was four years old, at which point they moved to [[Kalamazoo, Michigan]].<ref name=\"espnclassic\">{{cite news|url=http://espn.go.com/classic/biography/s/Jeter_Derek.html|title=Jeter Drives the Yankees|publisher=[[ESPN Classic]].com|last=Acocella|first=Nick|date=September 9, 2006|accessdate=July 23, 2009}}</ref> At age five Jeter began playing little league baseball. The children lived with their parents during the school year and spent their summers with their grandparents in New Jersey. Attending [[New York Yankees]] games with his grandparents, Jeter became a passionate fan of the team.<ref name=kalamazookid/><ref name=espnclassic/> Watching star outfielder [[Dave Winfield]] inspired him to pursue a career in baseball.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mlb.com/players/jeter_derek/news/article.jsp?story=06302006_news|title=Turn 2 Foundation celebrates 10th anniversary|accessdate=September 11, 2008|last=Mink|first=Ryan|date=June 29, 2006|publisher=MLB.com}}</ref>\n\nJeter attended [[Kalamazoo Central High School]], where he ran [[Cross country running|cross country]] in the fall, played [[basketball]] in the winter and baseball in the spring.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Adams|first1=Charlie|date=April 30, 2013|title=JOE MAUER OF THE TWINS: \"I THINK KIDS ARE SPECIALIZING WAY TOO SOON\"|url=http://www.ncsasports.org/blog/2013/04/30/joe-mauer-twins-kids-specializing/|publisher=[[National Collegiate Scouting Association Athletic Recruiting]]|accessdate=June 25, 2015}}</ref> Jeter posted high [[batting average (baseball)|batting average]]s for the school's baseball team; he batted .557 in his [[Tenth grade|sophomore year]] and .508 as a [[Eleventh grade|junior]].<ref name=espnclassic/> In his [[Twelfth grade|senior year]], he batted .508 and compiled 23&nbsp;[[Run batted in|runs batted in]] (RBIs), 21&nbsp;[[Base on balls|walks]], four [[home run]]s, a .637 [[on-base percentage]] (OBP), a .831 [[slugging percentage]] (SLG), 12&nbsp;[[stolen base]]s (in 12&nbsp;attempts), and only one [[strikeout]].<ref name=espnclassic/>\n\nJeter received several honors after his senior season. These included an All-State honorable mention, distinguishing him as one of the best high school baseball players in Michigan, the Kalamazoo Area [[B'nai B'rith]] Award for Scholar Athlete, the 1992 High School Player of the Year Award from the [[American Baseball Coaches Association]], the 1992 [[Gatorade]] High School [[Player of the year award]], and ''[[USA Today]]''{{'}}s High School Player of the Year.<ref name=espnclassic/><ref name=\"jeterbio\">{{cite web|url=http://www.mlb.com/players/jeter_derek/about/bio.jsp|title=Derek Jeter\u2014Biography|publisher=MLB.com|accessdate=July 23, 2009}}</ref> Jeter earned a baseball [[scholarship]] to attend the [[University of Michigan]] and play [[college baseball]] for the [[Michigan Wolverines baseball|Michigan Wolverines]].<ref name=olney2004/>\n\n==Professional career==\n===Draft===\nThe [[Houston Astros]] held the first overall pick in the [[1992 Major League Baseball draft|1992 MLB draft]]. [[Baseball Hall of Fame|Hall of Fame]] pitcher [[Hal Newhouser]], who worked for the Astros as a [[scout (sport)|scout]], evaluated Jeter extensively and lobbied team management to select him.<ref name=\"olney2004\">{{cite news|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/mlb/columns/story?columnist=olney_buster&id=1863947|title=Jeter: Dynasty's child|last=Olney|first=Buster|publisher=ESPN.com|date=August 23, 2004|accessdate=July 13, 2009}}</ref> Fearing Jeter would insist on a salary bonus of at least $1&nbsp;million to forgo college for a professional contract,<ref name=olney2004/> they chose [[California State University, Fullerton|Cal State Fullerton]] [[outfielder]] [[Phil Nevin]], who signed for $700,000.<ref name=olney2004/> Newhouser felt so strongly about Jeter's potential that he quit his job with the Astros in protest after they ignored his drafting advice.<ref>{{cite news|last=Olney|first=Buster|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2001/10/17/sports/baseball-what-can-we-do-next-just-watch-jeter-play.html|title=Baseball&nbsp;\u2013 What Can We Do Next? Just Watch Jeter Play|newspaper=The New York Times|date=October 17, 2001|accessdate=July 4, 2010}}</ref>\n\nThe Yankees, who selected sixth, also rated Jeter highly.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2011/07/08/sports/baseball/one-hit-for-derek-jeter-and-little-else-for-the-yankees.html|title=Rays 5, Yankees 1: Jeter Moves a Hit Closer as the Yanks Fall Again|first=Sam|last=Borden|newspaper=The New York Times|date=July 8, 2011|accessdate=November 30, 2011}}</ref> Yankees scout Dick Groch, assigned to scout in the [[Midwest]], watched Jeter participate in an all-star camp held at [[Western Michigan University]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.newsday.com/sports/baseball/yankees/zimmer-salutes-jeter-as-all-time-great-1.3011680|title=Zimmer salutes Jeter as all-time great|newspaper=Newsday|first=Barbara|last=Baker|date=July 7, 2011|accessdate=April 24, 2012}}</ref> Though Yankees officials were concerned that Jeter would attend college instead of signing a professional contract, Groch convinced them to select him, saying, \"the only place Derek Jeter's going is to [[Baseball Hall of Fame|Cooperstown]]\".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/2011/writers/joe_lemire/07/07/derek.jeter/index.html#ixzz1SxfZCzux |first=Joe |last=Lemire |title=Jeter not defined by number 3,000 |work=Sports Illustrated |date=July 7, 2011 |accessdate=July 23, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110711071935/http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/2011/writers/joe_lemire/07/07/derek.jeter/index.html |archivedate=July 11, 2011 }}</ref> The second through fifth picks were [[Paul Shuey]], [[B. J. Wallace]], [[Jeffrey Hammonds]], and [[Chad Mottola]]; those five would combine for two All-Star Game appearances (Nevin and Hammonds).<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/06/06/sports/baseball/06jeter.html?pagewanted=all|title=Five Players Who Outranked Jeter, if Only Briefly|first=Tyler|last=Kepner|newspaper=The New York Times|date=June 5, 2010|accessdate=April 24, 2012}}</ref> The Yankees drafted Jeter, who chose to turn pro, signing for $800,000.<ref name=\"journey\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2009/09/12/sports/baseball/12jeterteammates.html|title=Teammates Recall Jeter's Journey From Minor Leagues to Great Yankee|newspaper=The New York Times|first=Jack|last=Curry|date=September 12, 2009|accessdate=July 23, 2011}}</ref>\n\n===Minor leagues (1992\u20131995)===\nJeter played four seasons in [[minor league baseball]], then known as the National Association of Professional Baseball Leagues (NAPBL). Jeter began the [[1992 in baseball|1992 season]] with the [[Gulf Coast League Yankees|Gulf Coast Yankees]] of the [[Rookie-level|Rookie]]-level [[Gulf Coast League]], based in [[Tampa, Florida]]. In his first professional game, Jeter failed to get a hit in seven at-bats, going [[O-fer|0-for-7]], while striking out five times.<ref name=\"sensed what was to come\"/> Jeter continued to struggle during the rest of the season, batting .202 in 47 games.<ref name=olney2004/><ref name=\"sensed what was to come\"/> Manager [[Gary Denbo]] benched Jeter in the season's final game to ensure his average would not drop below .200, known in baseball as the [[Mendoza Line]].<ref name=\"mendoza\">{{cite news|url=http://web.minorleaguebaseball.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20110504&content_id=18638298&fext=.jsp&vkey=news_milb|title='Captain' Jeter developed in Minors: Gangly, homesick kid turned into a legend in O'Connor's book|first=Benjamin|last=Hill|work=MiLB.com|date=May 16, 2011|accessdate=November 23, 2011}}</ref> Frustrated by his lack of success and homesick, Jeter accrued $400-per-month phone bills from daily calls to his parents.<ref name=journey/><ref name=\"sensed what was to come\"/>\n\nThe Yankees promoted Jeter to the [[Greensboro Grasshoppers|Greensboro Hornets]] of the [[Class A (baseball)|Class A]] [[South Atlantic League]] (SAL) to give him more at-bats.<ref name=\"sensed what was to come\"/> He batted .247 in his first 11 games with Greensboro, and struggled defensively, making nine [[error (baseball)|errors]] in 48 [[fielding chance|chances]].<ref name=\"sensed what was to come\"/> Weighing {{convert|156|lbs|kg}}, Jeter had a scrawny appearance that did not match his reputation as the Yankees' future leader.<ref name=journey/> [[Jorge Posada]] and [[Andy Pettitte]], who played for the Hornets that season, at first questioned the hype surrounding Jeter, but recognized his talent and poise.<ref name=\"sensed what was to come\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2009/09/13/sports/baseball/13jeter.html?_r=1|title=Even in Class A, Posada and Pettitte Sensed What Was to Come With Jeter|first=Jack|last=Curry|newspaper=The New York Times|date=September 12, 2009|accessdate=May 11, 2012}}</ref>\n\nJeter focused the next offseason on his fielding.<ref name=olney2004/><ref name=mendoza/> ''[[Baseball America]]'' rated Jeter among the top 100 prospects in baseball before the [[1993 in baseball|1993 season]], ranking him 44th.<ref name=\"top100\">{{cite web|url=http://www.baseballamerica.com/today/prospects/rankings/top-100-prospects/all-time.html|title=All-Time Top 100 Prospects|work=Baseball America|accessdate=April 23, 2012}}</ref> Returning to the Hornets in 1993, his first full season of professional baseball, Jeter hit .295 with five home runs, 71 RBIs, and 18 stolen bases; SAL managers voted him the \"Most Outstanding Major League Prospect\" in the league.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=V91HAAAAIBAJ&sjid=vP8MAAAAIBAJ&pg=3679,4921919&dq=derek-jeter+albany&hl=en|title=Jeter Fits in Yankees' Near Future|page=D2|newspaper=Record-Journal|date=August 28, 1994|accessdate=April 9, 2012}}</ref> He finished second in the SAL in [[triple (baseball)|triples]] (11), third in hits (152), and eleventh in batting average, and was named to the postseason All-Star team.<ref name=jeterbio/> Jeter committed 56 errors, a SAL record.<ref name=mendoza/> Despite this, he was named the SAL's Best Defensive Shortstop, Most Exciting Player, and Best Infield Arm by ''Baseball America''.<ref name=jeterbio/><ref>{{cite news|url=http://espn.go.com/classic/biography/s/jeterderekadd.html|title=Jeter always in position to win|accessdate=September 8, 2008|last=Acocella|first=Nick|date=June 21, 2004|publisher=ESPN Classic}}</ref>\n\nComing off his strong 1993 season, ''Baseball America'' rated Jeter as the 16th-best prospect in baseball.<ref name=top100/> Jeter played for the [[Tampa Tarpons|Tampa Yankees]] of the [[Class A-Advanced]] [[Florida State League]] (FSL), the [[Richmond Flying Squirrels|Albany-Colonie Yankees]] of the [[Class AA]] [[Eastern League (baseball)|Eastern League]], and the [[Columbus Clippers]] of the [[Triple-A (baseball)|Class AAA]] [[International League]] during the [[1994 in baseball|1994 season]],<ref>{{cite news|url=https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/orlandosentinel/access/77941605.html?dids=77941605:77941605&FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:FT&type=current&date=Aug+28%2C+1994&author=Gordon+Edes%2C+Fort+Lauderdale+Sun-Sentinel&pub=Orlando+Sentinel&desc=YANKS+THINK+JETER+CLOSE+TO+MAJORS&pqatl=google|title=Yanks Think Jeter Close to Majors|newspaper=Fort Lauderdale Sun Sentinel|first=Gordon|last=Edes|date=August 28, 1994|accessdate=April 9, 2012}} {{subscription required|date=April 2012}}</ref> combining to hit .344 with five home runs, 68&nbsp;RBIs, and steal 50 bases across the three levels. He was honored with the [[Baseball America Minor League Player of the Year Award|Minor League Player of the Year Award]] by ''[[Baseball America]]'', ''[[The Sporting News]]'', ''[[USA Today Minor League Player of the Year Award|USA Today]]'', and [[Topps]]/NAPBL.<ref name=jeterbio/><ref name=olney2004/> He was also named the most valuable player of the FSL.<ref name=jeterbio/>\n\nConsidered the fourth-best prospect in baseball by ''Baseball America'' heading into the [[1995 in baseball|1995 season]],<ref name=top100/> Jeter was projected as the starting shortstop for the Yankees. However, he suffered mild [[inflammation]] in his right shoulder in the [[Arizona Fall League]] after the conclusion of the 1994 regular season. As a precaution, the Yankees signed [[Tony Fern\u00e1ndez]] to a two-year contract. With Fern\u00e1ndez the starting shortstop, the Yankees assigned Jeter to Class AAA.<ref name=\"replacement\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1995/02/28/sports/baseball-top-prospect-s-bottom-line-is-no-replacement-games.html|title=Baseball; Top Prospect's Bottom Line Is No Replacement Games|newspaper=The New York Times|first=Jack|last=Curry|date=February 28, 1995|accessdate=March 15, 2010}}</ref> During the [[1994\u201395 Major League Baseball strike]], [[Gene Michael]], the Yankees' [[General manager (baseball)|general manager]], offered Jeter the opportunity to work out for the MLB team with [[List of Major League Baseball replacement players|replacement players]] in [[spring training]] before the 1995 season. Jeter denied receiving the offer, and he did not [[strikebreaker|cross the picket line]].<ref name=replacement/>\n\n===Major leagues (1995\u20132014)===\n\n====1995\u20131998====\nEarly in the [[1995 New York Yankees season|1995 season]], Fern\u00e1ndez and [[infielder]] [[Pat Kelly (infielder)|Pat Kelly]] were injured. Consequently, Jeter made his MLB debut on May 29, 1995.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.nydailynews.com/archives/sports/tony-jeter-article-1.684987 |title=With Tony Down, Jeter's Looking Up |first=Jeff |last=Bradley |newspaper=New York Daily News |date=May 29, 1995 |accessdate=April 7, 2014}}</ref> He was assigned [[Uniform number (Major League Baseball)|uniform number]] 2, which was most recently worn by [[Mike Gallego]] from 1992 to 1994.<ref>{{cite web |last=Callahan |first=Maureen |date=March 30, 2014 |publisher= NY Post |title=Jeter's retirement marks end of Yanks' single-digit numbers |url=https://nypost.com/2014/03/30/jeters-retirement-marks-end-of-yanks-single-digit-numbers/ |accessdate=July 8, 2014}}</ref> [[Batting order (baseball)|Batting ninth]], he went hitless in five [[at bat]]s, striking out once.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/boxes/SEA/SEA199505290.shtml|title=May 29, 1995: New York Yankees at Seattle Mariners Box Score and Play by Play|publisher=Baseball-Reference.com|accessdate=June 5, 2012}}</ref> The following day, he recorded his first two major league hits and scored his first two career runs.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1995/05/31/sports/baseball-bullpen-lets-down-perez-and-yanks.html|title=Baseball; Bullpen Lets Down Perez And Yanks|first=Tom|last=Friend|newspaper=The New York Times |date=May 31, 1995 |accessdate=April 24, 2012}}</ref> Jeter batted .250<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/players/j/jeterde01-bat.shtml |title=Derek Jeter Batting Statistics and History |publisher=Baseball-Reference.com |accessdate=August 12, 2012}}</ref> and committed two errors in 13&nbsp;games before being demoted to Class AAA Columbus; Fern\u00e1ndez replaced Jeter at shortstop.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1995/06/12/sports/baseball-an-ailing-leyritz-and-yanks-recover.html |title=Baseball: An Ailing Leyritz And Yanks Recover |newspaper=The New York Times |first=Jack |last=Curry |date=June 12, 1995 |accessdate=October 16, 2009}}</ref> The Yankees advanced to the [[Major League Baseball postseason|postseason]] in 1995. Jeter traveled with the team during the [[1995 American League Division Series]] (ALDS), though he was not on the active roster. The Yankees lost to the [[Seattle Mariners]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Herrmann|first=Mark|title=How Derek Jeter's glorious career began|work=Newsday|date=March 29, 2014|url=http://www.newsday.com/sports/baseball/yankees/derek-jeter/how-derek-jeter-s-glorious-career-began-1.7536966|accessdate=July 3, 2016}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Derek Jeter defense.jpg|thumb|left|250px|Jeter tagging out [[Miguel Tejada]] in 2007|alt=Jeter in a grey baseball uniform tags his glove to a baserunner from the opposing team.]]\nAfter Fern\u00e1ndez batted a disappointing .245 and appeared in only 108&nbsp;games due to injuries in 1995, newly hired [[List of New York Yankees managers|Yankees manager]] [[Joe Torre]] turned to Jeter for the [[1996 New York Yankees season|1996 season]],<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1995/12/13/sports/baseball-torre-is-sure-of-only-one-thing-jeter-is-his-shortstop.html |title=Baseball: Torre Is Sure Of Only One Thing: Jeter Is His Shortstop |newspaper=The New York Times |first=Jack |last=Curry |date=December 13, 1995 |accessdate=October 16, 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://articles.courant.com/1996-03-19/sports/9603190402_1_yankees-season-opener-fielding-pat-kelly |title=Fernandez Fields Move to Second Well: Injury to Kelly Creates Another Chance |newspaper=Hartford Courant |first=Jack |last=O'Connell |date=March 19, 1996 |page=C.2 |accessdate=December 5, 2011}}</ref> hoping for a .250 batting average and dependable defense.<ref name=roy/> [[List of New York Yankees owners and executives|Yankees owner]] [[George Steinbrenner]], often skeptical of younger players, was unconvinced. After [[Clyde King]], a close Steinbrenner advisor, observed Jeter for two days in spring training in 1996, he came away with the impression that Jeter was not yet ready to contribute at the major league level.<ref name=zimmer/> To provide depth to the team at the shortstop position after an injury to Fern\u00e1ndez, Steinbrenner approved a trade that would have sent pitcher [[Mariano Rivera]] to the Mariners for shortstop [[F\u00e9lix Ferm\u00edn]], but Michael, by then the vice president of scouting, and assistant general manager [[Brian Cashman]] convinced Steinbrenner to give Jeter an opportunity.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.usatoday.com/sports/baseball/al/yankees/2009-10-06-yankees-quartet_N.htm |title=For Yanks quartet, winning a fifth title would add to a legacy |date=October 7, 2009 |first=Mel |last=Antonen |newspaper=USA Today |accessdate=December 5, 2011}}</ref>\n\nRated the sixth-best prospect in baseball by ''Baseball America'' heading into the 1996 season,<ref name=top100/> Jeter started on [[Opening Day]], the first Yankee [[rookie]] to start as shortstop for the team since [[Tom Tresh]] in 1962.<ref name=espnclassic/>{{refn|Though Jeter debuted with the Yankees in 1995, he qualified as a rookie in 1996, as he had fewer than 130 at-bats during the 1995 season.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://mlb.mlb.com/mlb/official_info/about_mlb/rules_regulations.jsp |title=MLB Miscellany: Rules, regulations and statistics|publisher=MLB.com |accessdate=June 5, 2012}}</ref>|group=lower-alpha}} He hit his first MLB home run that day.<ref name=roy/> With his speed and ability to execute the [[hit-and-run (baseball)|hit and run]], Jeter served as a complement to [[leadoff hitter]] [[Tim Raines]] while batting in the ninth spot in the [[Batting order (baseball)|batting order]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1996/09/23/sports/raines-and-jeter-adding-sizzle.html |title=Raines And Jeter Adding Sizzle |first=Selena |last=Roberts |newspaper=The New York Times |date=September 23, 1996 |accessdate=June 5, 2012}}</ref> By year's end Jeter far exceeded Torre's expectations &ndash; and anyone's &ndash; hitting .314 with 10&nbsp;home runs, 104&nbsp;[[runs scored]], and 78&nbsp;RBIs.<ref name=roy/> He was named the unanimous [[MLB Rookie of the Year award|AL Rookie of the Year]], receiving all 28 first-place votes in only the fifth sweep in the honor's 50-year history.<ref name=\"roy\">{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1996/11/05/sports/it-s-no-contest-as-jeter-captures-rookie-of-the-year.html |title=It's No Contest as Jeter Captures Rookie of the Year |first=Jack |last=Curry |newspaper=The New York Times |date=November 5, 1996|accessdate=July 12, 2012}}</ref>{{refn|As first-place votes are worth five points, second-place votes are worth three points, and third-place votes are worth one point, Jeter won the balloting with 140 points, ahead of [[James Baldwin (baseball)|James Baldwin]] (64 points), [[Tony Clark]] (30 points), [[Rocky Coppinger]] (6 points) and [[Jos\u00e9 Rosado]] (6 points).<ref name=roy/>|group=lower-alpha}}\n\nThe Yankees reached the 1996 postseason, and Torre batted Jeter in the leadoff spot based on his strong year-long performance.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=XSMxAAAAIBAJ&sjid=3-UFAAAAIBAJ&pg=4620,348727&dq=derek-jeter+leadoff&hl=en |title=Texas' home haunts visiting Yankees |newspaper=Gettysburg Times |page=B4 |date=October 1, 1996|accessdate=June 5, 2012}}</ref> During Game 1 of the [[1996 American League Championship Series|1996 American League Championship Series (ALCS)]], the Yankees trailed the [[Baltimore Orioles]] 4\u20133 in the 8th inning when Jeter hit a fly ball to [[right fielder|right field]] that was ruled a home run by the [[Umpire (baseball)|umpires]] after twelve-year-old fan [[Jeffrey Maier]] reached over the wall to catch the ball. Though the ball would have remained in play if not for Maier, and could have been caught by [[Tony Tarasco]], the home run stood as called, tying the game. It marked the first home run of Jeter's postseason career. The Yankees won the game and defeated the Orioles in five games.<ref name=\"maier\">{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2006/04/14/sports/baseball/14maier.html |title=Boy Who Helped Yankees Is a Hit Again |accessdate=September 11, 2008 |last=Lapointe |first=Joe |date=April 14, 2006 |newspaper=The New York Times}}</ref> Overall, Jeter batted .361 in the 1996 postseason, helping to lead the Yankees offensively with [[Bernie Williams]], as [[Wade Boggs]], [[Paul O'Neill (baseball)|Paul O'Neill]], and [[Tino Martinez]] struggled.<ref name=roy/> The Yankees defeated the [[Atlanta Braves]] in the [[1996 World Series]] to win their first championship since the [[1978 World Series]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/postseason/1996_WS.shtml |title=1996 World Series |publisher=Baseball-Reference.com |accessdate=November 25, 2011}}</ref>\n\nFollowing his Rookie of the Year campaign, considered the \"new crop\" of shortstops, along with [[Alex Rodriguez]] and [[Nomar Garciaparra]], as the careers of older shortstops such as [[Cal Ripken Jr.]], [[Barry Larkin]], [[Ozzie Smith]], and [[Alan Trammell]] were concluding.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/vault/article/magazine/MAG1009523/index.htm |date=February 24, 1997 |title=Long on Shortstops: The Yankees' Derek Jeter is part of a rich crop of young players who are redefining the position |authorlink=Tom Verducci |first=Tom |last=Verducci |work=Sports Illustrated |accessdate=October 25, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120119074123/http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/vault/article/magazine/MAG1009523/index.htm |archivedate=January 19, 2012 }}</ref> Rodriguez, the first overall selection in the [[1993 MLB draft]], first contacted Jeter about his experiences as a high-first round pick. The two became friends to the extent that ''The New York Times'' journalist Jack Curry commented \"[r]arely have two higher-profile opponents been as close\". Rodriguez described Jeter as being \"like my brother\", even though they were on-field adversaries.<ref name=\"friendship\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2004/02/16/sports/baseball-friendship-of-2-stars-is-safe-after-they-were-on-the-outs.html|first=Jack|last=Curry|title=Friendship of 2 Stars Is Safe After They Were on the Outs|newspaper=The New York Times|date=February 16, 2004|accessdate=July 24, 2012}}</ref>\n\nBefore the [[1997 New York Yankees season|1997 season]], Jeter and the Yankees agreed on a $540,000 contract with performance bonuses.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1997/03/11/sports/yankees-and-jeter-reach-agreement.html|title=Yankees And Jeter Reach Agreement|first=Jason|last=Diamos|newspaper=The New York Times|date=March 11, 1997|accessdate=October 25, 2011}}</ref> Becoming the Yankees' leadoff batter,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=CSTB&p_theme=cstb&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_topdoc=1&p_text_direct-0=0EB422FBC935316E&p_field_direct-0=document_id&p_perpage=10&p_sort=YMD_date:D&s_trackval=GooglePM|newspaper=Chicago Sun-Times|title=McDowell gets 1st start|page=6|date=April 6, 1997|accessdate=June 5, 2012}} {{subscription required|date=June 2012}}</ref> Jeter batted .291, with 10&nbsp;home runs, 70&nbsp;RBIs, 116&nbsp;runs, and 190&nbsp;[[hit (baseball)|hits]].<ref name=\"br\">{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/j/jeterde01.shtml|title=Derek Jeter Statistics and History|accessdate=September 11, 2008|publisher=Baseball-Reference.com}}</ref> Though he hit two home runs during the [[1997 American League Division Series]], the Yankees lost to the [[Cleveland Indians]], three games to two.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/postseason/1997_ALCS.shtml|title=1997 American League Championship Series|publisher=Baseball-Reference.com|accessdate=November 25, 2011}}</ref>\n\nJeter earned $750,000 for the [[1998 New York Yankees season|1998 season]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1998/05/31/sports/sports-of-the-times-jeter-is-still-the-torres-little-boy-shortstop.html|title=Sports of The Times; Jeter Is Still The Torres' 'Little Boy' Shortstop|first=Dave|last=Anderson|newspaper=The New York Times|date=May 31, 1998|accessdate=April 18, 2012}}</ref> That year, Jeter was selected for his first [[Major League Baseball All-Star Game|All-Star Game]]. In the regular season, he batted&nbsp;.324 with a league-leading 127&nbsp;runs, 19&nbsp;home runs, and 84&nbsp;RBIs,<ref name=br/> for a team that won 114&nbsp;games during the regular season and is widely considered to be one of the greatest of all time.<ref>{{cite news|title=Yankees best ever: They didn't have stars, just perfect team approach|url=https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/boston/access/35310008.html?FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:FT&type=current&date=Oct+23%2C+1998&author=Bob+Ryan%2C+Globe+Staff&pub=Boston+Globe&desc=Yankees+best+ever+They+didn't+have+stars%2C+just+perfect+team+approach&pqatl=google|newspaper=[[The Boston Globe]]|first=Bob|last=Ryan|authorlink=Bob Ryan|date=October 23, 1998|page=E.1|accessdate=November 25, 2011}} {{subscription required|date=November 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.boston.com/news/packages/mlbplayoffs98/best_ever.htm|title=Are these Yankees the best team ever?|work=[[Boston.com]]|first=Ben|last=Walker|date=October 22, 1998|accessdate=August 21, 2014}}</ref> In the playoffs, Jeter hit only .176 in the [[1998 American League Division Series|1998 ALDS]] and [[1998 American League Championship Series|ALCS]], but batted .353 in the [[1998 World Series|World Series]], as the Yankees defeated the [[San Diego Padres]] in four games.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/postseason/1998_WS.shtml|title=1998 World Series|publisher=Baseball-Reference.com|accessdate=November 25, 2011}}</ref> At season's end, Jeter finished third in voting for the [[Major League Baseball Most Valuable Player Award|AL Most Valuable Player (MVP) Award]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/awards/awards_1998.shtml#ALmvp|title=1998 Awards Voting|publisher=[[Baseball-Reference.com]]|accessdate=December 9, 2011}}</ref>\n\n====1999\u20132002====\n[[File:Derek Jeter 1999.jpg|thumb|left|250px|Jeter in his distinctive early career upright batting stance at the [[U.S. Cellular Field|new Comiskey Park]], 1999]]\nEligible for [[salary arbitration]] for the first time before the [[1999 New York Yankees season|1999 season]], Jeter was awarded a $5&nbsp;million salary.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/nypost/access/68475517.html?dids=68475517:68475517&FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:FT&type=current&date=Feb+17%2C+1999&author=Tom+Keegan&pub=New+York+Post&desc=JETER+%245M%2C+YANKEES+0+%3A+LOCK+UP+DEREK+LONG+TERM+NOW&pqatl=google|title=Jeter $5M, Yankees 0: Lock Up Derek Long Term Now|newspaper=New York Post|first=Tom|last=Keegan|page=60|date=February 17, 1999|accessdate=April 18, 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120725091927/http://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/nypost/access/68475517.html?dids=68475517%3A68475517&FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS%3AFT&type=current&date=Feb+17%2C+1999&author=Tom+Keegan&pub=New+York+Post&desc=JETER+%245M%2C+YANKEES+0+%3A+LOCK+UP+DEREK+LONG+TERM+NOW&pqatl=google|archivedate=July 25, 2012}} {{subscription required|date=April 2012}}</ref> Jeter led the AL in hits that season with 219, while finishing second in the league in batting average (.349) and runs scored (134), appearing in his second All-Star game that year.<ref name=br/> His season totals in batting average, runs, hits, runs batted in, [[Double (baseball)|doubles]] (37), [[Triple (baseball)|triples]] (9), home runs (24), SLG (.552), and OBP (.438) are all personal bests.<ref name=br/> Jeter, who for part of the year hit third in the batting order, also drove in 102 runs, becoming only the second Yankee shortstop to do so, following [[Lyn Lary]]'s 107 RBIs in 1931.<ref name=br/> In the postseason, Jeter batted .455 in the [[1999 American League Division Series|ALDS]], .350 in the [[1999 American League Championship Series|ALCS]], and .353 in the [[1999 World Series|World Series]],<ref name=br/> as the Yankees defeated the Braves to win another championship, Jeter's third.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/postseason/1999_WS.shtml|title=1999 World Series|publisher=Baseball-Reference.com|accessdate=November 25, 2011}}</ref>\n\nDuring the 1999\u20132000 offseason, the Yankees negotiated with Jeter, tentatively agreeing to a seven-year, $118.5&nbsp;million contract.<ref name=189mil/> However, because Steinbrenner did not want to set a record for the largest contract, Steinbrenner waited while [[Juan Gonz\u00e1lez (baseball)|Juan Gonz\u00e1lez]] and the [[Detroit Tigers]] negotiated on a reported eight-year, $143&nbsp;million contract extension. When that agreement fell through, so did Jeter's tentative deal. To avoid arbitration, Jeter and the Yankees agreed to a one-year deal worth $10&nbsp;million.<ref name=189mil/><ref>{{cite news|url=https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/nypost/access/68846006.html?dids=68846006:68846006&FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:FT&type=current&date=Feb+04%2C+2000&author=TOM+KEEGAN&pub=New+York+Post&desc=JETER%2C+YANKS+%2410M+DEAL%2CAVOID+HEARING&pqatl=google|title=Jeter, Yanks $10M Deal, Avoid Hearing|newspaper=New York Post|first=Tom|last=Keegan|date=February 4, 2000|accessdate=November 25, 2011|page=107|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120725055804/http://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/nypost/access/68846006.html?dids=68846006%3A68846006&FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS%3AFT&type=current&date=Feb+04%2C+2000&author=TOM+KEEGAN&pub=New+York+Post&desc=JETER%2C+YANKS+%2410M+DEAL%2CAVOID+HEARING&pqatl=google|archivedate=July 25, 2012}} {{Subscription required|date=November 2011}}</ref>\n\nJeter batted a team-best .339 in the 2000 regular season and added 15&nbsp;home runs, 73&nbsp;RBIs, 119&nbsp;runs scored, and 22&nbsp;stolen bases.<ref name=br/><ref name=189mil/> In the [[2000 Major League Baseball All-Star Game|2000 MLB All-Star Game]], he recorded three hits, including a two-run single that gave his team the lead and victory. The performance earned him the [[Major League Baseball All-Star Game Most Valuable Player Award|All-Star Game MVP Award]], the first time a Yankee won the award.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2000/07/12/sports/baseball-jeter-gives-the-fans-an-all-star-performance.html|title=Baseball; Jeter Gives the Fans an All-Star Performance|first=Jack|last=Curry|newspaper=The New York Times|date=July 12, 2000|accessdate=December 7, 2011}}</ref> During the postseason, he batted only .211 in the [[2000 American League Division Series|Division Series]] but rebounded to hit .318 in the [[2000 American League Championship Series|Championship Series]] against the [[Seattle Mariners]], and .409 in the [[2000 World Series|World Series]] against the [[New York Mets]].<ref name=br/> Jeter added two home runs, a triple, and two doubles in the World Series, including a leadoff home run on the first pitch of Game 4 and a triple later in the third inning.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/baseball/mlb/2000/world_series/news/2000/10/25/yankees_mets_game4_ap/|work=Sports Illustrated|title=Jeter provides spark; Yankees one stop from three-peat|date=October 25, 2000|accessdate=November 25, 2011|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130811082750/http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/baseball/mlb/2000/world_series/news/2000/10/25/yankees_mets_game4_ap/|archivedate=August 11, 2013}}</ref> His home run in Game 5 tied the game and extended his World Series hitting streak to 14&nbsp;games.<ref name=\"wsmvp\">{{cite news|url=http://www.cbc.ca/sports/baseball/yankees-awed-by-mvp-jeter-1.226956|title=Yankees awed by MVP Jeter|date=October 27, 2000|work=[[CBC Sports]]|publisher=[[Canadian Broadcasting Corporation]]|first=Hal|last=Bock|accessdate=August 21, 2014}}</ref> The Yankees defeated the Mets in five games for their third consecutive title and fourth in Jeter's first five full seasons.<ref name=189mil/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/postseason/2000_WS.shtml|title=2000 World Series|publisher=Baseball-Reference.com|accessdate=December 7, 2011}}</ref> Jeter won the [[World Series Most Valuable Player Award|World Series MVP Award]], becoming the only player to win the All-Star Game MVP and World Series MVP Awards in the same season.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/awards/postmvp.shtml|title=MLB Post-Season World Series MVP Awards & All-Star Game MVP Award Winners|publisher=Baseball-Reference.com|accessdate=December 7, 2011}}</ref>\n\nWith one year remaining until he would become eligible for [[free agent|free agency]], Jeter signed a ten-year, $189&nbsp;million contract before the 2001 season to remain with the Yankees.<ref name=\"189mil\">{{cite web|url=http://abcnews.go.com/Sports/story?id=99854|title=Jeter, Yankees Reach Deal|work=[[ABC News]]|date=February 9, 2001|first=Ronald|last=Blum|accessdate=August 21, 2014}}</ref> [[Alex Rodriguez]] had signed a ten-year, $252&nbsp;million contract with the [[Texas Rangers (baseball)|Texas Rangers]] earlier in the offseason, setting the market for Jeter's negotiations. Jeter became the [[List of largest sports contracts|second-highest-paid athlete]] across all [[team sport]]s and [[auto racing]], trailing only Rodriguez. The $18.9&nbsp;million average annual value of Jeter's contract was the third-highest in baseball, behind only Rodriguez ($25.2&nbsp;million) and [[Manny Ramirez]] ($20&nbsp;million).<ref name=189mil/>\n\nIn 2001, Jeter posted another strong season, batting .311 with 21&nbsp;home runs, 74&nbsp;RBIs, 110&nbsp;runs scored, and 27&nbsp;stolen bases, making his fourth All-Star appearance.<ref name=br/> Jeter made a notable defensive [[assist (baseball)|assist]] in Game 3 of the [[2001 American League Division Series]] against the [[Oakland Athletics]]. With [[Jeremy Giambi]] on [[first base]], Oakland right fielder [[Terrence Long]] hit a double off Yankees pitcher [[Mike Mussina]] into the right-field corner. As Giambi rounded [[third base]] and headed for [[home plate]], Yankees right fielder [[Shane Spencer]] retrieved the ball and made a wild throw that missed [[cut-off man]] Tino Martinez and dribbled down the first-base line. Jeter ran from shortstop to grab the ball and flipped it backhanded to catcher [[Jorge Posada]], rather than throwing it overhand.<ref name=\"Baseball's most amazing plays\"/> Posada tagged Giambi out on the leg just before he crossed home plate, preserving the Yankees' one-run lead. Facing elimination, the Yankees eventually won the game, as well as the series. The play, known as \"The Flip\",<ref name=espnclassic/> was later voted seventh in ''[[Baseball Weekly]]''{{'}}s 10 Most Amazing Plays of all time,<ref name=\"Baseball's most amazing plays\">{{cite news|url=https://www.usatoday.com/sports/bbw/2002-07-24/cover-side2.htm|title=Baseball's most amazing plays|accessdate=September 8, 2008|newspaper=USA Today|date=July 24, 2002}}</ref> and won the 2002 [[Best Play ESPY Award]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=AD&p_theme=ad&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_topdoc=1&p_text_direct-0=0FC4C0F9E8D89D18&p_field_direct-0=document_id&p_perpage=10&p_sort=YMD_date:D&s_trackval=GooglePM|date=July 13, 2003|newspaper=[[The Advocate (Louisiana)|The Advocate]]|title=Henderson's big play in running for ESPY|accessdate=November 23, 2011|url-access=subscription }}</ref>\n\n[[File:911 President George W. Bush at World Series, 10302001..jpg|thumb|right|Jeter chats with President [[George W. Bush]] before Game 3 of the [[2001 World Series]]]]\nAs a result of the [[September 11 attacks]], the start of the playoffs was delayed and the season's end was extended past the usual October timeframe. The Yankees advanced to the [[2001 World Series]] to face the [[Arizona Diamondbacks]]. Game 4 marked the first time that any non-exhibition MLB game had been played in the month of November.<ref name=espnclassic/> In extra innings, Jeter hit a game-winning home run off of [[Byung-hyun Kim]]. The words \"Mr. November\" flashed on the scoreboard, alluding to former Yankee [[Reggie Jackson]]'s nickname, \"Mr. October\".<ref name=espnclassic/> Despite the home run, Jeter slumped at the plate; he denied injuries were a factor, though a fall into a photographer's box trying to catch a [[foul ball]] may have aggravated an earlier [[hamstring]] injury.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/USAToday/access/87197366.html?dids=87197366:87197366&FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:FT&type=current&date=Oct+31%2C+2001&author=Mike+Dodd&pub=USA+TODAY&desc=Jeter+struggling+to+reverse+slump+%3B+Yankees+shortstop+feels+good+at+plate%2C+confident+hits+will+come&pqatl=google|title=Jeter struggling to reverse slump; Yankees shortstop feels good at plate, confident hits will come|newspaper=USA Today|first=Mike|last=Dodd|date=October 31, 2001|page=C.06|accessdate=November 25, 2011}} {{subscription required|date=November 2011}}</ref> Jeter batted .148 in the World Series, as the Yankees lost in seven games.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/postseason/2001_WS.shtml|title=2001 World Series|publisher=Baseball-Reference.com|accessdate=November 25, 2011}}</ref>\n\nJeter batted .297, with 18&nbsp;home runs, 75&nbsp;RBIs, 124&nbsp;runs scored, 191&nbsp;hits, and a career-best 32&nbsp;stolen bases during the [[2002 New York Yankees season|2002 regular season]]. He led the majors in stolen base percentage (91.4%), getting caught only three times. He made his fifth All-Star appearance.<ref name=br/> In the 2002 postseason, the [[Anaheim Angels]] defeated the Yankees in the [[2002 American League Division Series|ALDS]] on their way to winning the [[2002 World Series|World Series]].<ref name=\"jeter is back\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2003/05/14/sports/baseball-jeter-is-back-but-yankees-take-the-night-off.html|title=Baseball; Jeter Is Back, but Yankees Take the Night Off|first=Tyler|last=Kepner|newspaper=The New York Times|date=May 14, 2003|accessdate=April 24, 2012}}</ref>\n\n====2003\u20132008====\nOn Opening Day of the [[2003 New York Yankees season|2003 season]], Jeter dislocated his left shoulder when he collided with [[Toronto Blue Jays]] catcher [[Ken Huckaby]] at third base.<ref>{{cite news|title=Jeter suffers dislocated left shoulder in collision|work=ESPN.com|date=April 1, 2003|url=http://static.espn.go.com/mlb/news/2003/0331/1531991.html|accessdate=March 5, 2009}}</ref> He was placed on the [[disabled list]] for six weeks and missed 36&nbsp;games; he had never played fewer than 148&nbsp;games in the prior seven full seasons.<ref>{{cite news|title=Yanks win after injury takes out Jeter|newspaper=USA Today|date=April 1, 2003|url=https://www.usatoday.com/sports/baseball/games/2003-03-31-jeter-injury_x.htm|accessdate=June 5, 2008}}</ref> Jeter returned to bat .324, finishing third in batting average to [[Bill Mueller]], who batted .326. Ramirez finished second.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/leagues/AL/2003-batting-leaders.shtml|title=2003 American League Batting Leaders|publisher=Baseball-Reference.com|accessdate=November 23, 2011}}</ref><ref name=\"jeter looks back on 2003\"/>\n\nSteinbrenner named Jeter the [[List of New York Yankees captains|captain of the Yankees]] on June 3, 2003, following eight seasons without a captain after [[Don Mattingly]] retired in 1995.<ref name=\"captain\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2003/06/04/sports/baseball-steinbrenner-appoints-jeter-captain-of-the-yankees.html|title=Baseball: Steinbrenner appoints Jeter captain of the Yankees|first=Tyler|last=Kepner|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|date=June 4, 2003|accessdate=October 12, 2009}}</ref> That postseason, Jeter batted .314 with two home runs, five RBIs, and 10 runs scored across 17 playoff games,<ref name=\"jeter looks back on 2003\">{{cite web|url=http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20031027&content_id=595297&vkey=news_mlb&fext=.jsp&c_id=mlb|date=October 27, 2003|title=Jeter looks back on 2003: Yankees' captain reflects on tough season|first=Mark|last=Feinsand|publisher=MLB.com|accessdate=July 3, 2016|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130729134041/http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20031027&content_id=595297&vkey=news_mlb&fext=.jsp&c_id=mlb|archivedate=July 29, 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref> including three hits in Game 3 of the [[2003 World Series]] against the [[Florida Marlins]]&nbsp;\u2013 the only three hits [[Josh Beckett]] allowed during the game.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/nypost/access/429451511.html?dids=429451511:429451511&FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:FT&type=current&date=Oct+23%2C+2003&author=Kevin+Kernan&pub=New+York+Post&desc=DEREK+SHOWS+HIS+STRIPES%3A+PLAYOFFS+TURN+JETER+INTO+A+REAL+TIGER&pqatl=google|title=Derek Shows His Stripes: Playoffs Turn Jeter Into a Real Tiger|newspaper=New York Post|first=Kevin|last=Kernan|date=October 23, 2003|accessdate=April 24, 2012|page=94|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120725050640/http://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/nypost/access/429451511.html?dids=429451511%3A429451511&FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS%3AFT&type=current&date=Oct+23%2C+2003&author=Kevin+Kernan&pub=New+York+Post&desc=DEREK+SHOWS+HIS+STRIPES%3A+PLAYOFFS+TURN+JETER+INTO+A+REAL+TIGER&pqatl=google|archivedate=July 25, 2012}} {{subscription required|date=April 2012}}</ref> Jeter committed a crucial error in a Game 6 loss, and the Marlins won the series in six games.<ref name=\"jeter looks back on 2003\"/>\n\n[[File:Derek Jeter 2004.jpg|thumb|upright|Jeter during batting practice before a game in 2004|alt=Derek Jeter stands in front of a batting cage wearing a navy long-sleeve shirt over a baseball uniform while holding a weighted bat in his left hand.]]\n\nThe Yankees acquired Rodriguez from the [[Texas Rangers (baseball)|Texas Rangers]] during the 2003\u201304 offseason. Rodriguez had won two [[List of Gold Glove Award winners at shortstop|Gold Glove Awards at shortstop]]<ref name=\"assure\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2004/02/17/sports/baseball/17YANK.html|title=Baseball; Yanks Assure Jeter He's Safe at Shortstop|first=Tyler|last=Kepner|newspaper=The New York Times|date=February 17, 2004|accessdate=April 24, 2012}}</ref> and was considered the best shortstop in baseball.<ref name=friendship/> Jeter\u2014who had no Gold Gloves at the time\u2014remained the team's starting shortstop while Rodriguez moved to third base.<ref name=assure/> Rodriguez's fielding range allowed Jeter to cede ground to his right to Rodriguez and cheat to his left: fielding balls hit to his left is a weakness identified by scouts.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2006/10/15/sports/baseball/15score.html|date=October 15, 2006|title=Beyond the Tumult, Rodriguez Is a Key Contributor|first=Benjamin|last=Hoffman|newspaper=The New York Times|accessdate=July 18, 2012}}</ref> The 2004 season began with Jeter mired in a slump, at one point getting only one hit in a span of 36 at-bats; through April, he batted .168. His batting average improved to .277 by the [[All-Star break (MLB)|All-Star break]] in July.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2011/05/04/sports/baseball/04jeter.html|title=Under a Microscope, Jeter Has a Powerless Start skid in April|newspaper=The New York Times|first=Ben|last=Shpigel|date=May 3, 2011|accessdate=May 11, 2012}}</ref>\n\nJeter made the All-Star team and finished the season with a .292 average; 23&nbsp;home runs, the second-most of his career; 78&nbsp;RBIs; 111&nbsp;runs scored; and a career-best 44&nbsp;doubles, which broke the Yankee single-season record for doubles by a shortstop, besting [[Tony Kubek]]'s 38 in 1961.<ref name=br/><ref>{{cite news|url=https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/courant/access/709565091.html?dids=709565091:709565091&FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:FT&type=current&date=Oct+08%2C+2004&author=DOM+AMORE%3B+Courant+Staff+Writer&pub=Hartford+Courant&desc=THE+TAG+%60LEADER%27+STILL+FITS+%3B+JETER+MAKES+HIS+OWN+BREAK&pqatl=google|title=The Tag 'Leader' Still Fits; Jeter Makes His Own Break|newspaper=Hartford Courant|first=Don|last=Amore|date=October 8, 2004|accessdate=April 12, 2012|page=C.1}} {{subscription required|date=April 2012}}</ref> He batted .316 with a team-leading four RBIs as the Yankees defeated the [[Minnesota Twins]] in the [[2004 American League Division Series|2004 ALDS]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/nypost/access/710532551.html?dids=710532551:710532551&FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:FT&type=current&date=Oct+11%2C+2004&author=LENN+ROBBINS&pub=New+York+Post&desc=JETER%27S+MAKING+ALL+THE+PIVOTAL+PLAYS&pqatl=google|title=Jeter's Making All the Pivotal Plays|newspaper=New York Post|first=Lenn|last=Robbins|date=October 11, 2004|accessdate=April 24, 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120725072303/http://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/nypost/access/710532551.html?dids=710532551%3A710532551&FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS%3AFT&type=current&date=Oct+11%2C+2004&author=LENN+ROBBINS&pub=New+York+Post&desc=JETER%27S+MAKING+ALL+THE+PIVOTAL+PLAYS&pqatl=google|archivedate=July 25, 2012}} {{Subscription required|date=April 2012}}</ref> Jeter struggled in the [[2004 American League Championship Series|2004 ALCS]], batting .200 with one [[extra base hit]], as the Yankees lost the series to the Red Sox in seven games, despite winning the first three games.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/2004/writers/john_donovan/10/21/yankees.collapse/|title=Yankee magic disappears: Bronx Bombers fizzled out as Red Sox exorcise demons|date=October 21, 2004|first=John|last=Donovan|work=Sports Illustrated|accessdate=April 24, 2012|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130731061929/http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/2004/writers/john_donovan/10/21/yankees.collapse/|archivedate=July 31, 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn the 12th inning of a tied game on July 1, 2004, against their [[Yankees\u2013Red Sox rivalry|rivals]], the [[Boston Red Sox]], [[Trot Nixon]] hit a [[pop fly]] down the left field line. Jeter ran from his position at shortstop and made an over-the-shoulder catch. He launched himself over the third-base side railing and two rows of seats, receiving a lacerated chin and bruised face. The Yankees went on to win the game in the bottom of the 13th inning.<ref>{{cite news|title=Yankees rally following Jeter's heroics|work=ESPN.com|date=July 1, 2004|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/mlb/recap?gameId=240701110|accessdate=May 14, 2008}}</ref> This was voted the Play of the Year in the ''[[This Year in Baseball Awards]]'' competition, as voted on by fans at MLB.com.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://newyork.yankees.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20050426&content_id=1029292&vkey=news_nyy&fext=.jsp&c_id=nyy|title=Three Yankees honored by fans|first=Mark|last=Feinsand|work=MLB.com|date=April 26, 2005|accessdate=October 17, 2009|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110606130532/http://newyork.yankees.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20050426&content_id=1029292&vkey=news_nyy&fext=.jsp&c_id=nyy|archivedate=June 6, 2011}}</ref> Following the 2004 season, Jeter was presented with his first Gold Glove Award; his diving catch on July 1 was cited as a reason for the award.<ref name=\"gg1\">{{cite news|url=https://www.usatoday.com/sports/baseball/al/2004-11-02-gold-gloves_x.htm|title=Detroit's Rodriguez sets Gold Glove mark|agency=Associated Press|newspaper=USA Today|date=November 2, 2004|accessdate=April 24, 2012}}</ref> Though Jeter was fourth among shortstops in [[fielding percentage]] and errors, two traditional fielding statistics, critics pointed to his lower ratings in the more advanced [[sabermetric]] statistics, such as [[range factor]] and [[ultimate zone rating]] (UZR).<ref name=\"jeter's gold\">{{cite news|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/archives/sports/jeter-gold-yanks-article-1.609568|title=Jeter's Gold A First For Yanks|first=Sam|last=Borden|newspaper=New York Daily News|date=November 3, 2004|accessdate=July 12, 2012}}</ref>\n\nJeter was second in the AL in runs scored (122) in the 2005 season,<ref>{{cite web|title=2005 Baseball Leaderboard|publisher=FanGraphs|url=http://www.fangraphs.com/leaders.aspx?pos=all&stats=bat&lg=all&qual=y&type=1&season=2005|accessdate=May 10, 2008}}</ref> and was third in the league in both at bats (654) and hits (202). Though his critics continued to see Jeter as a liability defensively, he won his second consecutive Gold Glove in 2005. [[Orlando Cabrera]] of the Angels had a higher fielding percentage and committed fewer errors, but voters noted that Jeter had more assists.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/archives/sports/jeter-catches-gold-nets-2nd-straight-glove-article-1.655662|title=Jeter Catches More Gold. Nets 2nd Straight Glove|first=Sam|last=Borden|newspaper=New York Daily News|date=November 2, 2005|accessdate=August 21, 2014}}</ref> Though Jeter batted .333 during the [[2005 American League Division Series|2005 ALDS]], the Yankees lost to the Angels.<ref name=\"derek's flat fall\"/>\n\n[[File:Jeter Gets a Hit2.jpg|thumb|left|250px|Jeter connects for a hit against the [[Tampa Bay Devil Rays]] in 2006|alt=A baseball player in a grey uniform follows through with his swing, while a catcher on the opposing team in a white uniform squats behind him and an umpire in a black uniform stands behind the catcher.]]\n\nFor the 2006 season, the Yankees signed [[Johnny Damon]] to play center field and lead off, moving Jeter to the second position in the batting lineup.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/mlb/columns/story?columnist=klapisch_bob&id=2267855|title=Damon to give Yanks a major spark. With the addition of Johnny Damon, the Yankees will have a lineup in 2006 that will be a modern-day Murderers' Row|accessdate=April 24, 2012|date=December 21, 2005|first=Bob|last=Klapisch|authorlink=Bob Klapisch|publisher=ESPN.com}}</ref> During the [[2006 New York Yankees season|2006 season]], Jeter recorded his 2,000th career hit, becoming the eighth Yankee to reach the milestone.<ref name=\"hit\">{{cite web|url=http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20060526&content_id=1473280&vkey=news_mlb&fext=.jsp&c_id=mlb|title=Jeter collects career hit No. 2,000|accessdate=September 11, 2008|last=Stier|first=Kit|date=May 27, 2006|publisher=MLB.com}}</ref> Jeter finished the season second in the AL in both batting average (.343) and runs scored (118), third in hits (214), and fourth in OBP (.417), earning his seventh All-Star selection.<ref name=br/><ref name=\"deny tension\"/><ref>{{cite web|title=2006 Baseball Leaderboard|publisher=FanGraphs|url=http://www.fangraphs.com/leaders.aspx?pos=all&stats=bat&lg=all&qual=y&type=2&season=2006|accessdate=May 11, 2008}}</ref> Jeter batted .500 with one home run in the [[2006 American League Division Series|2006 ALDS]], including a perfect 5-for-5 performance in Game 1, making him the sixth player to record five hits in one postseason game.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2006/10/04/sports/baseball/04yankees.html?ref=sports|title=Yankees 8, Tigers 4: Jeter, as Usual, Saves His Best for October|first=Tyler|last=Kepner|newspaper=The New York Times|date=October 4, 2006|accessdate=May 17, 2012}}</ref> The Yankees lost to the [[Detroit Tigers]], three games to one.<ref name=\"derek's flat fall\"/>\n\nMany expected Jeter would win the AL MVP Award for 2006.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.baseball.ca/morneau-upsets-field-in-al-mvp-race |first=Kelly |last=Thesier |title=Morneau upsets field in AL MVP race |publisher=MLB.com |date=November 21, 2006 |accessdate=March 2, 2018}}</ref> In a close vote, Jeter finished second in the voting to [[Justin Morneau]] of the Twins.<ref name=\"mvp\">{{cite news|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/apps/news?pid=newsarchive&sid=aGOWQ5VYyQeQ&refer=us|title=Twins' Morneau Wins AL MVP Award Over Yankees' Jeter|first=Danielle|last=Sessa|date=November 21, 2006|work=[[Bloomberg Businessweek]]|accessdate=October 25, 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130729052900/http://www.bloomberg.com/apps/news?pid=newsarchive&sid=aGOWQ5VYyQeQ&refer=us|archivedate=July 29, 2013}}</ref>{{refn|Morneau received 15 of the 28 first-place votes, while Jeter received 12. Morneau won the balloting with 320 points to Jeter's 306 points.<ref name=mvp/>|group=lower-alpha}} It was his sixth top-10 finish in the MVP balloting in 11 full seasons through 2006.<ref name=br/> Though he lost the MVP Award, he won the [[Hank Aaron Award]], given for superior offensive performance.<ref name=\"deny tension\">{{cite news|url=http://www.sptimes.com/2006/10/26/Rays/Yanks__captain__manag.shtml|title=Yanks' captain, manager deny tension with A-Rod|newspaper=St. Petersburg Times|date=October 26, 2006|accessdate=April 24, 2012}}</ref> He also won his third consecutive Gold Glove Award.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2006/11/03/sports/baseball/03base.ready.html?_r=1|title=Mussina, Not Wright, Figures in Yanks' Pitching Plans|first=Tyler|last=Kepner|newspaper=The New York Times|date=November 3, 2006|accessdate=July 18, 2012}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Derek Jeter on Aug 3 2007.jpg|thumb|upright|Jeter in 2007]]\nThough the Yankees continued to struggle with postseason failures, Jeter remained a consistent contributor.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2006/11/23/sports/baseball/23araton.html|title=Intangibles Separate Rodriguez and Jeter|first=Harvey|last=Araton|newspaper=The New York Times|date=November 23, 2006|accessdate=July 13, 2012}}</ref> During the [[2007 New York Yankees season|2007 season]], Jeter was third in the AL with 203 hits, his third consecutive season and sixth overall, with at least 200 hits. He also finished ninth in batting average (.322).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/leagues/AL/2007-batting-leaders.shtml|title=2007 American League Batting Leaders|publisher=Baseball-Reference.com|accessdate=May 17, 2012}}</ref> He was selected for his eighth All-Star appearance.<ref name=br/> In the field, he was involved in turning a career-high 104 [[double play]]s.<ref name=br/> He struggled during the [[2007 American League Division Series|2007 ALDS]], batting 3-for-17 (.176) with one RBI, as the Indians defeated the Yankees.<ref name=\"derek's flat fall\">{{cite news|url=http://www.nypost.com/p/sports/yankees/item_2FiLv4VHclqoAp70rxqYPJ|title=Derek's Flat Fall: No October Magic For Usually Clutch Jeter|first=Mike|last=Puma|date=October 9, 2007|accessdate=April 24, 2012|newspaper=New York Post}}</ref>\n\nJeter hit his 400th career double on June 27, 2008,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://newyork.yankees.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20080627&content_id=3012989&vkey=recap&fext=.jsp&c_id=nyy|title=Giese, Yanks drop Game 1 of twin bill|accessdate=September 11, 2008|last=Hoch|first=Bryan|date=June 27, 2008|publisher=MLB.com|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081209075926/http://newyork.yankees.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20080627&content_id=3012989&vkey=recap&fext=.jsp&c_id=nyy|archivedate=December 9, 2008}}</ref> and his 200th home run on July 12.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.nj.com/yankees/index.ssf/2008/07/yankees_jeter_hits_200th_home.html|title=Yankees' Jeter hits 200th home run|first=Tom|last=Bergeron|newspaper=The Star-Ledger|date=July 12, 2008|accessdate=September 22, 2009}}</ref> Jeter's [[slugging percentage]] (SLG) dropped to .410 in the [[2008 New York Yankees season|2008 season]], his lowest mark since 1997.<ref name=br/> His offense took an upward turn after May as he hit .322 with a .824 OPS after June 1.<ref name=br/> Jeter was elected to his [[2008 Major League Baseball All-Star Game|ninth All-Star game]] as the starting shortstop.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.usatoday.com/sports/baseball/al/yankees/2008-07-13-jeter_N.htm|title=Pinstripes a perfect fit for Yankees All-Star Jeter|newspaper=USA Today|first=Paul|last=White|date=July 13, 2008|accessdate=November 25, 2011}}</ref> He finished the season with a .300 batting average.<ref name=br/>\n\nJeter tied [[Lou Gehrig]]'s record for hits at [[Yankee Stadium (1923)|Yankee Stadium]] (1,269) with a home run off [[Tampa Bay Rays]] pitcher [[David Price (baseball)|David Price]] on September 14, 2008.<ref name=\"tiegehrig\">{{cite news|url=http://www.nj.com/sports/index.ssf/2008/09/jeter_ties_hit_mark_in_new_yan.html|title=Derek Jeter ties Gehrig hits mark in New York Yankees' win over Rays; Cano benched|first=Lisa|last=Kennelly|newspaper=The Star-Ledger|date=September 14, 2008|accessdate=November 28, 2011}}</ref> On September 16, he broke the record against [[Chicago White Sox]] pitcher [[Gavin Floyd]].<ref name=\"beatgehrig\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2008/09/17/sports/baseball/17yankees.html|title=Yankees Fall, but Jeter Breaks a Gehrig Milestone|first=Joshua|last=Robinson|newspaper=The New York Times|date=September 17, 2008|accessdate=November 25, 2011}}</ref> The Yankees were eliminated from postseason contention,<ref>{{cite news|url=https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/nypost/access/1557785311.html?dids=1557785311:1557785311&FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:FT&type=current&date=Sep+19%2C+2008&author=MIKE+PUMA&pub=New+York+Post&desc=AT+LEAST+BOMBERS+WILL+AVOID+ANOTHER+ALDS+DEFEAT&pqatl=google|title=At Least Bombers Will Avoid Another ALDS Defeat|first=Mike|last=Puma|newspaper=New York Post|page=114|date=September 19, 2008|accessdate=April 24, 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120725055908/http://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/nypost/access/1557785311.html?dids=1557785311%3A1557785311&FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS%3AFT&type=current&date=Sep+19%2C+2008&author=MIKE+PUMA&pub=New+York+Post&desc=AT+LEAST+BOMBERS+WILL+AVOID+ANOTHER+ALDS+DEFEAT&pqatl=google|archivedate=July 25, 2012}} {{subscription required|date=April 2012}}</ref> the only full season in Jeter's career where he did not compete in the playoffs. Following the final game in Yankee Stadium history, Jeter made a speech at the request of the Yankees, thanking the Yankees fans for their support\u2014a moment later voted by fans as the Moment of the Year in MLB.com's This Year in Baseball Awards:<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mlb.mlb.com/mlb/awards/y2008/tyib/index.jsp|title=2008 This Year in Baseball Awards: Moment of the Year Nominees|publisher=MLB.com|accessdate=August 1, 2012}}</ref>\n{{quote|From all of us up here, it's a huge honor to put this uniform on every day and come out here and play. Every member of this organization, past and present, has been calling this place home for 85 years. There's a lot of tradition, a lot of history and a lot of memories. The great thing about memories is you're able to pass them along from generation to generation. Although things are going to change next year and we're going to move across the street, there are a few things with the New York Yankees that never change. That's pride, tradition and most of all, we have the greatest fans in the world. We're relying on you to take the memories from this stadium and add them to the new memories we make at the new Yankee Stadium and continue to pass them on from generation to generation. We just want to take this moment to salute you, the greatest fans in the world.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.nydailynews.com/2008-09-21/sports/17906999_1_yankee-stadium-memories-fans|title=Yankee Stadium's last word goes to captain Derek Jeter|newspaper=New York Daily News|first=Mark|last=Feisand|date=September 21, 2008|accessdate=August 1, 2012}}</ref>}}\n\n====2009\u20132013====\nFor the [[2009 New York Yankees season|2009 season]], Yankees [[Manager (baseball)|manager]] [[Joe Girardi]] switched Jeter and Damon in the batting order, with Damon moving to second and Jeter to the leadoff role.<ref name=\"leadoff\">{{cite news|url=http://www.nypost.com/p/sports/yankees/girardi_tinkers_with_top_of_yankees_SspwkYIX7keqo4wyTIkfkM|title=Girardi Tinkers With Top of Yankees Order|newspaper=New York Post|last=King|first=George A.|date=March 27, 2009|accessdate=September 27, 2009}}</ref> Jeter batted .334, third-best in the AL, with a .406 OBP, an .871 OPS, 18 home runs, 66 RBIs, 30 stolen bases in 35 attempts, 107 runs scored, 72 walks, and 212 hits (second in MLB).<ref name=br/> Defensively, Jeter committed a career-low eight errors, and his .986 fielding percentage was his career best.<ref name=\"gg2009\">{{cite news|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/sports/baseball/yankees/new-york-yankees-derek-jeter-mark-teixeira-win-gold-glove-awards-article-1.414911|title=New York Yankees Derek Jeter, Mark Teixeira win Gold Glove awards|first=Mark|last=Feinsand|newspaper=New York Daily News|date=November 10, 2009|accessdate=July 9, 2012}}</ref> The addition of Gold Glove-winning [[first baseman]] [[Mark Teixeira]] allowed [[second baseman]] [[Robinson Can\u00f3]] to shift his focus to his right, helping Jeter.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20091110&content_id=7646624&vkey=news_mlb&fext=.jsp&c_id=mlb|title=Jeter, Tex take home Gold Gloves: Captain picks up his fourth; it's first as Yankee for slugger|first=Bryan|last=Hoch|publisher=MLB.com|date=November 10, 2009|accessdate=July 18, 2012}}</ref> During the season, the ''[[Sporting News]]'' named Jeter eighth on their list of the 50 greatest current players in baseball.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.jsonline.com/sports/45556307.html|title=Braun makes greatest list|last=Wolfley|first=Bob|newspaper=[[Milwaukee Journal Sentinel]]|date=May 20, 2009|accessdate=July 24, 2009}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Derek Jeter Hit -2722 edit.jpg|upright|thumb|Jeter saluting the crowd after becoming the all-time Yankees hits leader in 2009|alt=A man in a white baseball uniform with navy pinstripes removes his helmet to salute the crowd, which is cheering for him.]]\nJeter achieved two career hit milestones in the second half of the 2009 season. On August 16, 2009, against the [[Seattle Mariners]], Jeter doubled down the right-field line for his 2,675th hit as a shortstop, breaking [[Luis Aparicio]]'s previous major league record.<ref name=\"shortstop\">{{cite news|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/sports/baseball/yankees/derek-jeter-all-time-hit-leader-shortstops-yankees-routed-mariners-article-1.399177|title=Derek Jeter becomes all-time hit leader among shortstops as Yankees routed by Mariners|newspaper=[[Daily News (New York)|New York Daily News]]|first=Mark|last=Feinsand|date=August 16, 2009|accessdate=October 7, 2010}}</ref> Then, Jeter became the all-time hits leader as a member of the Yankees (2,722), passing [[Lou Gehrig]] on September 11, 2009. The hit was a single off Baltimore Orioles pitcher [[Chris Tillman]] in the third inning.<ref name=\"hitrecord\">{{cite web|last=DiComo|first=Anthony|date=September 12, 2009|title=Jeter passes Gehrig with 2722nd hit|url=http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20090911&content_id=6909874&vkey=news_mlb&fext=.jsp&c_id=mlb|publisher=MLB.com|accessdate=September 13, 2009}}</ref>\n\nIn the 2009 postseason, Jeter batted .355, including .407 in the [[2009 World Series]],<ref name=br/> as he won his fifth World Series championship. He was named [[Sportsman of the Year]] for 2009 by ''[[Sports Illustrated]]'',<ref>{{cite news|url=http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/2009/magazine/specials/sportsman/2009/11/25/derek.jeter/index.html |date=November 30, 2009 |work=Sports Illustrated |title=SI names Derek Jeter 2009 Sportsman of the Year |accessdate=December 1, 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091201190714/http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/2009/magazine/specials/sportsman/2009/11/25/derek.jeter/index.html |archivedate=December 1, 2009 }}</ref> and won the [[Roberto Clemente Award]], [[Hank Aaron Award]],<ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.nydailynews.com/2009-11-02/sports/17939310_1_hank-aaron-award-base-roberto-clemente-award|title=New York Yankees' Derek Jeter is well-deserving of Hank Aaron Award|first=Anthony|last=McCarron|newspaper=New York Daily News|date=November 2, 2009|accessdate=June 25, 2012}}</ref> his fourth Gold Glove Award<ref name=gg2009/> and his fourth Silver Slugger Award. Jeter also finished third in the AL MVP voting, behind Minnesota's [[Joe Mauer]] and Yankee teammate [[Mark Teixeira]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2009/11/24/sports/baseball/24mauer.html|title=Mauer Near-Unanimous Pick as American League M.V.P|first=Tyler|last=Kepner|newspaper=The New York Times|date=November 23, 2009|accessdate=November 25, 2011}}</ref> It was also the fifth championship for Pettitte, Posada, and Rivera, who along with Jeter were referred to as the \"[[Core Four]]\".<ref>{{cite web|title=So Far, So Good |url=http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/vault/article/magazine/MAG1168943/1/index.htm |date=May 3, 2010 |accessdate=December 1, 2011 |first=Tom |last=Verducci |work=Sports Illustrated |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100505175509/http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/vault/article/magazine/MAG1168943/1/index.htm |archivedate=May 5, 2010 }}</ref>\n\nIn 2010, Jeter, along with Posada and Rivera, became the first trio of teammates in any of the four major league sports in North America (MLB, [[National Football League|NFL]], [[National Basketball Association|NBA]], or [[National Hockey League|NHL]]) to play in at least 16 consecutive seasons on the same team as teammates.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/mlb/recap?gameId=300406102|title=Scutaro's miscue leads to key run in Yankees' win over Red Sox|work=ESPN|agency=Associated Press|date=April 6, 2010|accessdate=April 6, 2010}}</ref> The [[2010 New York Yankees season|2010 season]] was statistically Jeter's worst in many respects.<ref name=\"back on track\">{{cite news|first=Mark|last=Feinsand|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/sports/baseball/yankees/york-yankees-hitting-coach-kevin-long-working-derek-jeter-captain-back-track-article-1.438707|title=New York Yankees hitting coach Kevin Long working with Derek Jeter to get captain back on track|newspaper=New York Daily News|date=September 14, 2010|accessdate=November 8, 2010}}</ref><ref name=\"sheehan\">{{cite news|url=http://www.foxnews.com/sports/2010/10/14/yankee-captain-derek-jeter-playing-new-contract-alcs/|title=Yankee captain Derek Jeter playing for new contract in ALCS|date=October 14, 2010|agency=Reuters|first=Daniel|last=Trotta|work=[[Fox News]]|accessdate=July 10, 2012}}</ref> The Yankee captain batted .270 with a .340 OBP and .370 SLG, all career lows,<ref name=sheehan/> as he hit more ground balls than usual.<ref name=\"turned back the clock\"/> Despite this, Jeter was elected to start at shortstop in the All-Star Game.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.nydailynews.com/2010-07-05/sports/27069067_1_jeter-and-rivera-phil-hughes-robinson-cano|title=Yankees manager Joe Girardi plans to get lefty Andy Pettitte on American League All-Star team roster|first1=Roger|last1=Rubin|first2=Mitch|last2=Abramson|first3=Peter|last3=Botte|newspaper=New York Daily News|date=July 5, 2010|accessdate=December 8, 2011}}</ref> He rebounded to bat&nbsp;.342 in his last 79&nbsp;at-bats after making adjustments to his swing with the help of [[Kevin Long (baseball)|Kevin Long]], the Yankees hitting coach, who had successfully helped [[Nick Swisher]] and [[Curtis Granderson]] make adjustments that improved their production. With Long, Jeter changed the way he strode with his left leg.<ref name=\"back on track\"/><ref>{{cite news|url=http://newyork.cbslocal.com/2010/11/4/sweeny-says-a-decade-with-derek/|title=Sweeny Says: A Decade With Derek|publisher=CBS New York|date=November 4, 2010|accessdate=March 8, 2011}}</ref> Following the season, Jeter won his fifth Gold Glove award.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20101109&content_id=16041110&vkey=news_mlb&c_id=mlb|title=Cano, Tex, Jeter honored with Gold Gloves|publisher=MLB.com|date=November 9, 2010|accessdate=March 8, 2011}}</ref> Jeter committed six errors during the season, his lowest total in 15 full seasons.<ref name=\"kepner\">{{cite news|last=Kepner|first=Tyler|title=Jeter's Gold Glove an Error, Metric Indicates|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/11/10/sports/baseball/10bats.html?ref=todayspaper|newspaper=The New York Times|page=B19|date=November 10, 2010|accessdate=November 10, 2010|quote=Jeter committed six errors this season, his lowest total in 15 full seasons.}}</ref>\n\n{{quote box|align=left|width=25%|\"He might go down, when it's all over, as the all-time Yankee.\"|source= \u2014[[Don Zimmer]], September 13, 2009<ref name=zimmer>{{cite news|url=http://articles.nydailynews.com/2009-09-14/sports/17931482_1_yankee-bench-coach-yankee-stadium-crowds-hits-record|title=Derek Jeter a hit with Don Zimmer going back to the very start of Yankee career|first=Bill|last=Madden|newspaper=New York Daily News|date=September 14, 2009|accessdate=April 24, 2012}}</ref>}}\nAfter the 2010 season, Jeter became a [[free agent]] for the first time in his career. At age 36, Jeter appeared to be in decline; [[Joe Sheehan]] of ''[[Baseball Prospectus]]'' suggested that Jeter, once a \"good, not great\" shortstop, had declined to become \"below average\" defensively,<ref name=sheehan/> to the extent that he would likely need to change positions; Cashman later acknowledged that Jeter might need to shift to the outfield.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20110125&content_id=16497734&vkey=news_mlb&c_id=mlb|title=Cashman: Jeter could move to outfield in future: But Yankees general manager says 'he's our shortstop' now|first=Bryan|last=Hoch|publisher=MLB.com|date=January 25, 2011|accessdate=July 10, 2012}}</ref> Though Jeter stated that he wanted to remain with the Yankees, negotiations became tense. Jeter's agent, [[Casey Close]], stated that he was \"baffled\" by the Yankees' approach to the negotiations, and Cashman, now the team's general manager, responded publicly that Jeter should test the open market to ascertain his value, which angered Jeter.<ref name=drama/> According to reports, Jeter initially sought a four-year contract worth between $23&nbsp;million and $25&nbsp;million per season.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://espn.go.com/blog/new-york/yankees/post/_/id/88649/brian-cashman-was-prepared-to-dump-derek-jeter-what-else-is-new|title=Brian Cashman wanted to dump Derek Jeter? What else is new?|first=Wallace|last=Matthews|work=ESPN New York|publisher=ESPN.com|date=August 20, 2015|accessdate=August 20, 2015}}</ref> He reached an agreement with the Yankees on a three-year contract for $51&nbsp;million with an option for a fourth year.<ref name=\"drama\">{{cite web|url=http://newyork.yankees.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20101207&content_id=16270452&vkey=news_nyy&c_id=nyy|title=Jeter drama ends with signed three-year pact|last=Hoch|first=Bryan|publisher=MLB.com|date=December 7, 2010|accessdate=December 7, 2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101208230506/http://newyork.yankees.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20101207&content_id=16270452&vkey=news_nyy&c_id=nyy|archivedate=December 8, 2010}}</ref> He spent the offseason working with Long on adjustments to his swing.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2011/01/29/sports/baseball/29jeter.html?_r=1&ref=sports|title=To Increase Production, Jeter Tries Subtracting a Step|first=Ben|last=Shpigel|newspaper=The New York Times|page=D1|date=January 28, 2011|accessdate=January 28, 2011}}</ref><ref name=\"excellence\">{{cite web|url=http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20120224&content_id=26837156&vkey=news_mlb&c_id=mlb|title=For Jeter, nothing less than excellence will do|first=Bryan|last=Hoch|publisher=MLB.com|date=February 24, 2012|accessdate=June 25, 2012}}</ref>\n\nThe adjustments left Jeter frustrated, as he batted .242 in the first month of the 2011 season.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://espn.go.com/new-york/mlb/story/_/id/7612606/new-york-yankees-derek-jeter-lot-muhammad-ali|title=Jeter may be more like Ali than he thinks: The Captain could have something other than greatness in common with the Champ|first=Wallace|last=Matthews|publisher=ESPN New York|date=March 2, 2012|accessdate=June 25, 2012}}</ref> As he struggled, it appeared that the 2011 season was the continuation of Jeter's decline.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2011/05/04/sports/baseball/04jeter.html|title=Under a Microscope, Jeter Has a Powerless Start|first=Ben|last=Shpigel|work=The New York Times|date=May 3, 2011|accessdate=July 17, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2011/05/08/weekinreview/08silver.html|title=Derek Jeter and the Curse of Age|first=Nate|last=Silver|authorlink=Nate Silver|work=The New York Times|date=May 7, 2011|accessdate=July 17, 2012}}</ref> Jeter broke [[Rickey Henderson]]'s franchise record for stolen bases when he stole his 327th base against the Mariners on May 28, 2011.<ref name=\"newyork.yankees.mlb.com\">{{cite web|title=Jeter passes Rickey as Yankees' steals leader|url=http://newyork.yankees.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20110528&content_id=19697362&notebook_id=19710538&vkey=notebook_nyy&c_id=nyy|date=May 28, 2011|accessdate=May 28, 2011|first=Bryan|last=Hoch|publisher=MLB.com|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110530010308/http://newyork.yankees.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20110528&content_id=19697362&notebook_id=19710538&vkey=notebook_nyy&c_id=nyy|archivedate=May 30, 2011}}</ref> He suffered a calf injury on June 13 that required his fifth stint on the 15-day [[disabled list]], and his first since 2003.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20110614&content_id=20465992&vkey=news_mlb&c_id=mlb|title=Yankees decide to place Jeter on DL|first=Bryan|last=Hoch|publisher=MLB.com |date=June 15, 2011|accessdate=May 24, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Costello|first=Brian|url=http://www.nypost.com/p/sports/yankees/jeter_working_way_back_slowly_t2DFeL7l6vduFpIlxFGN1K|title=Jeter working way back to Yankees&nbsp;\u2013 slowly|newspaper=New York Post|date=June 26, 2011|accessdate=July 9, 2011}}</ref> At that point, he was batting .260 for the [[2011 New York Yankees season|2011 season]] with a .649&nbsp;OPS.<ref name=\"jeter2011\">{{cite news|first=Jeff|last=Bradley|url=http://www.nj.com/yankees/index.ssf/2011/09/bradley_yankees_should_hit_der.html|title=Yankees should hit Derek Jeter leadoff through postseason|newspaper=[[The Star-Ledger]]|date=September 21, 2011|accessdate=October 7, 2011}}</ref> Rehabilitating from his injury in Tampa, Jeter worked on his swing with Denbo, his former minor league manager.<ref name=\"DL stint helped Jeter's hitting\">{{cite news|url=http://www.newsday.com/sports/baseball/yankees/dl-stint-helped-jeter-s-hitting-1.3101963|title=DL stint helped Jeter's hitting|first=Erik|last=Boland|newspaper=Newsday|date=August 16, 2011|accessdate=April 24, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://newyork.yankees.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20120423&content_id=29486890&vkey=news_nyy&c_id=nyy|title=Jeter defying all who wrote him off|publisher=MLB.com|first=Richard|last=Justice|date=April 24, 2012|accessdate=April 24, 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120504095910/http://newyork.yankees.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20120423&content_id=29486890&vkey=news_nyy&c_id=nyy|archivedate=May 4, 2012}}</ref> With Denbo, Jeter returned to the mechanics he used in his minor league days.<ref name=excellence/> Following his activation from the disabled list, he hit .326 with an .806 OPS in his last 64 games of the season.<ref name=jeter2011/> Jeter finished the year with a .297 batting average, 6 home runs, 61 runs batted in, 84 runs, and 16 stolen bases.<ref name=br/> He credited the turnaround to his work with Denbo;<ref name=\"DL stint helped Jeter's hitting\"/> Long acknowledged that his attempt to adjust Jeter's swing did not work.<ref name=excellence/>\n\n[[File:Jeter crosses home plate after 3000th CROP.jpg|thumb|250px|Jeter crosses home plate after recording his 3,000th hit in 2011, his teammates waiting to congratulate him|alt=A man in a white baseball uniform with navy pinstripes and the number \"2\" on the back of his uniform runs towards home plate, while his teammates run to meet him to celebrate.]]\nOn July 9, 2011, Jeter recorded his [[3,000 hit club|3,000th career hit]], a home run off of David Price of the Tampa Bay Rays. Jeter finished the day with five hits in five at-bats, the second player to have five hits on the day he achieved his 3,000th hit (the first was [[Craig Biggio]]).<ref>{{cite news|url=http://bostonherald.com/sports/red_sox_mlb/boston_red_sox/2011/07/jeter%E2%80%99s_heroics_mirror_biggio|title=Jeter heroics mirror Biggio|first=John|last=Tomase|newspaper=[[Boston Herald]]|date=July 10, 2011|page=10|accessdate=August 21, 2014}}</ref> He also became the second player to hit a home run for his 3,000th hit, [[Wade Boggs]] having done so in 1999. The last of Jeter's five hits proved to be the game-winning hit. He is the only member of the 3,000 hit club to record all of his hits with the New York Yankees, and the only player to join the club as a Yankee.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20110614&content_id=20463750&vkey=news_mlb&c_id=mlb|title=Derek Jeter joins elite group with 3,000th hit|publisher=MLB.com|date=July 9, 2011|accessdate=July 9, 2011}}</ref> Jeter joined [[Honus Wagner]] as only the second regular shortstop to reach the 3,000 hit plataeu.<ref name=\"nyt3000\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2011/07/10/sports/baseball/jeter-relentlessly-consistent-reaches-3000-hits-with-a-home-run.html?_r=1|title=Jeter Reaches Fabled 3,000, and It's a Blast|first=Tyler|last=Kepner|newspaper=The New York Times|page=A1|date=July 9, 2011|accessdate=July 24, 2011}}</ref><ref name=\"Matuszewski\">{{cite news |last=Matuszewski |first=Erik |title=Derek Jeter Ends Quest for 3,000 With Home Run Against Rays |date=July 10, 2011 |work=Businessweek |url=http://www.businessweek.com/news/2011-07-10/derek-jeter-ends-quest-for-3-000-with-home-run-against-rays.html |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/67xQHGnQt?url=http://www.businessweek.com/news/2011-07-10/derek-jeter-ends-quest-for-3-000-with-home-run-against-rays.html |archivedate=May 26, 2012 |url-status=dead  }}</ref>{{refn|Though Honus Wagner was primarily a shortstop, he also played other infield positions as well as the outfield. [[Cal Ripken, Jr.]] reached 3,000 after he had moved to third base. [[Robin Yount]] reached the milestone after moving to center field, where he spent almost half his career.<ref name=Matuszewski/><ref name=Shapiro>{{cite news |last=Shapiro |first=Ben |title=Derek Jeter, on the verge of 3,000 hits, is the greatest shortstop in major league history |date=June 7, 2011 |publisher=masslive.com |url=http://www.masslive.com/sports/index.ssf/2011/06/derek_jeter_greatest_shortstop_of_all_time.html |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/67xRF5Q1f?url=http://www.masslive.com/sports/index.ssf/2011/06/derek_jeter_greatest_shortstop_of_all_time.html |archivedate=May 26, 2012 |url-status=dead  }}</ref> Some consider Jeter the third regular shortstop to reach 3,000 along with Wagner and Ripken.<ref name=Shapiro/><ref>{{cite news |last=Anderson |first=Dave |title=A Yankees Footnote to Jeter's Quest for 3,000 |date=June 27, 2011 |newspaper=The New York Times |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2011/06/28/sports/baseball/dave-anderson-yankees-footnote-to-jeters-quest-for-3000.html |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/67xRLWQOE?url=http://www.nytimes.com/2011/06/28/sports/baseball/dave-anderson-yankees-footnote-to-jeters-quest-for-3000.html?_r=1 |archivedate=May 26, 2012 |url-status=dead }}</ref>|group=lower-alpha}} Only [[Ty Cobb]], [[Hank Aaron]], and [[Robin Yount]] were younger than Jeter on the day of their 3,000th hit.<ref name=nyt3000/> MLB and [[HBO]] produced ''Derek Jeter 3K'', a documentary that profiled his path to 3,000 hits and originally aired on July 28, 2011.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20110728&content_id=22421472&vkey=news_mlb&c_id=mlb|title=Jeter's HBO special premieres: Unique inside access gives new insight on Yankees' captain|first=Mark|last=Newman|date=July 28, 2011|accessdate=August 19, 2011|publisher=MLB.com}}</ref>\n\nFatigued from the stress of chasing 3,000 career hits and wanting to rest his calf, Jeter opted not to attend the [[2011 MLB All-Star Game]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.newsday.com/sports/baseball/yankees/jeter-to-skip-all-star-game-1.3013374|title=Jeter to skip All-Star Game|date=July 8, 2011|first=Barbara|last=Barker|newspaper=Newsday|accessdate=July 12, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Marchand |first=Andrew |title=Derek Jeter clarifies All-Star absence |date=July 15, 2011 |publisher=ESPN.com |url=http://espn.go.com/new-york/mlb/story/_/id/6770218/new-york-yankees-derek-jeter-explains-decision-skip-all-star-game-festivities |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/698GjeLHY?url=http://espn.go.com/new-york/mlb/story/_/id/6770218/new-york-yankees-derek-jeter-explains-decision-skip-all-star-game-festivities |archivedate=July 13, 2012 |url-status=live  }}</ref> Jeter and Posada played their 1,660th game together on July 14, 2011, breaking the previous franchise record of 1,659 by Gehrig and [[Tony Lazzeri]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20110714&content_id=21785778&notebook_id=21803042&vkey=notebook_nyy&c_id=nyy|last=Gonzalez|first=Alden|title=Jeter, Posada set appearance record|publisher=MLB.com|date=July 14, 2011|accessdate=July 14, 2011}}</ref> Jeter played his 2,402nd game with the Yankees on August 29, 2011, breaking [[Mickey Mantle]]'s record for most [[games played]] as a Yankee.<ref>{{cite web|title=Jeter adds games played to his Yanks records|url=http://newyork.yankees.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20110828&content_id=23856358&notebook_id=23857254&vkey=notebook_nyy&c_id=nyy|date=August 29, 2011|accessdate=August 29, 2011|first=Bryan|last=Hoch|publisher=MLB.com|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121008032804/http://newyork.yankees.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20110828&content_id=23856358&notebook_id=23857254&vkey=notebook_nyy&c_id=nyy|archivedate=October 8, 2012}}</ref> He finished the 2011 season with 162 hits, his 16th consecutive season with 150 hits, which tied him with [[Pete Rose]] for the second-most consecutive 150-hit seasons, one behind [[Hank Aaron]] for the MLB record.<ref>{{cite news|last=Marchand|first=Andrew|url=http://espn.go.com/blog/new-york/yankees/post/_/id/23560/page/RapidReaction/rapid-reaction-mariners-2-yankees-1-12-innings|title=Rapid Reaction: Mariners 2, Yankees 1 (12)|publisher=ESPN New York|date=September 15, 2010|accessdate=October 7, 2011}}</ref> Jeter was honored with the [[Lou Gehrig Memorial Award]], given in recognition of charitable endeavors.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20120118&content_id=26386450&vkey=news_mlb&c_id=mlb|title=Jeter honored with Lou Gehrig Memorial Award|first=Adam|last=Berry|publisher=MLB.com|date=January 18, 2012|accessdate=April 10, 2012}}</ref>\n\nDespite continuing concerns about his age, the beginning of the [[2012 New York Yankees season|2012 season]] saw Jeter on a hot streak: he batted .411 through April 23.<ref name=\"turned back the clock\">{{cite news|url=http://www.nj.com/yankees/index.ssf/2012/04/how_the_yankees_derek_jeter_ha.html|title=How the Yankees' Derek Jeter has turned back the clock|date=April 24, 2012|first=Marc|last=Carig|newspaper=The Star-Ledger|accessdate=April 27, 2012}}</ref> Rodriguez commented that Jeter is playing as he did in 1999, while Girardi said Jeter looks like he is 25 years old.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://news.yahoo.com/jeter-gets-4-hits-yankees-7-4-win-031812206--mlb.html |date=April 23, 2012 |title=Jeter gets 4 hits for Yankees in 7\u20134 win at Texas |first=Stephen |last=Hawkins |agency=Associated Press |publisher=Yahoo! Inc |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/685Lr8Koj?url=http://news.yahoo.com/jeter-gets-4-hits-yankees-7-4-win-031812206--mlb.html |archivedate=June 1, 2012 |url-status=dead  }}</ref> In the [[2012 MLB All-Star Game]], Jeter recorded his eleventh All-Star hit, passing Mantle for the most All-Star Game hits in Yankees history.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://espn.go.com/blog/new-york/yankees/post/_/id/39545/jeter-passes-mantle|title=Jeter passes Mantle|date=July 10, 2012|first=Andrew|last=Marchand |publisher=ESPN New York|accessdate=July 12, 2012}}</ref> Jeter went 1-for-2 in the game, moving into fourth all-time with a .458 average among players with a minimum of 12 plate appearances in the All-Star Game.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.freep.com/article/20120711/SPORTS02/207110427/Back-in-game-Derek-Jeter-new-york-yankees-all-star-game|title= Back in game, Derek Jeter rises on star chart|first=Jayson|last=Jenks|work=[[Detroit Free Press]]|date=July 11, 2012|accessdate=July 12, 2012}}</ref>\n\nJeter finished the 2012 season with the most hits in MLB (216).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/leagues/MLB/2012-batting-leaders.shtml|title=2012 Major League Baseball Batting Leaders|publisher=Baseball-Reference.com|accessdate=October 14, 2012}}</ref> Against the Tampa Bay Rays on September 14 of that year, he moved into the Top 10 on the all-time hit list, surpassing [[Willie Mays]] by beating out an infield single for his 3,284th career hit.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://sports.yahoo.com/news/price-rays-beat-yankees-stay-024536661--mlb.html |title=Price, Rays beat Yankees, stay close in AL East |publisher=[[Yahoo! Sports]] |date=September 15, 2012 |accessdate=August 21, 2014}}</ref> After hitting .364 in the [[2012 American League Division Series|2012 ALDS]], Jeter fractured his left ankle during Game 1 of the [[2012 American League Championship Series|2012 ALCS]] against the [[Detroit Tigers]] reaching for a ground ball, an injury which ended his season.<ref>{{cite web|last=King|first=George|title=Jeter breaks ankle, Yankees fall in 12 after miracle four-run comeback|url=http://www.nypost.com/p/sports/yankees/jeter_carried_comeback_field_yankees_aC9Wez9zVwl2jwNM4rNMJM|work=The New York Post|accessdate=October 14, 2012}}</ref> Jeter had received a [[cortisone]] shot to treat a bone bruise in his left foot in September, which could have contributed to the break. Jeter had surgery on his broken left ankle on October 20, with an expected recovery time of four to five months.<ref>{{cite web|title=Derek Jeter To Have Surgery on Ankle; Will Likely Need 4 To 5 Months To Recover|url=http://newyork.cbslocal.com/2012/10/17/derek-jeter-to-have-surgery-on-ankle-will-likely-need-4-to-5-months-to-recover/|publisher=CBS News New York|accessdate=October 17, 2012}}</ref>\n\nWhile rehabilitating, Jeter suffered a small crack in the area of his previous ankle fracture. As a result, Jeter began the 2013 season on the disabled list.<ref>{{cite web|title=Derek Jeter out until after All-Star break|url=http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20130418&content_id=45146236|publisher=MLB.com|accessdate=April 18, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Derek Jeter has new ankle fracture, report says |url=http://www.myfoxny.com/story/22017261/derek-jeter-has-new-ankle-fracture-report-says |publisher=MyFoxNY |accessdate=April 18, 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130420082827/http://www.myfoxny.com/story/22017261/derek-jeter-has-new-ankle-fracture-report-says |archivedate=April 20, 2013 }}</ref> The Yankees activated Jeter on July 11,<ref>{{cite web|title=Derek Jeter to return to Yankees on Thursday|url=http://www.newsday.com/sports/baseball/yankees/derek-jeter-to-return-to-yankees-on-thursday-1.5665944?qr=1|publisher=Newsday|accessdate=July 11, 2013}}</ref> but after playing in one game, Jeter returned to the disabled list with a [[quadriceps]] strain.<ref>{{cite web|last=Snyder |first=Matt |url=http://www.cbssports.com/mlb/blog/eye-on-baseball/22817958/yankees-place-derek-jeter-on-disabled-list |title=Yankees place Derek Jeter on disabled list |publisher=CBSSports.com |date=July 19, 2013 |accessdate=July 19, 2013}}</ref> He returned to the Yankees lineup on July 28, hitting a home run on the first pitch off of [[Matt Moore (baseball)|Matt Moore]] of Tampa Bay.<ref>{{cite web|title=Jeter Returns To Yankees Lineup, Ends Team's HR Dry Spell |url=http://www.ny1.com/content/sports/sports_news/186220/jeter-returns-to-yankees-lineup--ends-team-s-hr-dry-spell |publisher=ny1 |accessdate=July 28, 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131005021056/http://www.ny1.com/content/sports/sports_news/186220/jeter-returns-to-yankees-lineup--ends-team-s-hr-dry-spell |archivedate=October 5, 2013 }}</ref> Jeter was again placed on the 15-day disabled list on August 5 due to a Grade 1 [[Calf (anatomy)|calf]] [[Strain (injury)|strain]], and after a brief return to the lineup, he was placed on the 15-day disabled list for a third time on September 11 due to problems with his ankle, ending his season.<ref>{{cite web|title=Derek Jeter placed on Disabled List for injured ankle essentially ending season |url=http://abclocal.go.com/wabc/story?section=news/sports/pro/baseball&id=9244582 |publisher=WABC TV |accessdate=September 11, 2013 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130913020035/http://abclocal.go.com/wabc/story?section=news%2Fsports%2Fpro%2Fbaseball&id=9244582 |archivedate=September 13, 2013 |url-status=dead }}</ref> On September 14, 2013 Jeter was transferred to the 60-day disabled list.<ref>{{cite web|title=Phelps reinstated from DL to bolster bullpen|url=http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20130914&content_id=60567644&notebook_id=60567652&vkey=notebook_nyy&c_id=nyy|publisher=MLB.com|date=September 14, 2013}}</ref> Jeter batted .190 in only 17 games played during the 2013 season.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/sports/mlb/yankees/2013/09/11/derek-jeter-yankees-injury-season-over/2801329/|title=Derek Jeter's season over|work=USA Today|date=September 11, 2013|accessdate=September 11, 2013}}</ref>\n\n====Final season (2014)====\n[[File:Derek Jeter Fan (14462795718).jpg|right|thumb|A fan holding a sign honoring Jeter during his final season|alt=A woman with brown hair wearing a navy blue hat and navy blue shirt holds a sign to her right with the word \"DEREK\" at the top left, the word \"JETER\" at the bottom right, and a navy blue circle with navy blue vertical stripes and the number 2 inside it in the center.]]\nJeter re-signed with the Yankees on a one-year, $12&nbsp;million contract for the 2014 season.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://newyork.yankees.mlb.com/news/article/nyy/yankees-re-sign-jeter-for-one-year-12-million?ymd=20131101&content_id=63611710 |title=Yankees re-sign Jeter for one-year, $12&nbsp;million |last=Nowak |first=Joey |publisher=MLB.com |access-date=December 28, 2013}}</ref> Jeter announced on his [[Facebook]] page on February 12, 2014, that the [[2014 New York Yankees season|2014 season]] would be his last.<ref name=\"retirement\">{{cite web|url=http://espn.go.com/new-york/mlb/story/_/id/10444978/derek-jeter-says-2014-last-season-via-facebook-post |publisher=ESPN New York|title=Derek Jeter says '14 will be last year|date=February 12, 2014|accessdate=February 12, 2014}}</ref> During his final season, each opposing team honored Jeter with a gift during his final visit to their city, which has included donations to Jeter's charity, the [[Turn 2 Foundation]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nj.com/yankees/index.ssf/2014/05/look_derek_jeters_farewell_tour_gifts.html|title=Derek Jeter's farewell tour gifts|first=Brendan|last=Kuty|work=NJ.com|date=May 15, 2014|accessdate=July 14, 2014}}</ref>\n\nOn July 10, Jeter recorded his 1,000th career multi-hit game, becoming the fourth player to do so.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gammonsdaily.com/derek-jeter-now-has-1000-regular-season-multi-hit-games/|title=Derek Jeter now has 1000 regular season multi-hit games|date=July 11, 2014 |first=Bill |last=Chuck|work=Daily Gammons|publisher=Trumedia Networks|accessdate=August 6, 2014}}</ref> He was elected to start at shortstop in the [[2014 Major League Baseball All-Star Game|2014 All-Star Game]], and batted leadoff for the AL.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nj.com/yankees/index.ssf/2014/07/2014_mlb_all-star_game_yankees_derek_jeter_will_bat_leadoff_in_final_appearance.html|title=2014 MLB All-Star Game: Yankees' Derek Jeter will bat leadoff in final appearance|first=Brendan|last=Kuty|work=NJ.com|date=July 14, 2014|accessdate=July 14, 2014}}</ref> Jeter went 2 for 2, scored one run and received two standing ovations in the four innings he played at the 2014 All-Star Game.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://newyork.cbslocal.com/2014/07/15/derek-jeter-scores-1-run-receives-2-standing-ovations-in-all-star-game/ |title=Derek Jeter Scores 1 Run, Receives 2 Standing Ovations in All-Star Game |date=July 15, 2014 |website=CBS - New York |access-date=July 16, 2014}}</ref> As a result, Jeter's .481 career All-Star batting average (13 for 27) ranked him fifth all-time (among players with at least 10 at-bats). At 40, Jeter also became the oldest player to have two or more hits in an All-Star Game.<ref name=\"Hoch MLB\">{{cite web|last1=Hoch|first1=Bryan|title=Jeter goes out in style to fitting All-Star farewell|url=http://kansascity.royals.mlb.com/news/article/mlb/derek-jeter-goes-out-in-style-to-fitting-all-star-game-farewell?ymd=20140715&content_id=84832774&vkey=news_mlb|website=MLB.com|publisher=MLB Advanced Media, LP|date=July 15, 2014|accessdate=July 16, 2014}}\n</ref> In July, Jeter broke [[Omar Vizquel]]'s MLB career record of 2,609 games started at [[shortstop]], and Gehrig's franchise career record of 534 doubles.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article/mlb/derek-jeter-atop-yankees-all-time-doubles-list-with-no-535?content_id=85802252|title=Jeter atop Yanks' doubles list with No. 535: Captain passes Gehrig with ninth-inning drive down left-field line off Cotts|first=Jake|last=Kring-Schreifels|work=MLB.com |date=July 23, 2014}}</ref> On July 17, Derek scored the 1,900th run of his career becoming the 10th player in MLB history to do so.<ref>{{cite web|author=|url=http://www.gammonsdaily.com/stats-report-derek-jeter-scores-his-1900th-career-run/ |title=Stats report: Derek Jeter scores his 1900th career run |publisher=GammonsDaily.com |date=June 18, 2014 |accessdate=August 21, 2014}}</ref> Jeter passed [[Carl Yastrzemski]] for seventh place on MLB's all-time career hit list on July 28<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nj.com/yankees/index.ssf/2014/07/yankees_derek_jeter_passes_red_soxs_carl_yastrzemski_on_all-time_hits_list.html|title=Yankees' Derek Jeter passes Red Sox's Carl Yastrzemski on all-time hits list|first=Brendan|last=Kuty|work=NJ.com|date=July 28, 2014|accessdate=August 6, 2014}}</ref> and on August 11 he passed [[Honus Wagner]] climbing to sixth on the all-time hits list.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://espn.go.com/blog/new-york/yankees/post/_/id/78968/jeters-hit-that-tied-wagner-ruled-an-error |title=Jeter's 'hit' that tied Wagner ruled an error Jeter's 'hit' that tied Wagner ruled an error|date=August 19, 2014|first=Andrew |last=Marchand | work=ESPNNewYork.com|accessdate=September 5, 2014}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Jeter in 2014 All Star Game.jpg|thumb|upright=0.75|Jeter saluting the crowd during his final All Star Game appearance in the 2014 All Star Game]]\nThe Yankees honored Jeter with a pregame tribute on September 7.<ref name=\"honor\">{{cite web|url=http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20140718&content_id=85129604&notebook_id=85130102&vkey=notebook_nyy&c_id=nyy|title=Yanks to honor Jeter's career on Sept. 7|first1=Bryan |last1=Hoch |first2=Jamal|last2=Collier |work=MLB.com |date=July 18, 2014|accessdate=August 6, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Marchand|first1=Andrew|title=Derek Jeter honored, thanks fans|url=http://espn.go.com/new-york/mlb/story/_/id/11482918/derek-jeter-honored-new-york-yankees|publisher=ESPN New York|accessdate=September 7, 2014}}</ref> Beginning with that day's game, the Yankees wore a patch on their hats and uniforms honoring Jeter for the remainder of the season.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/2014-09-02/yankees-to-celebrate-jeter-with-uniform-patch-for-final-22-games.html|title=Yankees to Celebrate Jeter With Uniform Patch for Final 22 Games|first=Eben|last=Novy-Williams|work=Bloomberg|date=September 2, 2014|accessdate=September 5, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nj.com/yankees/index.ssf/2014/09/yankees_will_wear_derek_jeter_patch.html|title=Yankees will wear Derek Jeter patch|first=Brendan|last=Kuty |work=NJ.com|date=September 2, 2014|accessdate=September 5, 2014}}</ref> In the final week of Jeter's career, MLB Commissioner [[Bud Selig]] honored him as the 15th recipient of the [[Commissioner's Historic Achievement Award]] for being \"one of the most accomplished shortstops of all-time\".<ref>{{cite press release|url=http://m.mlb.com/news/article/96046376/derek-jeter-honored-with-commissioners-historic-achievement-award|title=Derek Jeter honored with Commissioner's Historic Achievement Award|publisher=Major League Baseball|date=September 23, 2014|accessdate=September 24, 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171031104859/http://m.mlb.com/news/article/96046376/derek-jeter-honored-with-commissioners-historic-achievement-award/|archivedate=October 31, 2017}}</ref>\n\nDuring Jeter's final [[series (baseball)|series]] at Yankee Stadium, [[Louisville Slugger]] announced they would retire their \"P72\" model [[baseball bat]], the bat Jeter uses, though it will be sold under the name \"DJ2\", in Jeter's honor.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://m.yankees.mlb.com/news/article/96195366/louisville-slugger174-retires-p72-bat-model-in-honor-of-derek-jeter|title=Louisville Slugger\u00ae retires P72 bat model in honor of Derek Jeter|publisher=Major League Baseball|date=September 24, 2014|accessdate=September 27, 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140929065148/http://m.yankees.mlb.com/news/article/96195366/louisville-slugger174-retires-p72-bat-model-in-honor-of-derek-jeter|archivedate=September 29, 2014}}</ref> The average ticket price for Jeter's final home game, on September 25, reached $830 on the [[secondary market]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/09/26/nyregion/a-shortstop-and-the-creator-of-the-jeter-superfan.html?_r=0|title=As Era Ends, Derek Jeter's Fans Fill the Seats, No Matter the Cost|first=Alan|last=Feuer|work=The New York Times|date=September 25, 2014|accessdate=September 26, 2014}}</ref> In his final game at Yankee Stadium, Jeter hit a [[Walk-off hit|walk-off]] single against [[2014 Baltimore Orioles season|Orioles]] pitcher [[Evan Meek]] to win the game, 6\u20135.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Araton|first1=Harvey|title=Of All His Numbers, the One on Jeter's Back Matters Most|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/09/26/sports/baseball/feeling-the-impact-of-derek-jeters-numbers-especially-the-one-on-his-back.html|work=The New York Times|accessdate=September 25, 2014|date=September 25, 2014}}</ref>\n\nJeter decided to play exclusively as the [[designated hitter]] in the final series of his career, at [[Fenway Park]] in Boston, so that his final memories of playing shortstop would be at Yankee Stadium.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/sports/mlb/2014/09/25/derek-jeter-final-home-game-game-winning-rbi/16242129/|title=Derek Jeter's unbelievable closing act at Yankee Stadium|first=Bob|last=Nightengale|work=USA Today|date=September 26, 2014|accessdate=September 26, 2014}}</ref> The Red Sox honored Jeter with a pregame ceremony including Red Sox retired stars [[Carl Yastrzemski]], [[Jim Rice]], [[Fred Lynn]], [[Luis Tiant]] and [[Rico Petrocelli]], the [[Boston Bruins]]' [[Bobby Orr]], [[New England Patriots]] receiver [[Troy Brown]] and the [[Boston Celtics]]' [[Paul Pierce]], while many Boston fans at Fenway Park loudly cheered for Jeter and gave him a standing ovation.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nydailynews.com/sports/baseball/yankees/jeter-career-ends-infield-hit-boston-red-sox-salute-retiring-yankee-captain-article-1.1955842 |title=Boston legends Bobby Orr and Carl Yastrzemski headline Red Sox salute Derek Jeter |last=Rubin |first=Roger |date=September 29, 2014 |website=New York Daily News |access-date=July 22, 2019}}</ref> In his final at-bat, he hit an RBI infield single against [[Clay Buchholz]], before being substituted for pinch runner [[Brian McCann (baseball)|Brian McCann]];<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/09/29/sports/baseball/derek-jeter-plays-final-game-at-a-friendly-fenway-park.html|title=In Enemy Territory, a Farewell Comes With a Warm Embrace|first=Tyler|last=Kepner|work=The New York Times|date=September 28, 2014|accessdate=July 3, 2016}}</ref> he received an ovation from the Red Sox fans as he exited the field.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cbssports.com/mlb/news/video-derek-jeter-exits-to-ovation-after-hitting-single-in-final-at-bat/|title=Video: Derek Jeter exits to ovation after hitting single in final at-bat|first=Mike|last=Axisa|publisher=CBS Sports|date=September 28, 2014|accessdate=July 3, 2016}}</ref>\n\n===World Baseball Classic===\nJeter started at shortstop for the [[United States national baseball team]] in the [[2006 World Baseball Classic]]. He hit 9-for-20 (.450) and scored five runs in six games. Only teammate [[Ken Griffey, Jr.]] (.524) and [[Cuba national baseball team|Cuba's]] [[Yoandy Garlobo]] (.480) had a higher batting average with a minimum of 20 at-bats.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.worldbaseballclassic.com/2006/stats/stats.jsp?t=l_bat&lid=160|archive-url=https://wayback.archive-it.org/all/20120216013709/http://www.worldbaseballclassic.com/2006/stats/stats.jsp?t=l_bat&lid=160|url-status=dead|archive-date=February 16, 2012|title=World Baseball Classic Statistics \u2013 2006|date=March 21, 2006|accessdate=March 21, 2006|publisher=[[World Baseball Classic]]}}</ref> Jeter's play earned him recognition as the shortstop selection on the All-Tournament Team.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/mlb/worldclassic2006/news/story?id=2377725|title=World Baseball Classic All-Tournament Team|agency=Associated Press|date=March 21, 2006|accessdate=March 21, 2006}}</ref>\n\nIn the [[2009 World Baseball Classic]], Jeter again started at shortstop. He was named captain of the United States team by manager [[Davey Johnson]],<ref>{{cite news|url=http://bats.blogs.nytimes.com/2009/03/03/rivals-suit-up-for-team-usa-jeter-faces-yankees/|title=Rivals Suit Up for Team USA; Jeter Faces Yankees|first=Joe|last=LaPointe|date=March 3, 2009|accessdate=March 3, 2009|newspaper=The New York Times Baseball Blog}}</ref> and he batted 8-for-29 (.276) in eight games.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://web.worldbaseballclassic.com/stats/index.jsp?team=wbc|archive-url=https://wayback.archive-it.org/all/20120215235346/http://web.worldbaseballclassic.com/stats/index.jsp?team=wbc|url-status=dead|archive-date=February 15, 2012|title=World Baseball Classic Statistics \u2013 2009|accessdate=May 24, 2012|publisher=World Baseball Classic}}</ref> Jeter and the United States team faced the Yankees at [[Steinbrenner Field]] in an exhibition game, the only time Jeter played against the Yankees.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/sports/baseball/yankees/derek-jeter-kos-yankees-trange-uniform-world-baseball-classic-article-1.366002|title=Derek Jeter KOs Yankees in 'strange' uniform for World Baseball Classic|first=Anthony|last=McCarron|newspaper=New York Daily News|date=March 3, 2009|accessdate=October 8, 2009}}</ref>\n\n==Player profile==\n[[File:Derek Jeter outside of Baltimore hotel in 2014. .jpg|alt=Jeter signing autographs.|thumb|upright|Jeter signing autographs in Baltimore prior to his final game at Camden Yards]]\nJeter is considered to be one of the most consistent baseball players of all time.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/waynemcdonnell/2012/08/31/baseball-is-a-game-of-adjustments-and-derek-jeter-has-mastered-the-art/|title=Baseball is a Game of Adjustments and Derek Jeter has Mastered the Art|last=McDonnell, Jr.|first=Wayne G.|publisher=Forbes|date=August 31, 2012|accessdate=October 12, 2013}}</ref> He played fewer than 145 games a season only three times in his career: when he dislocated his left shoulder on Opening Day 2003 (119 games), when he injured his calf in 2011 (131 games), and in 2013 when he struggled with a myriad of injuries (17 games).<ref name=br/> For his career, he averaged 204 [[hit (baseball)|hits]], 113 [[runs scored]] and 21 [[stolen bases]] per 162 games.<ref name=\"br\"/> He is currently 6th on the all-time hits list in MLB history.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/leaders/H_career.shtml |title=Career Leaders &amp Records for Hits |publisher=Baseball-Reference.com |date=January 1, 2009 |accessdate=August 21, 2014}}</ref> Highly competitive, Jeter once said, \"If you're going to play at all, you're out to win. Baseball, [[board game]]s, playing ''[[Jeopardy!]]'', I hate to lose.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.recordonline.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/20061122/SPORTS/611220350|title=Jeter don't care 'bout stinkin' metal|first=Michael P.|last=Geffner|work=[[Times Herald-Record]]|date=November 22, 2006|accessdate=April 18, 2012}}</ref> Jeter has been viewed as one of the best players of his generation.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20090909&content_id=6882850&vkey=news_nyy&fext=.jsp&c_id=nyy|title=Jeter's feat recognized around MLB: Players, coaches respect what shortstop has done for game|first1=John|last1=Schlegel|last2=Bollinger|first2=Rhett|publisher=MLB.com|date=September 12, 2009|accessdate=October 14, 2009}}</ref>\n\n{{quote box|quote=\"Derek Jeter has always been above the fray. As someone who's wallowed in it, 'foot-in-mouthed' it hundreds of times, said dumb things and backed up dumber ones, it's refreshing. He's shown up, played, and turned in a first-ballot Hall of Fame career in the hardest environment in sports to do any/all of the above.\"|source= \u2014[[Curt Schilling]], September 14, 2009<ref name=schilling>{{cite web|url=http://38pitches.wordpress.com/2009/09/14/congratulations-derek-jeter/|title=Congratulations, Derek Jeter|last=Schilling|first=Curt|publisher=38pitches.com|date=September 14, 2009|accessdate=September 15, 2009}}</ref>|width = 25%|align = right}}\nAn aggressive hitter, Jeter swung at most pitches in the strike zone and many near it.<ref name=olney2004/> Though right-handed hitters often pull the ball into left field, Jeter's signature inside-out swing, dubbed the \"Jeterian Swing\",<ref>{{cite news|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/newyork/mlb/news/story?id=6654029|title=Derek Jeter pulls within 7 hits of 3,000|first=Mike|last=Mazzeo|publisher=ESPNNewYork.com|date=June 13, 2011|accessdate=October 25, 2011}}</ref> resulted in most of his hits going to center and right field. Similarly, most of his home runs were hit to right field rather than to center or to left, as his swing took advantage of Yankee Stadium's close right-field fences.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2011/06/15/sports/baseball/jeter-3000-hits.html|title=Derek Jeter Joins an Exclusive Club|first1=Shan|last1=Carter|first2=Kevin|last2=Quealy|first3=Joe|last3=Ward|newspaper=The New York Times|date=July 9, 2011|accessdate=July 10, 2011}}</ref>\n\nJeter is also known for his professionalism. In an age where professional athletes often find themselves in personal scandals, he mostly avoided major controversy in a high-profile career in New York City while maintaining a strong work ethic.<ref name=60minutes/><ref name=\"gq\">{{cite journal|url=https://www.gq.com/sports/profiles/201104/derek-jeter-seth-mnookin|title=Derek Jeter's Swinging Years|journal=[[GQ]]|authorlink=Seth Mnookin|first=Seth|last=Mnookin|issue=April 2011|accessdate=October 31, 2011}}</ref><ref name=\"kurkjian\">{{cite news|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/mlb/columns/story?columnist=kurkjian_tim&id=2073780|title=There's Jeter&nbsp;... and then everyone else|publisher=ESPN.com|first=Tim|last=Kurkjian|authorlink=Tim Kurkjian|date=June 2, 2005|accessdate=July 13, 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.nesn.com/2009/09/love-him-or-hate-him-derek-jeter-is-the-pride-of-professional-sports.html|title=Love Him or Hate Him, Derek Jeter Is the Pride of Professional Sports|date=September 10, 2009|accessdate=October 31, 2011|publisher=[[New England Sports Network]]|first=Eric|last=Ortiz}}</ref> Due to his style of play, opponents and teammates held him in high esteem.<ref name=schilling/><ref name=kurkjian/> A clubhouse leader, Jeter often defused confrontations between teammates.<ref name=kurkjian/>\n\n===Postseason performance===\nJeter is noted for his postseason performances and has earned the titles of \"Captain [[Clutch hitter|Clutch]]\", and \"Mr. November\" due to his outstanding postseason play.<ref name=\"sportsillustrated\">{{cite news|url=http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/2006/writers/tom_verducci/10/04/yankee.doodle.dandy/|title=Jeter displays his postseason form|first=Tom|last=Verducci|work=[[Sports Illustrated]]|date=October 4, 2006|accessdate=May 22, 2011|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20061116162820/http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/2006/writers/tom_verducci/10/04/yankee.doodle.dandy/|archivedate=November 16, 2006}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://mlb.mlb.com/stats/individual_player_postseason.jsp?playerID=116539|title=Derek Jeter Stats, Bio, Photos, Highlights|publisher=[[MLB.com]]|accessdate=March 8, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.usatoday.com/sports/columnist/zillgitt/2003-10-22-zillgitt_x.htm|title=Jeter turns on jets in time for postseason push|first=Jeff|last=Zillgitt|newspaper=USA Today|date=October 22, 2003|accessdate=May 22, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|first=Bill|last=Eichenberger|url=http://aol.sportingnews.com/mlb/story/2009-10-07/fitting-jeter-s-hr-christened-new-stadium-s-playoff-debut|title=Fitting that Jeter's HR christened new Stadium's playoff debut|work=Sporting News|date=October 8, 2009|accessdate=May 22, 2011}}</ref> He had a career .309 postseason batting average, and a .321 batting average in the World Series. Except for 2008, 2013 and 2014, the Yankees qualified for the postseason every year of Jeter's major league career. He holds MLB postseason records for [[games played]] (158), [[plate appearance]]s (734), at-bats (650), hits (200), singles (143), doubles (32), triples (5), runs scored (111), total bases (302) and strikeouts (135). Jeter is also third in home runs (20), fourth in runs batted in (61), fifth in base on balls (66) and sixth in stolen bases (18).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/postseason/Playoffs_batting.shtml|title=All-time and Single-Season Postseason Batting Leaders|publisher=Baseball-Reference.com|accessdate=June 27, 2012}}</ref>\n\n===Defense===\n[[File:Derek Jeter pregame ground balls 2011.jpg|thumb|left|Jeter practices fielding in August 2011|alt=A man in a blue baseball uniform with \"New York\" written on the front in grey letters and a navy hat with white letters \"N\" and \"Y\" interlocking prepares to catch a ground ball with his baseball glove.]]\nJeter won five [[Gold Glove Award]]s, trailing only Vizquel, [[Ozzie Smith]], [[Luis Aparicio]], [[Dave Concepci\u00f3n]], and [[Mark Belanger]] for most by a shortstop.<ref>{{cite web|title=Multiple Winners of the Gold Glove Award|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/awards/gold_glove_nl.shtml#multi|work=Baseball-Reference.com|accessdate=June 25, 2013}}</ref> He was credited with positioning himself well and for a quick release when he threw the ball.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/2009/writers/joe_posnanski/08/19/jeter/index.html |title=Derek Jeter underrated? Yankee icon great in a tangible way |first=Joe |last=Posnanski |date=August 19, 2009 |work=Sports Illustrated |accessdate=June 23, 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090919005754/http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/2009/writers/joe_posnanski/08/19/jeter/index.html |archivedate=September 19, 2009 }}</ref> One of his signature defensive plays is the \"jump-throw\", by which he leapt and threw to first base while moving towards third base.<ref name=\"signature\">{{cite news|url=https://www.usatoday.com/sports/baseball/al/yankees/2011-06-12-2001-derek-jeter-3000-hits_N.htm|title=Jeter's signature moments make him next Yankee icon|first=Seth|last=Livingstone|newspaper=USA Today|date=June 12, 2011|accessdate=June 25, 2012}}</ref>\n\nDespite this, Jeter's defense was the subject of criticism from a number of [[sabermetrics|sabermetricians]], including [[Rob Neyer]] and the publication ''[[Baseball Prospectus]]''.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Jensen|first1=Shane T.|first2=Kenny|last2=Shirley|first3=Abraham|last3=Wyner|title=SAFE: Spatial Aggregate Fielding Evaluation|url=http://stat.wharton.upenn.edu/~stjensen/research/safe.html|publisher=[[Wharton School of the University of Pennsylvania]]|accessdate=March 3, 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://static.espn.go.com/mlb/columns/neyer_rob/1415713.html|title=From the archives: Assessing Jeter's defense|first=Rob|last=Neyer|authorlink=Rob Neyer|date=February 7, 2001|publisher=ESPN.com|accessdate=March 5, 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.baseballprospectus.com/article.php?articleid=98|title=A Subjective Look at Defense|first=Gary|last=Huckabay|date=April 13, 1998|work=[[Baseball Prospectus]]|accessdate=December 14, 2008}}</ref> The 2006 book ''The Fielding Bible'' by John Dewan contains an essay by [[Bill James]] in which he concluded that Jeter \"was probably the most ineffective defensive player in the major leagues, at any position\" over his entire career.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=NB9Bhi6mOgAC&pg=PA149&lpg=PA149&dq=Jeter+%22was+probably+the+most+ineffective+defensive+player+in+the+major+leagues,+at+any+position.#v=onepage&q=Jeter%20%22was%20probably%20the%20most%20ineffective%20defensive%20player%20in%20the%20major%20leagues%2C%20at%20any%20position.&f=false|title=Wizardry: Baseball's All-Time Greatest Fielders Revealed|first=Michael A.|last=Humphreys|page=149|publisher=Oxford University Press|year=2011|isbn=978-0-19-539776-5|accessdate=November 23, 2011}}</ref> A 2008 study by researchers at the [[University of Pennsylvania]] found that, from 2002 through 2005, Jeter was the worst defensive shortstop in MLB.<ref>{{cite news|last=Mazor|first=John|title=You've Got To Be Kidding!|newspaper=New York Post|date=February 17, 2008|url=http://www.nypost.com/p/news/national/you_ve_got_to_be_kidding_WSNDnFR2MfZJ6R2jwUZK3L|accessdate=May 15, 2008}}</ref> Two sites that rely on advanced defensive statistics, [[FanGraphs.com]] and [[FieldingBible.com]], rated Jeter below middle-of-the-pack status in 2010, despite his receiving his fifth Gold Glove Award that season.<ref>{{cite news|title=AL Gold Glove winners named |url=http://sports.espn.go.com/mlb/news/story?id=5784846 |work=ESPN.com |agency=Associated Press |date=November 11, 2010 |accessdate=November 10, 2010 |quote=Two websites that study glovework&nbsp;\u2013 Fangraphs.com with its [[Ultimate Zone Rating]] and Fieldingbible.com&nbsp;\u2013 listed Chicago's [[Alexei Ram\u00edrez]] as the top-fielding AL shortstop with Jeter nowhere close to even middle-of-the-pack status. |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131110014341/http://sports.espn.go.com/mlb/news/story?id=5784846 |archivedate=November 10, 2013  }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Gleeman |first=Aaron |title=Derek Jeter now has more Gold Glove awards than all but four shortstops in baseball history |url=http://hardballtalk.nbcsports.com/2010/11/09/derek-jeter-now-has-more-gold-glove-awards-than-all-but-four-shortstops-in-baseball-history/ |publisher=[[NBC Sports]] |date=November 9, 2010 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5u9QH1oLg?url=http://hardballtalk.nbcsports.com/2010/11/09/derek-jeter-now-has-more-gold-glove-awards-than-all-but-four-shortstops-in-baseball-history/ |archivedate=November 11, 2010 |accessdate=November 10, 2010 |quote=And that's fine, but the notion that Jeter, at age 36, was the best defensive shortstop in the American League this season is simply absurd, whether you love defensive statistics, hate defensive statistics, or merely prefer the Ultimate Warrior to Ultimate Zone Rating. |url-status=dead  }}</ref>\n\nJeter committed 18 errors in 2007, his highest total since finishing with 24 in 2000.<ref name=frias/> After the season, Cashman and his staff saw Jeter's defense as an area that needed to be addressed.<ref name=hoch/> At the Yankees' request, Jeter embarked on a rigorous training program to combat the effects of age, by focusing on lateral movement and first-step quickness.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://msn.foxsports.com/mlb/story/How-will-Cubs%2C-Mets-GMs-turn-things-around%3F |title=How will Cubs, Mets GMs Turn Things Around? |last=Rosenthal |first=Ken |publisher=Fox Sports |date=August 25, 2009 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5uI5SGasJ?url=http://msn.foxsports.com/mlb/story/How-will-Cubs%2C-Mets-GMs-turn-things-around%3F |archivedate=November 16, 2010 |accessdate=November 16, 2010 |url-status=dead  }}{{cbignore}}</ref> Jeter's [[ultimate zone rating]] (UZR) improved from worst in the AL for shortstops in 2007 to close to league average in 2008.<ref name=\"hoch\">{{cite web |url=http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20090727&content_id=6094262&vkey=news_nyy&fext=.jsp&c_id=nyy&partnerId=rss_nyy |title=Jeter making long strides at shortstop |last=Hoch |first=Bryan |publisher=MLB.com |date=July 28, 2009 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5uI75F4kn?url=http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20090727&content_id=6094262&vkey=news_nyy&fext=.jsp&c_id=nyy&partnerId=rss_nyy |archivedate=November 16, 2010 |accessdate=November 16, 2010 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nWhen asked to respond to criticism of his defense, Jeter replied: \"I play in New York, man. Criticism is part of the game, you take criticism as a challenge.\"<ref name=\"frias\">{{cite news |url=http://www.palmbeachpost.com/sports/content/sports/epaper/2008/03/30/a8c_basejeter_0330.html |title=Criticism of his defense isn't about to make Jeter change plans |newspaper=[[Palm Beach Post]] |last=Frias |first=Carlos |date=March 30, 2008 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5uI7VcSyT?url=http://www.palmbeachpost.com/sports/content/sports/epaper/2008/03/30/a8c_basejeter_0330.html |archivedate=November 16, 2010 |accessdate=November 16, 2010 |url-status=dead  }}</ref> Jeter further asserted that many defensive factors cannot be quantified.<ref name=kepner/> The controversy over Jeter's fielding became a flash point for the debate over whether the analyses of statistics or subjective observation is the better method to assess a player's defensive ability and for criticism of the Gold Glove Award.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.slate.com/articles/sports/sports_nut/2008/07/derek_jeter_vs_objective_reality.html|title=Derek Jeter vs. Objective Reality|work=Slate|last=DiMeo|first=Nate|date=July 14, 2008|accessdate=July 27, 2011}}</ref>\n{{Clear}}\n\n==Personal life==\nJeter maintains homes in [[Marlboro Township, New Jersey]]; [[Greenwood Lake, New York]];<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.recordonline.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/20071007/NEWS/710070343/-1/NEWS|title=Fun facts about our region|newspaper=[[Times Herald-Record]]|last=Israel|first=Steve|date=October 7, 2007|accessdate=July 18, 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Inside Derek Jeter's $14.75 million castle in upstate NY |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2018/06/29/photos-derek-jeter-selling-upstate-new-york-castle-.html |publisher=CNBC |last=Im |first=Jimmy |date=June 29, 2018 |accessdate=June 29, 2018}}</ref> and the [[Davis Islands, Tampa, Florida|Davis Islands]] neighborhood of [[Tampa, Florida]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www2.tbo.com/sports/breaking-news-sports/2009/jul/15/derek-jeters-mansion-will-easily-be-tampas-biggest-ar-96638/|title=Derek Jeter's mansion will easily be Tampa's biggest home|last=Mullins|first=Richard|newspaper=[[The Tampa Tribune]]|date=July 15, 2009|accessdate=July 18, 2009}}</ref> He previously owned a penthouse apartment in Manhattan's [[Trump World Tower]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/life-style/real-estate/jeter-sells-trump-world-tower-home-15-5m-article-1.1179642|title=Derek Jeter sells Trump World Tower home for $15.5&nbsp;million|work=New York Daily News|first1=Gina|last1=Pace|first2=Jason|last2=Sheftell|date=October 10, 2012|accessdate=October 11, 2012}}</ref> Jeter settled a tax dispute regarding his official residence with the [[New York State Department of Taxation and Finance]] in 2008.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/mlb/news/story?id=3231419|title=Report: Jeter settles tax dispute with New York state|work=ESPN.com|agency=Associated Press|date=February 5, 2008|accessdate=February 5, 2008}}</ref> New York State alleged that Jeter should have paid state [[income tax]] from 2001 to 2003, as Jeter resided in the Manhattan apartment he bought in 2001; Jeter claimed to have established his residence in Tampa, Florida, in 1994 and that he was still a resident of Florida at the time. Florida has no state income tax.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/sports/baseball/yankees/taxman-derek-jeter-cheated-york-millions-article-1.259813|title=Taxman: Derek Jeter cheated New York out of millions|newspaper=New York Daily News|last1=Zambito|first1=Thomas|last2=Connor|first2=Tracy|date=November 16, 2007|accessdate=May 15, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.foxnews.com/story/0,2933,311830,00.html|title=New York Tax Officials: Yankees Star Derek Jeter Is No Floridian|publisher=Fox News|date=November 16, 2007|accessdate=July 11, 2009|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090625154429/http://www.foxnews.com/story/0,2933,311830,00.html|archive-date=June 25, 2009|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nIn December 2002, Yankees owner George Steinbrenner criticized Jeter for staying out until 3 a.m. at a birthday party during the 2002 season, saying that his star shortstop \"wasn't totally focused\" and that \"it didn't sit well\" with him.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/archives/news/boss-riding-jeter-joe-big-guys-gotta-produce-yankees-owner-warns-article-1.504180|title=Big guys gotta produce, Yankees owner warns: Boss Riding Jeter & Joe|first=Bill|last=Hutchinson|date=December 29, 2002|newspaper=New York Daily News|accessdate=August 21, 2014}}</ref> The two mocked the incident in a May 2003 [[VISA]] commercial,<ref name=\"jeter is back\"/> similar to the manner in which Steinbrenner and former Yankees manager [[Billy Martin]] made light of their feud in a [[Miller Lite]] commercial during the 1970s.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://money.cnn.com/2003/05/05/news/companies/visa_steinbrenner_jeter/|title=Visa ends Steinbrenner-Jeter feud|publisher=[[CNNMoney]]|date=May 6, 2003|accessdate=July 23, 2009}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Derek Jeter 2007 in Baltimore.jpg|thumb|upright|left|Jeter in 2007|alt=Derek Jeter wearing a navy hat and grey baseball uniform with a black glove stares into the distance.]]\nJeter's personal life has been a frequent topic in gossip columns and celebrity magazines since his rookie year in 1996. He had a well-publicized relationship with singer [[Mariah Carey]] from 1997 to 1998.<ref name=espnclassic/><ref name=page3/> Jeter has also dated model [[Vida Guerra]], former [[Miss Universe]] [[Lara Dutta]],<ref name=espnclassic/><ref>{{cite journal|url=http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/vault/article/magazine/MAG1020985/2/index.htm |title=The Toast of the Town |journal=Sports Illustrated |last=Verducci |first=Tom |authorlink=Tom Verducci |date=November 6, 2000 |volume=93 |issue=19 |accessdate=July 18, 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091109150858/http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/vault/article/magazine/MAG1020985/2/index.htm |archivedate=November 9, 2009 }}</ref> singer [[Joy Enriquez]],<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/archives/news/jeter-sweeter-a-rod-ex-date-yankee-star-article-1.938187|title=Jeter Sweeter A-Rod says OK as ex-date is seen with Yankee star|newspaper=New York Daily News|last1=Gillies|first1=Bob|last2=Gittrich|first2=Greg|last3=Garin|first3=Kristoffer|date=August 19, 2001|accessdate=August 21, 2014}}</ref> television personality [[Vanessa Minnillo]],<ref name=\"page3\">{{cite web|url=http://proxy.espn.go.com/espn/page3/story?page=mcintyre/jeter|title=Derek Jeter: All-Star ladies' man|last=McIntyre|first=Jason|date=February 14, 2005|accessdate=September 16, 2008|publisher=ESPN.com|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090214114635/http://proxy.espn.go.com/espn/page3/story?page=mcintyre%2Fjeter|archivedate=February 14, 2009}}</ref> and the actresses [[Jordana Brewster]],<ref name=espnclassic/><ref>{{cite journal|url=http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/vault/article/magazine/MAG1026234/index.htm |title=Sports Beat |journal=Sports Illustrated |date=July 15, 2002 |volume=97 |issue=3 |accessdate=July 18, 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100108050133/http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/vault/article/magazine/MAG1026234/index.htm |archivedate=January 8, 2010 }}</ref> [[Jessica Biel]],<ref>{{cite news|url=http://blog.sfgate.com/dailydish/2006/11/16/biel-dating-jeter/|title=Biel Dating Jeter?|date=November 16, 2006|accessdate=November 16, 2006|work=San Francisco Chronicle|first=Karen|last=Reardanz}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/espn/page2/story?page=jeter/women&lpos=spotlight&lid=tab5pos1|title=The Women of Derek Jeter|date=November 18, 2006|accessdate=October 4, 2009|publisher=ESPN.com}}</ref> and [[Minka Kelly]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/vault/article/web/COM1147484/4/index.htm |title=Derek Jeter talks Minka Kelly (sort of) |work=Sports Illustrated |date=October 28, 2008 |accessdate=July 18, 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090924030820/http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/vault/article/web/COM1147484/4/index.htm |archivedate=September 24, 2009 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/sports/baseball/yankees/derek-jeter-father-dr-charles-jeter-girlfriend-actress-minka-kelly-support-jeter-suite-article-1.156638|title=Derek Jeter's father, Dr. Charles Jeter, girlfriend and actress Minka Kelly support Jeter from suite|first=Kristie|last=Ackert|newspaper=New York Daily News|date=July 10, 2011|accessdate=July 15, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Saad|first=Nardine|title=Minka Kelly and Derek Jeter have 'amicable' breakup|url=http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/gossip/2011/08/derek-jeter-minka-kelly-breakup-split-yankees-charlies-angels.html|accessdate=August 26, 2011|newspaper=Los Angeles Times|date=August 26, 2011}}</ref>\n\nJeter and model [[Hannah Jeter|Hannah Davis]], who had been dating since 2012, became engaged in 2015.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.si.com/swim-daily/2015/11/03/derek-jeter-hannah-davis-engaged-players-tribune-article-confirms|title=It's Official: Hannah Davis and Derek Jeter are engaged!|first=Kelsey|last=Hendrix|work=Sports Illustrated|date=November 3, 2015|accessdate=November 3, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/sports/baseball/yankees/derek-jeter-confirms-engagement-hannah-davis-article-1.2422173|title=Derek Jeter confirms engagement to Hannah Davis as Yankees legend posts story \u2013 about his dog|first=Amara|last=Grautski|work=New York Daily News|date=November 3, 2015|accessdate=November 3, 2015}}</ref> In July 2016, the two married.<ref>{{cite web|last=Kruth|first=Cash|title=Jeter marries longtime girlfriend Davis|publisher=Major League Baseball|date=July 10, 2016|url=http://m.yankees.mlb.com/news/article/189048076/derek-jeter-marries-hannah-davis/|accessdate=July 10, 2016}}</ref> On February 13, 2017, Hannah announced that she was pregnant with a daughter.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/mlb/story/_/id/18676664/derek-jeter-wife-hannah-jeter-announce-couple-expecting-first-child|title=Derek Jeter, wife Hannah expecting their first child|work=ESPN.com|date=February 13, 2017|accessdate=February 13, 2017}}</ref> Their first child was born in August 2017.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.today.com/parents/new-york-yankees-legend-derek-jeter-his-wife-hannah-welcome-t115280|title=New York Yankees legend Derek Jeter and his wife, Hannah, welcome 1st child|last=Vivinetto|first=Gina|work=TODAY.com|accessdate=August 18, 2017}}</ref> Their second daughter was born in January 2019.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://people.com/parents/derek-jeter-hannah-jeter-welcome-daughter-story-grey/|title=A New Rookie! Derek Jeter and Wife Hannah Welcome Daughter Story Grey|work=People|first=Deirdre|last=Durkan|date=January 31, 2019|accessdate=February 1, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Business interests==\nDuring his injury-shortened 2013 season, Jeter arranged a partnership with [[Simon & Schuster]] to form an [[imprint (trade name)|imprint]] called Jeter Publishing. He called it \"the blueprint for postcareer\". It will begin publishing nonfiction books for adults, children's picture books, elementary grade fiction, and books for children who are learning to read.  Eventually, the partnership could lead to film and television productions.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2013/11/15/sports/baseball/next-chapter-in-jeters-career-book-publishing.html?_r=0|title=Jeter Prepares to Turn a Page and Publish Many Others|first=Julie|last=Bosman|newspaper=The New York Times|date=November 14, 2013|accessdate=November 16, 2013}}</ref>\n\nOn October 1, 2014, Jeter's new website, [[The Players' Tribune|ThePlayersTribune.com]], appeared online;<ref>{{cite web|title=Derek Jeter gets back to work|publisher=ESPN|date=October 2, 2014|url=http://espn.go.com/new-york/mlb/story/_/id/11621489/derek-jeter-launches-website-connect-athletes-fans|accessdate=July 10, 2016}}</ref> it was billed as \"a new media platform that will present the unfiltered voice of professional athletes, bringing fans closer to the games they love than ever before\".<ref>{{cite web|last=McClellan|first=Preston|title=What Derek Jeter's 'The Players' Tribune' means for sports media|publisher=Sporting News|date=October 20, 2014|url=http://www.sportingnews.com/mlb/news/derek-jeter-the-players-tribune-sports-media/1nj76c6wnfxxd1kpf9gnbpqx2z|accessdate=July 10, 2016}}</ref> It was reported by the Tampa Bay Business Journal in March 2015 that Jeter had partnered with Concessions Tampa to bid for a space within the Tampa International Airport, and plans to open a restaurant named after his website.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Sandomir|first1=Richard|title=For Derek Jeter, Retirement Is a Job|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/04/06/sports/baseball/for-derek-jeter-retirement-is-a-job.html?ref=sports&_r=0|accessdate=April 7, 2015|work=New York Times|date=April 5, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Snider|first1=Eric|title=Derek Jeter bids for restaurant slot in TIA concessions|url=http://www.bizjournals.com/tampabay/news/2015/03/26/derek-jeter-bids-for-restaurant-slot-in-tia.html?page=all|accessdate=April 7, 2015|work=Tampa Bay Business Journal|date=March 26, 2015}}</ref>\n\nJeter also serves as a brand development officer for [[Luvo Inc.]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/sports/baseball/yankees/derek-jeter-spends-day-promoting-healthy-eating-luvo-food-truck-article-1.1875019|title=Derek Jeter promotes healthy eating at Luvo food truck in Columbus Circle |first=Christian|last=Red|work=New York Daily News|date=July 21, 2014|accessdate=August 6, 2015}}</ref> and has investment interests in multi-channel video network company, [[Whistle Sports Network]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Peyton Manning helps fund Whistle Sports, called ESPN for Millennials|url=http://www.denverpost.com/business/ci_27311773/peyton-manning-ponies-up-whistle-sports-video-network|website=[[Denver Post]]|accessdate=January 14, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Multi-channel video network Whistle Sports grabs $28M from Peyton Manning, Derek Jeter, & others|url=https://venturebeat.com/2015/01/13/whistle-sports/|website=[[VentureBeat]]|accessdate=January 14, 2015}}</ref> He explored purchasing the [[Buffalo Bills]] football team in 2014.<ref>{{cite news|last=Graham|first=Tim|title=Derek Jeter reached on-deck circle while examining Bills purchase, sources say|work=The Buffalo News|date=February 4, 2015|url=http://bills.buffalonews.com/2015/02/04/derek-jeter-reached-deck-circle-examining-bills-purchase-sources-say/|accessdate=July 10, 2016|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160811085223/http://bills.buffalonews.com/2015/02/04/derek-jeter-reached-deck-circle-examining-bills-purchase-sources-say/|archivedate=August 11, 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Miami Marlins===\nIn July 2017, Jeter engaged in the bidding for ownership of the [[Miami Marlins]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Gasparino|first1=Charlie|title=Derek Jeter turns to Michael Dell firm to keep Marlins bid alive|url=http://www.foxbusiness.com/features/2017/07/28/derek-jeter-turns-to-michael-dell-firm-to-keep-marlins-bid-alive.html|website=FoxBusiness.com|accessdate=August 8, 2017|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170808193904/http://www.foxbusiness.com/features/2017/07/28/derek-jeter-turns-to-michael-dell-firm-to-keep-marlins-bid-alive.html|archivedate=August 8, 2017}}</ref> In August 2017, Jeter and [[Bruce Sherman]] finalized a deal to purchase the Miami Marlins. The sale was completed in September 2017, following unanimous approval of the other 29 MLB team owners. Though Jeter only owns a 4% stake in the franchise, he was named [[chief executive officer]] of the team, and controlling owner Bruce Sherman entrusted him to oversee day-to-day operations of the team.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.miamiherald.com/sports/mlb/miami-marlins/article175684166.html/|title=MLB owners approve sale of Marlins to Derek Jeter and Bruce Sherman|first=Barry|last=Jackson|work=[[Miami Herald]]|publisher=Miami Herald|date=September 27, 2017|accessdate=November 20, 2017|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171002124749/http://www.miamiherald.com/sports/mlb/miami-marlins/article175684166.html|archivedate=October 2, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Appearances outside of baseball==\n[[File:JeterSmilingt.JPG|thumb|right|180px|Jeter joking with other players during Spring training in 2007|alt=A man in a navy helmet and navy windbreaker smiles while talking to someone dressed in the same uniform who is turned away from the camera.]]\n\n===Philanthropy===\nJeter created the [[Turn 2 Foundation]], a charitable organization, in 1996. It was established to help children and teenagers avoid [[drug addiction|drug]] and [[alcoholism|alcohol addiction]], and to reward those who show high academic achievement.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://derekjeter.mlb.com/players/jeter_derek/turn2/index.jsp|title=Turn 2 Foundation Mission Statement|accessdate=September 11, 2008|publisher=MLB.com}}</ref> In 2012, Jeter received an [[honorary doctorate]] from [[Siena College]] honoring him for his foundation's work.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://whtc.com/news/articles/2012/may/14/call-him-dr-jeter/|title=Derek Jeter receives honorary doctorate|date=May 14, 2012|publisher=WHTC|accessdate=May 14, 2012}}</ref>\n\nJeter also serves as an ambassador for [[Weplay]], a website designed to encourage children to get involved in sports.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20090331&content_id=4094260&vkey=news_mlb&fext=.jsp&c_id=mlb|title=Jeter an ambassador for youth sports: Yankees captain's 'Weplay' site spurs kids to athletic lifestyle|last=Gonzalez|first=Alden|publisher=MLB.com|date=March 31, 2009|accessdate=September 25, 2009}}</ref>\n\n===Endorsements===\nJeter has appeared in national ad campaigns for [[Nike, Inc.|Nike]], [[Gatorade]],<ref>{{cite web|last1=Suddath|first1=Claire|title=Gatorade Says Goodbye to Derek Jeter|url=http://www.businessweek.com/articles/2014-09-19/gatorade-says-goodbye-to-derek-jeter|publisher=Bloomberg Businessweek|accessdate=September 20, 2014}}</ref> [[FleetBoston Financial|Fleet Bank]], [[Ford Motor Company|Ford]], VISA,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://content.usatoday.com/communities/dailypitch/post/2011/03/josh-hamilton-behind-yanks-derek-jeter-mariano-rivera-as-most-marketable/1#.T-sGxbVrOH8|date=March 24, 2011|title=Josh Hamilton trails only Derek Jeter, Mariano Rivera as most marketable|first=Seth|last=Livingstone|newspaper=USA Today|accessdate=June 27, 2012}}</ref> [[Discover Card]],<ref>{{cite news|url=http://money.cnn.com/2003/05/05/news/companies/visa_steinbrenner_jeter/|title=Visa ends Steinbrenner-Jeter feud: Yankees' owner and star player whom he earlier criticized will appear in Visa ad together|date=May 6, 2003|publisher=[[CNN Money]]|accessdate=June 27, 2012}}</ref> [[Florsheim Shoe|Florsheim]],<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/archives/news/champs-field-big-bucks-endorsements-article-1.840729|title=Champs To Field Big Bucks in Endorsements|first=Judith|last=Schoolman|newspaper=New York Daily News|date=October 29, 1999|accessdate=June 27, 2012}}</ref> [[Gillette (brand)|Gillette]], [[Skippy (peanut butter)|Skippy]],<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2000/04/03/business/media-business-advertising-bestfoods-introduces-new-products-enlists-derek-jeter.html|title=The Media Business: Advertising; Bestfoods introduces new products and enlists Derek Jeter's help on the peanut butter front|first=Constance L.|last=Hays|newspaper=The New York Times|date=April 3, 2000|accessdate=June 27, 2012}}</ref> and [[XM Satellite Radio]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.nbcnews.com/id/11386154|title=Growing pains for satellite radio: Despite rapid acceptance, financial losses continue to mount|first=John W.|last=Schoen|publisher=[[NBC News]]|date=February 16, 2006|accessdate=June 27, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1999/04/10/sports/sports-of-the-times-jordan-adds-a-shortstop-to-his-team.html|title=Sports of The Times; Jordan Adds A Shortstop To His Team|first=William C.|last=Rhoden|newspaper=The New York Times|date=April 10, 1999|accessdate=July 18, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.nypost.com/p/news/business/ad_rod_on_deck_RHb0t8bMffIBhL5B4rR04N|title=Ad-Rod on deck: 2nd chance for Yankee bad boy|first=Holly|last=Sanders Ware|date=November 6, 2009|newspaper=New York Post|accessdate=July 18, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bizofbaseball.com/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=2317&Itemid=42|title=Derek Jeter Joins \"Gillette Champions\" Ad Campaign|publisher=The Biz of Baseball|first=Maury|last=Brown|date=June 30, 2008|accessdate=July 18, 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110930070322/http://www.bizofbaseball.com/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=2317&Itemid=42|archivedate=September 30, 2011}}</ref> He endorses a cologne named ''Driven'', designed in collaboration with and distributed by [[Avon Products, Inc.|Avon]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/mlb/news/story?id=2536111|title=Jeter cologne not for those who think Yankees stink|agency=Associated Press|work=ESPN.com|date=August 1, 2006|accessdate=August 1, 2006}}</ref> Jeter has his own [[Jumpman (logo)|Jumpman]] shoe.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/archives/sports/jeter-joins-jet-set-shoe-biz-article-1.584362|title=Jeter Joins Jet Set of Shoe Biz|first=Christian|last=Red|newspaper=New York Daily News|date=July 8, 2004|accessdate=August 21, 2014}}</ref> To commemorate Jeter's final year, the Jordan brand made a tribute commercial titled \"#RE2PECT\", which had many baseball players (such as [[Jon Lester]]) and celebrities, even rival Boston Red Sox fans tip their caps.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Mandell|first1=Nina|title=The Derek Jeter commercial everyone will be talking about at the All-Star Game|url=http://ftw.usatoday.com/2014/07/carmelo-anthony-jay-z-derek-jeter-jordan-ad|work=USA Today|accessdate=July 24, 2014|date=July 14, 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn 2006, Jeter was the second-highest paid endorser in baseball, behind [[Ichiro Suzuki]], who received endorsement deals in Japan.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.forbes.com/lists/2006/53/9O99.html|title=Derek Jeter, The Top 100 Celebrities|accessdate=September 8, 2008|year=2007|work=Forbes}}</ref> He was ranked as the most marketable player in baseball according to the 2003, 2005, and 2010 Sports Business Surveys.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20050406&content_id=1001571&vkey=news_nyy&fext=.jsp&c_id=nyy|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071013142414/http://mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20050406&content_id=1001571&vkey=news_nyy&fext=.jsp&c_id=nyy|url-status=dead|archive-date=October 13, 2007|title=Sports Business Daily-Most Marketable players in MLB|accessdate=September 8, 2008|last=Feinsand|first=Mark|date=April 6, 2005|publisher=MLB.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.sportsbusinessdaily.com/Daily/Issues/2010/07/Issue-211/Sponsorships-Advertising-Marketing/Derek-Jeter-Again-Tops-The-Dailys-Most-Marketable-In-MLB-Survey.aspx|title=Derek Jeter Again Tops The Daily's Most Marketable in MLB Survey|first1=Bryan|last1=Helfrich|first2=Erik|last2=Swanson|work=Sports Business Daily|date=July 20, 2010|accessdate=July 20, 2010}}</ref> A 2011 list by the marketing firm [[Nielsen Company|Nielsen]] ranked Jeter as the most marketable player in baseball, accounting for personal attributes such as sincerity, approachability, experience, and influence.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blog.nielsen.com/nielsenwire/consumer/pinstripe-power-jeter-rivera-top-10-most-marketable-players-in-baseball/|title=Pinstripe Power: Jeter, Rivera Top List of 10 Most Marketable Players in Baseball|publisher=[[Nielsen Company]]|date=March 24, 2011|accessdate=March 28, 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110420003319/http://blog.nielsen.com/nielsenwire/consumer/pinstripe-power-jeter-rivera-top-10-most-marketable-players-in-baseball/|archive-date=April 20, 2011|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n===Other appearances===\nJeter has appeared on television as a guest actor in the sitcom ''[[Seinfeld]]'' in the episode titled, \"[[The Abstinence]]\" and ''[[Saturday Night Live]]'', a late-night [[live television]] [[sketch comedy]] and [[variety show]], in episode 7 during [[Saturday Night Live (season 27)|season 27]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mlb.mlb.com/news/print.jsp?ymd=20091113&content_id=7662674|title='Aging' Jeter playing himself in upcoming flick: Yankees' captain gets role in film starring Ferrell, Wahlberg|first=Bryan|last=Hoch|publisher=MLB.com|date=November 13, 2009|accessdate=November 19, 2011}}</ref> He had [[cameo appearance]]s in the comedy films ''[[Anger Management (film)|Anger Management]]'' and ''[[The Other Guys]]''.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.nypost.com/p/news/local/brooklyn/jeter_plays_bronx_bummer_for_movie_3qdPn6QooUGivifiCf7MFN#ixzz0Wm0wNcUC|title=Jeter plays a Bronx bummer for movie|first1=Rich|last1=Calder|last2=Alpert|first2=Lukas I.|newspaper=New York Post|date=November 13, 2009|accessdate=November 13, 2009}}</ref> Jeter was the subject of a 2005 segment on the TV news magazine ''[[60 Minutes]]''<ref name=\"60minutes\">{{cite news|url=http://www.cbsnews.com/stories/2005/09/22/60minutes/main880059.shtml|title=Derek Jeter: The Captain|last=Bradley|first=Ed|date=September 25, 2005|accessdate=September 25, 2005|publisher=[[CBS News]]|authorlink=Ed Bradley}}</ref> and a 2014 episode of ''[[Finding Your Roots]]'', a [[Public Broadcasting Service]] (PBS) [[public television|public]] [[television series]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Born Champions Derek Jeter|url=https://www.pbs.org/wnet/finding-your-roots/profiles/derek-jeter/|website=[[Finding Your Roots|Finding Your Roots with Henry Louis Gates, Jr.]]|publisher=[[WNET|THIRTEEN]] Productions LLC|accessdate=September 28, 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141002100457/http://www.pbs.org/wnet/finding-your-roots/profiles/derek-jeter/|archivedate=October 2, 2014}}</ref> Jeter also appears as a character in the [[Broadway theatre|Broadway]] play ''[[Bronx Bombers (play)|Bronx Bombers]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://artsbeat.blogs.nytimes.com/2013/10/21/a-broadway-run-for-bronx-bombers/?_php=true&_type=blogs&_r=0|series=ArtsBeat Blog|work=The New York Times|date=October 21, 2013|title=A Broadway Run for 'Bronx Bombers'|first=Adam W. |last=Kepler|accessdate=February 6, 2014}}</ref> Jeter made an appearance alongside [[Peyton Manning]] to celebrate [[Saturday Night Live 40th Anniversary Special|''Saturday Night Live'''s 40th Anniversary]] in February 2015.<ref>{{cite web|title = WATCH: Peyton Manning, Derek Jeter introduce 'SNL 40' sports clip mashup|url = http://www.cbssports.com/nfl/eye-on-football/25070449/watch-peyton-manning-derek-jeter-introduce-snl-40-sports-clip-mashup|website = CBSSports.com|access-date = January 26, 2016}}</ref>\n\nVideo games have featured Jeter on their cover, including [[2K Sports]]' ''MLB 2K5'', ''[[Major League Baseball 2K6|MLB 2K6]]'', and ''[[MLB 2K7]]'',<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.businesswire.com/news/home/20051206005388/en/2K-Sports-Announces-Major-League-Baseball-2K6|date=December 6, 2005|title=2K Sports Announces Major League Baseball 2K6&nbsp;\u2013 The Exclusive 2006 Multi-Platform Baseball Title; New York Yankee All-Star Derek Jeter to Again Grace Cover|publisher=Business Wire|accessdate=April 10, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.gameindustry.com/ih/item.asp?id=1138|title=Derek Jeter is 2K7 Cover Athlete|publisher=Game Industry News|date=January 12, 2007|accessdate=April 10, 2012|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130809051636/http://www.gameindustry.com/ih/item.asp?id=1138|archivedate=August 9, 2013}}</ref> [[Acclaim Entertainment]]'s ''[[All-Star Baseball]]'' series of video games,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.gamespot.com/articles/yankees-star-signs-with-acclaim/1100-2452465/|title=Yankees Star Signs With Acclaim|last=Mullen|first=Michael|date=January 6, 1999|publisher=GameSpot|accessdate=April 29, 2014}}</ref> and [[Gameloft]]'s [[mobile gaming|wireless phone]] baseball game, ''[[Derek Jeter Pro Baseball 2008]]''.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.sys-con.com/node/513772|title=Gameloft Continues Winning Streak With Release of Derek Jeter Pro Baseball 2008|date=March 6, 2008|accessdate=April 10, 2012|publisher=Sys-Con}}</ref> A [[wax figure]] immortalizes Jeter at the [[Madame Tussauds]] Wax Museum in New York,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.madametussauds.com/NewYork/OurFigures/SportsStars/DerekJeter/Default.aspx|title=Derek Jeter's wax figure at Madame Tussauds description page|publisher=[[Merlin Entertainments Group|Merlin Entertainments]]|accessdate=October 18, 2009}}</ref> and a sculpture at the [[Louisville Slugger Museum & Factory]] in [[Louisville, Kentucky]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20111012&content_id=25622972&vkey=news_mlb&c_id=mlb|title=Jeter honored at Louisville Slugger Museum|first=Bryan|last=Hoch|publisher=MLB.com|date=October 12, 2011|accessdate=October 17, 2011}}</ref>\n\n==Career highlights==\n===Honors===\n{{MLBBioRet\n|Image  = DerekJeter2.jpg\n|Name   = Derek Jeter\n|Number = 2\n|Team   = New York Yankees\n|Year   = 2017\n|}}\nKalamazoo Central High School inducted Jeter into its athletic hall of fame in 2003<ref name=\"Mack\">{{cite news|url=http://blog.mlive.com/kzgazette/2007/12/kalamazoo_central_names_jeter.html|title=Kalamazoo Central names Jeter to its hall of fame|last=Mack|first=Julie|newspaper=[[Kalamazoo Gazette]]|date=December 5, 2007|accessdate=July 13, 2009}}</ref> and renamed its baseball field in his honor in 2011.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.mlive.com/news/kalamazoo/index.ssf/2011/11/kalamazoo_central_names_baseba.html|title=Kalamazoo Central names baseball field after Derek Jeter|date=November 11, 2011|accessdate=November 11, 2011|first=Julie|last=Mack|newspaper=Kalamazoo Gazette}}</ref> In 2015, Jeter was inducted into the [[New Jersey Hall of Fame]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Kuperinsky|first=Amy|title=N.J. Hall of Fame 2015: Jon Stewart, Frank Lautenberg, Derek Jeter among inductees|newspaper=[[The Newark Star Ledger]]|date=June 26, 2015|url=http://www.nj.com/entertainment/index.ssf/2015/06/new_jersey_hall_of_fame_class_of_2015_inductees.html|accessdate=August 21, 2015}}</ref> The Yankees retired Jeter's uniform number and unveiled a plaque in his honor that was installed at [[Monument Park (Yankee Stadium)|Monument Park]] in a pregame ceremony on May 14, 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/early-lead/wp/2017/05/14/family-is-forever-derek-jeters-number-retired-at-yankee-stadium/|title=\u2018Family is forever\u2019: Derek Jeter\u2019s number retired at Yankee Stadium|first=Scott|last=Allen|work=The Washington Post|date=May 14, 2017|accessdate=January 21, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn January 21, 2020, Jeter was elected to the [[National Baseball Hall of Fame and Museum|Baseball Hall of Fame]] as part of its [[2020 Baseball Hall of Fame balloting|class of 2020]] in his first year of eligibility, only one vote shy of being only the second unanimous selection in Hall of Fame history.<ref>{{cite web|last=Pickman |first=Ben |url=https://www.si.com/mlb/2020/01/21/baseball-hall-of-fame-derek-jeter-larry-walker-inducted |title=Derek Jeter, Larry Walker voted into 2020 MLB Hall of Fame class - Sports Illustrated |publisher=Si.com |date=January 16, 2020 |accessdate=January 21, 2020}}</ref> His 99.7% of the vote was second only to [[Mariano Rivera]] (100%), and ahead of Ken Griffey (99.3%) in the history of Hall of Fame voting.<ref>https://www.cbssports.com/mlb/news/baseball-hall-of-fame-derek-jeter-says-a-vote-that-kept-him-from-being-unanimous-pick-wont-bother-him/</ref>\n\n===Awards===\n[[File:Jeter receives 2009 World Series Champion ring.jpg|thumb|upright|Jeter receives his [[2009 World Series]] [[World Series ring|Championship ring]]|alt=A man in a white baseball uniform with navy pinstripes raises his right arm in the air while holding a box in his left hand.]]\n[[File:Derek Jeter pregame warmups 2011.jpg|thumb|right|upright|Jeter warming up before a game in 2011|alt=A man in a navy windbreaker and navy hat prepares to catch a baseball.]]\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"width:74%;\" center;\"\n|-\n!style=\"background:#ccf;\"|Award / Honor\n!style=\"background:#ccf;\"|Time(s)\n!style=\"background:#ccf;\"|Date(s)\n|-\n|AL [[Major League Baseball All-Star Game|All-Star]]<ref name=jeterbio/>\n|14\n|[[1998 Major League Baseball All-Star Game|1998]], [[1999 Major League Baseball All-Star Game|1999]], [[2000 Major League Baseball All-Star Game|2000]], [[2001 Major League Baseball All-Star Game|2001]], [[2002 Major League Baseball All-Star Game|2002]], [[2004 Major League Baseball All-Star Game|2004]], [[2006 Major League Baseball All-Star Game|2006]], [[2007 Major League Baseball All-Star Game|2007]], [[2008 Major League Baseball All-Star Game|2008]], [[2009 Major League Baseball All-Star Game|2009]], [[2010 Major League Baseball All-Star G