{"title_page": "Suspension of the 2019\u201320 NBA season", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date = March 2020}}\n\n[[File:Rudy Gobert 2015 (cropped).jpg|thumb|right|upright=0.90|[[Rudy Gobert]] was the first NBA player to test positive for COVID-19]]\nOn March 11, 2020, the [[National Basketball Association]] (NBA) announced the suspension of the [[2019\u201320 NBA season|2019\u201320 season]] following [[Utah Jazz]] center [[Rudy Gobert]] testing positive for the [[coronavirus disease 2019]], also known as COVID-19. Gobert had come down with an illness before a scheduled basketball game against the [[Oklahoma City Thunder]] that day at [[Chesapeake Energy Arena]] in [[Oklahoma City]]. He was not at the arena but instead at the team's hotel, and was later taken to a nearby hospital where he tested positive for the coronavirus. The next day, Gobert's teammate [[Donovan Mitchell]] also tested positive for the virus.\n\n==Background==\n{{main|2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United States|2020 coronavirus pandemic in Canada|l2=Canada}}\nThe NBA had been tracking [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|the coronavirus pandemic]] closely, speaking with public health authorities such as the [[Centers for Disease Control and Prevention|Center for Disease Control]] (CDC) on the matter.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite web|first1=Mark|last1=Medina|first2=Jeff|last2=Zillgitt|title=Coronavirus: NBA moving toward banning fans, but still no decision on how to handle games|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/sports/nba/2020/03/11/coronavirus-nba-plan-games-fans/5023870002/|website=USA Today|date=March 11, 2020|accessdate=March 12, 2020}}</ref> The league spoke to the [[National Basketball Players Association|players' union]] on the prospect of playing games without fans. The league held a conference call on March 11, 2020 between [[Adam Silver|Commissioner Adam Silver]] and the 30 owners to reach a consensus on the matter.<ref>{{cite web|first1=Adrian|last1=Wojnarowski|first2=Zach|last2=Lowe|title=Sources: NBA, owners to plot coronavirus plans|url=https://www.espn.com/nba/story/_/id/28872514/sources-nba-books-wednesday-conference-call-discuss-coronavirus-strategy-owners|website=ESPN.com|date=March 9, 2020|accessdate=March 12, 2020}}</ref> They were envisioning a scenario where games were to be played with essential personnel only and no fans in attendance, following suit with the [[National Collegiate Athletic Association|NCAA]].<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nThe NBA's first material measures included limiting locker room access to players, coaches, general managers, and basketball and public relations staff, with the notable exclusion of media. The NBA had told teams they should make plans for the possibility of playing games without fans and with only essential personnel in attendance.<ref>{{cite web|first=Joseph|last=Zucker|title=NBA Will Reportedly Limit Locker Room Access Amid Coronavirus Concerns|url=https://bleacherreport.com/articles/2880015-report-nba-schedules-conference-call-to-talk-coronavirus-leagues-next-steps|website=Bleacher Report|date=March 9, 2020|accessdate=March 12, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Golden State Warriors]] earlier that day said the game the following day between them and the [[Brooklyn Nets]] would be played without fans, offering refunds or exchanges, following [[San Francisco]]'s order prohibiting assemblies larger than 1,000 individuals.<ref>{{cite web|first=Nick|last=Friedell|title=Warriors to play Nets without fans in arena following San Francisco order|url=https://www.espn.com/nba/story/_/id/28884486/warriors-play-home-games-fans-following-san-francisco-order|website=ESPN.com|date=March 11, 2020|accessdate=March 12, 2020}}</ref> The [[Cleveland Cavaliers]] were also going to play home games without fans, due to [[Ohio]] governor [[Mike DeWine]] banning mass gatherings in the state.<ref>{{cite web|first=John|last=Chick|title=Ohio to ban mass gatherings including sporting events|url=https://www.thescore.com/mlb/news/1963809/ohio-to-ban-mass-gatherings-including-sporting-events|website=theScore|date=March 11, 2020|accessdate=March 12, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Suspension==\nThe NBA indefinitely suspended the season for at least 30 days immediately following Utah Jazz center Rudy Gobert testing positive for the coronavirus prior to the tip-off of the Jazz\u2013Thunder game.<ref>{{cite web|first=Dan|last=Feldman|title=Jazz explain coronavirus testing of player (Rudy Gobert)|url=https://nba.nbcsports.com/2020/03/11/jazz-explain-coronavirus-testing-of-player-rudy-gobert/|website=ProBasketballTalk {{!}} NBC Sports|date=March 12, 2020|accessdate=March 12, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=NBA says virus hiatus will likely last 'at least' a month|url=https://www.foxnews.com/sports/nba-says-virus-hiatus-will-likely-last-at-least-a-month.amp|website=Fox News|agency=Associated Press|date=March 13, 2020|accessdate=March 13, 2020}}</ref> Players warming up were told to return to their locker rooms. Attendees were told by the public address announcer that the game was postponed \"due to unforeseen circumstances.\"<ref name=\":1\">{{cite web|first1=Brad|last1=Botkin|first2=Michael|last2=Kaskey-Blomain|title=NBA suspends season after Rudy Gobert tests positive for coronavirus; to reevaluate in 30 days|url=https://www.cbssports.com/nba/news/nba-suspends-season-after-rudy-gobert-tests-positive-for-coronavirus-to-reevaluate-in-30-days/|website=CBS Sports|date=March 11, 2020|accessdate=March 13, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe league asked teams who played the Jazz in the past 10 days to undergo 14 days of [[self-isolation]], including the Cleveland Cavaliers, [[New York Knicks]], [[Boston Celtics]], [[Detroit Pistons]], [[Toronto Raptors]], and the Oklahoma City Thunder.<ref name=\":1\"/> On March 12, 2020, the [[Philadelphia 76ers]] were asked to undergo self-isolation as well.<ref>{{cite web|first=Brian|last=Linder|title=Sixers ask players, staff to self-quarantine after possible coronavirus exposure, reports say|url=https://www.pennlive.com/sports/2020/03/sixers-ask-players-staff-to-self-quarantine-after-possible-coronavirus-exposure-reports-say.html|website=Penn Live|date=March 12, 2020|accessdate=March 13, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe [[NBA G League]] also suspended [[2019\u201320 NBA G League season|their season]].<ref>{{cite news|first=Jack|last=Maloney|title=NBA G League also suspends play indefinitely due to concerns about coronavirus|url=https://www.cbssports.com/nba/news/nba-g-league-also-suspends-play-indefinitely-due-to-concerns-about-coronavirus/|website=CBS Sports|date=March 11, 2020|accessdate=March 12, 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn the midst of the CDC recommending that events of 50 or more persons be cancelled for up to eight weeks, the NBA is looking at being suspended until June 2020, with the season ending in August 2020.<ref name=\"Quinn1\">{{cite web |last1=Quinn |first1=Sam |title=Coronavirus: NBA brass viewing mid-June return as best-case scenario amid new CDC recommendations, per report |url=https://www.cbssports.com/nba/news/coronavirus-nba-brass-viewing-mid-june-return-as-best-case-scenario-amid-new-cdc-recommendations-per-report/ |website=CBS Sports |date=March 15, 2020 |accessdate=March 15, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Subsequent actions===\nOn March 12, the NBA delineated a set of policies that was effective through March 16. These included players being required to remain in the market of their team, no group workouts or practices, and team physicians or trainers talking to each player daily.<ref>{{cite tweet|number=1238227995413921793|user=ShamsCharania|title=The NBA has informed all 30 teams on policies effective immediately and through March 16, including: <nowiki>-</nowiki> All players must remain in market of team <nowiki>-</nowiki> Players remain home as long as possible <nowiki>-</nowiki> NO group workouts, practices <nowiki>-</nowiki> Team physicians/trainers speak to each player once a day|first=Shams|last=Charania|date=March 12, 2020|accessdate=March 13, 2020}}</ref> The following day, the league and the [[National Basketball Players Association]] set a moratorium period until April 10, with players getting their pay in full on March 15.<ref>{{cite tweet|number=1238515375999983617|user=ShamsCharania|title=NBA and players union's moratorium period is planned to be effective March 12 (yesterday) to April 10, then reassess. Players will be paid in full on next check on March 15..|first=Shams|last=Charania|date=March 13, 2020|accessdate=March 13, 2020}}</ref> A memo sent to the NBA teams on March 15 allowed for players to travel out of their market provided they [[quarantine]]d, practiced [[social distancing]], and gave notices of their whereabouts. Teams were encouraged to do health check-ins.<ref>{{Cite tweet|user=ShamsCharania|number=1239377620824981510|title=Sources: Players who travel out of team's market during NBA season hiatus must: Provide whereabouts; remain home, do social distancing. Team permitted to pay for certain travel. Teams also encouraged to establish daily health/basketball check-ins (such as via FaceTime, Skype)..|last=Charania|first=Shams|date=2020-03-15|language=en|access-date=2020-03-19}}</ref>\n\nOn April 6, [[Ernie Johnson Jr.|Ernie Johnson]] from the [[NBA on TNT]] conducted an interview with Silver over [[videotelephony]], which was posted to the league's Twitter account. In it, Silver stated there would be no decision on a restart of the season made before May 1 at the bare minimum, a date that Silver admitted that a decision may not be made, and it could come much later.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.espn.com/nba/story/_/id/29003667/commissioner-adam-silver-does-not-expect-make-decisions-nba-season-least-may|title=Commissioner Adam Silver does not expect to make any decisions on NBA season until at least May|last=Bontemps|first=Tim|date=6 April 2020|publisher=ESPN.com|accessdate=7 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Infected players and personnel==\nThe following is a list of NBA players and personnel from the 2019\u201320 season that are known to have been infected:\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n! No.\n! Name\n! Team\n! Announced\n! Ref.\n|-\n! 1\n| [[Rudy Gobert]]\n| rowspan=\"2\"|[[Utah Jazz]]\n| March 11, 2020\n| <ref>{{cite web|first=Jack|last=Maloney|title=Coronavirus: Infected Jazz star Rudy Gobert issues apology 'to the people that I have endangered'|url=https://www.cbssports.com/nba/news/coronavirus-infected-jazz-star-rudy-gobert-issues-apology-to-the-people-that-i-have-endangered/|website=CBS Sports|date=March 12, 2020|accessdate=March 13, 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n! 2\n| [[Donovan Mitchell]]\n| March 12, 2020\n| <ref>{{cite web|title=Donovan Mitchell tests positive for coronavirus|url=https://www.espn.com/nba/story/_/id/28891354/donovan-mitchell-tests-positive-coronavirus|website=ESPN.com|agency=ESPN News Services|date=March 12, 2020|accessdate=March 12, 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n!3\n|[[Christian Wood]]\n|[[Detroit Pistons]]\n|March 14, 2020\n|<ref>{{cite web|first=Duncan|last=Smith|title=Detroit Pistons Center Christian Wood Tests Positive For Coronavirus|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/duncansmith/2020/03/14/detroit-pistons-center-christian-wood-tests-positive-for-coronavirus/#a5403dc603d0|website=Forbes|date=March 14, 2020|accessdate=March 15, 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n!4\n|[[Kevin Durant]]\n|rowspan=\"4\"|[[Brooklyn Nets]]\n|rowspan=\"4\"|March 17, 2020\n|rowspan=\"4\"|<ref name=Durant>{{cite web|title=Kevin Durant among four Nets players to test positive for coronavirus|url=https://www.espn.com/nba/story/_/id/28917855/four-nets-players-test-positive-coronavirus|website=ESPN.com|date=March 17, 2020|accessdate=March 17, 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n!5\n|rowspan=\"3\"|Undisclosed\n|-\n!6\n|-\n!7\n|-\n!8\n|Undisclosed\n|[[Denver Nuggets]]\n|March 19, 2020\n|rowspan=\"4\"|<ref name=Bontemps>{{cite web|first=Tim|last=Bontemps|title=Members of Philadelphia 76ers and Denver Nuggets test positive for virus|url=https://www.espn.com/nba/story/_/id/28927302/nuggets-say-member-organization-tested-positive-virus|website=ESPN.com|date=March 19, 2020|accessdate=March 22, 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n!9\n|rowspan=\"3\"|Undisclosed\n|rowspan=\"3\"|[[Philadelphia 76ers]]\n|rowspan=\"3\"|March 19, 2020\n|-\n!10\n|-\n!11\n|-\n!12\n|rowspan=\"2\"|Undisclosed\n|rowspan=\"2\"|[[Los Angeles Lakers]]\n|rowspan=\"2\"|March 19, 2020\n|rowspan=\"2\"|<ref name=\":4\">{{cite web|first=Michael|last=Kaskey-Blomain|title=Coronavirus: Lakers announce two players have tested positive for COVID-19|url=https://www.cbssports.com/nba/news/coronavirus-lakers-announce-two-players-have-tested-positive-for-covid-19/|website=CBS Sports|date=March 19, 2020|accessdate=March 22, 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n!13\n|-\n!14\n|[[Marcus Smart]]\n|[[Boston Celtics]]\n|March 19, 2020\n|<ref name=Smart>{{cite tweet|number=1240786953924214793|user=smart_ms3|title=I was tested 5 days ago and the results came back tonight, which were positive. Ive been self quarantined since the test, thank goodness. COVID-19 must be taken w the highest of seriousness. I know it\u2019s a #1 priority for our nations health experts, & we must get more testing ASAP|first=Marcus|last=Smart|date=March 19, 2020|accessdate=March 19, 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n!15\n|Maury Hanks\n|Detroit Pistons\n|March 26, 2020\n|<ref name=Hanks>{{cite web|first1=Ryan|last1=Ford|first2=Chris|last2=Thomas|title=Detroit Pistons scout Maury Hanks hospitalized with coronavirus: Here's what we know|url=https://www.freep.com/story/sports/nba/pistons/2020/03/26/detroit-pistons-scout-maury-hanks-coronavirus/2914039001/|website=Detroit Free Press|date=March 26, 2020|accessdate=March 26, 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n!16\n|[[James L. Dolan|James Dolan]]\n|[[New York Knicks]]\n|March 28, 2020\n|<ref>{{cite web|first=Malika|last=Andrews|title=Knicks owner James Dolan tests positive for coronavirus|url=https://www.espn.com/nba/story/_/id/28966720/knicks-owner-james-dolan-tests-positive-coronavirus|website=ESPN.com|date=March 28, 2020|accessdate=March 30, 2020}}</ref>\n|}\n\nOn March 12, during a special edition of ''[[Inside the NBA]]'', Hall of Fame player and analyst [[Charles Barkley]] revealed he was tested for the coronavirus after suffering from an illness after a recent trip to New York, which was rapidly becoming the worst hit locality of the U.S. pandemic. Barkley self-quarantined in his apartment in Atlanta, away from his wife and daughter. Barkley's test was subsequently negative and he completed his isolation period two weeks later.\n\nOn March 17, the Brooklyn Nets announced that four of their players had tested positive as well, one of whom was forward Kevin Durant.<ref name=Durant/>\n\nOn March 19, the Denver Nuggets announced one of their players tested positive three days earlier. On the same day, the Philadelphia 76ers announced three of their staffers also tested positive,<ref name=Bontemps/> and the Los Angeles Lakers announced two players tested positive.<ref name=\":4\" /> Marcus Smart later went on Twitter to announce that his results came back positive after he was tested five days prior.<ref name=Smart/>\n\nOn March 25, Christian Wood announced he had \"fully recovered\" from the virus.<ref>{{cite web|first=Sam|last=Quinn|title=Coronavirus: Pistons' Christian Wood 'fully recovered' from COVID-19, according to agent|url=https://www.cbssports.com/nba/news/coronavirus-pistons-christian-wood-fully-recovered-from-covid-19-according-to-agent/|website=CBS Sports|date=March 25, 2020|accessdate=March 26, 2020}}</ref> However, on the same day, it was reported that a cameraman who worked the Jazz\u2013Pistons game on March 7 at [[Little Caesars Arena]] had been infected by the virus and was placed in a medically induced coma.<ref>{{cite web|first1=Vincent|last1=Goodwill|first2=Dan|last2=Wetzel|title=Cameraman who worked Jazz-Pistons game diagnosed with coronavirus, in coma|url=https://sports.yahoo.com/cameraman-who-worked-jazz-pistons-game-diagnosed-with-coronavirus-in-coma-033052933.html|website=Yahoo Sports|date=March 25, 2020|accessdate=March 26, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 26, it was announced that Maury Hanks, a Pistons scout, had been hospitalized with the virus.<ref name=Hanks/>\n\nOn March 27, the [[Utah Department of Health]] cleared the Jazz of the virus.<ref>{{cite web|first=Aaron|last=Falk|title=Utah Jazz players, staff cleared by health department after 14 days of COVID-19 quarantine and isolation|url=https://www.nba.com/jazz/news/utah-jazz-players-staff-cleared-health-department-after-14-days-covid-19-quarantine-and|website=NBA.com|date=March 27, 2020|accessdate=March 30, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 27, ESPN NBA analyst [[Doris Burke]] revealed she had tested positive for the virus two weeks earlier. Burke had been experiencing symptoms before calling her scheduled game on March 11 in Dallas. There has been no word on whether or not her colleague, Ryan Ruocco, was either tested or symptomatic following his exposure to Burke.<ref>{{cite web|first=Mike|last=Chiari|title=ESPN NBA Analyst Doris Burke Says She's Tested Positive for COVID-19|url=https://bleacherreport.com/articles/2883400-espn-nba-analyst-doris-burke-says-shes-tested-positive-for-covid-19|website=Bleacher Report|date=March 27, 2020|accessdate=March 29, 2020}}</ref> She is now symptom-free, but was not cleared as of March 30. \n\nOn April 13, the mother of [[Minnesota Timberwolves]] center [[Karl-Anthony Towns]], Jacqueline Towns, died at age 58 of complications of the coronavirus after having previously been placed in a medically-induced coma.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Press|first=The Associated|url=https://www.nytimes.com/aponline/2020/04/13/sports/basketball/ap-bkn-obit-towns-mother.html|title=Mom of T-Wolves Star Karl-Anthony Towns Dies From COVID-19|date=2020-04-13|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-04-14|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\n==Reactions==\n===Players===\nThe suspension drew remarks from several current and former NBA players.<ref>{{cite web|title=NBA players react to league suspending season due to coronavirus|url=https://www.espn.com/nba/story/_/id/28887696/nba-players-react-league-suspending-season-due-coronavirus|website=ESPN.com|date=March 12, 2020|accessdate=March 12, 2020}}</ref> Several players pledged to offer assistance to arena workers across the league who are without work due to the league's response to the coronavirus.<ref name=Love>{{cite web|first=Dave|last=McMenamin|title=Kevin Love kicks off support drive for arena workers with $100K pledge|url=https://www.espn.com/nba/story/_/id/28894232/kevin-love-kicks-support-drive-arena-workers-100k-pledge|website=ESPN.com|date=March 13, 2020|accessdate=March 13, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|first=Nick|last=Schwartz|title=Zion Williamson will pay the salaries of New Orleans arena workers for one month|url=https://ftw.usatoday.com/2020/03/zion-williamson-will-pay-the-salaries-of-new-orleans-arena-workers-for-one-month|website=For the Win|date=March 13, 2020|accessdate=March 13, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|first1=Malika|last1=Andrews|first2=Andrew|last2=Lopez|title=Giannis Antetokounmpo, Zion Williamson among stars aiding arena workers|url=https://www.espn.com/nba/story/_/id/28898869/giannis-antetokounmpo-pledges-100k-help-fiserv-forum-staff|website=ESPN.com|date=March 13, 2020|accessdate=March 14, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|first=Jeff|last=Zillgitt|title=Utah's Rudy Gobert, first NBA player with positive coronavirus test, pledges more than $500,000 for arena employees, others|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/sports/nba/jazz/2020/03/14/jazz-rudy-gobert-giving-over-500-000-coronavirus-relief-funds/5051521002/|website=USA Today|date=March 14, 2020|accessdate=March 15, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Teams and arenas===\nThe [[Dallas Mavericks]], Cleveland Cavaliers, and Detroit Pistons were among the first to announce plans that would pay workers for the days they are missing due to the suspension of the league.<ref name=Love/><ref>{{cite web|first=Dana|last=Gauruder|title=All Detroit Pistons employees, including LCA operations, to be paid during NBA's hiatus|url=https://www.freep.com/story/sports/nba/pistons/2020/03/12/detroit-pistons-news-employees-little-caesars-arena/5039226002/|website=Detroit Free Press|date=March 12, 2020|accessdate=March 13, 2020}}</ref> On March 28, the Pistons announced that they would offer their performance center facility to health officials for use against the virus.<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.tmz.com/2020/03/28/detroit-pistons-nba-new-performance-center-coronavirus-covid-19/|title=DETROIT PISTONS OFFER UP NEW FACILITY FOR COVID-19 ... Testing, Patients, Etc.|date=28 March 2020|work=TMZ Sports|access-date=29 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===National Hockey League===\nOn March 12, 2020, the following day after the NBA suspended the season, the [[National Hockey League|NHL]] suspended [[2019\u201320 NHL season|their 2019\u201320 season]]. In a statement addressing the situation, the NHL included: <blockquote>The NHL has been attempting to follow the mandates of health experts and local authorities, while preparing for any possible developments without taking any premature or unnecessary measures. However, following last night's news that an NBA player has tested positive for the coronavirus \u2013 and given that our leagues share so many facilities and locker rooms and it now seems likely that some member of the NHL community would test positive at some point \u2013 it is no longer appropriate to try to continue to play games at this time.<ref>{{cite web|title=NHL statement on coronavirus|url=https://www.nhl.com/news/nhl-coronavirus-status/c-316155530|website=NHL.com|date=March 12, 2020|accessdate=March 16, 2020}}</ref></blockquote>\n\n==Impact==\nThe suspension is expected to cost the league hundreds of millions of dollars in lost revenue in national television advertisements and lost ticket sales.<ref>{{cite web|first=Thomas|last=Barrabi|title=What coronavirus will cost NCAA, NBA and other US sports leagues|url=https://www.foxbusiness.com/sports/coronavirus-cost-ncaa-nba-mlb-nfl-nhl.amp|website=Fox Business|date=March 13, 2020|accessdate=March 13, 2020}}</ref> With the vast majority of events at stadiums cancelled, down-the-line arena workers are at risk due to lost revenue from unused tickets and effective employment as a result of closed concession stands and surrounding team memorabilia stands and shops, along with surrounding entertainment districts.<ref name=\":0\"/>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic on games and sports]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://cares.nba.com/coronavirus/ Coronavirus Information for NBA Fans] (NBA.com)\n\n{{NBA}}\n{{2019\u201320 NBA season by team}}\n{{2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United States}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Suspension of the 2019-20 NBA season}}\n[[Category:2019\u201320 NBA season]]\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United States]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date = March 2020}}\n\n[[File:Rudy Gobert 2015 (cropped).jpg|thumb|right|upright=0.90|[[Rudy Gobert]] was the first NBA player to test positive for COVID-19]]\nOn March 11, 2020, the [[National Basketball Association]] (NBA) announced the suspension of the [[2019\u201320 NBA season|2019\u201320 season]] following [[Utah Jazz]] center [[Rudy Gobert]] testing positive for the [[coronavirus disease 2019]], also known as COVID-19. Gobert had come down with an illness before a scheduled basketball game against the [[Oklahoma City Thunder]] that day at [[Chesapeake Energy Arena]] in [[Oklahoma City]]. He was not at the arena but instead at the team's hotel, and was later taken to a nearby hospital where he tested positive for the coronavirus. The next day, Gobert's teammate [[Donovan Mitchell]] also tested positive for the virus.\n\n==Background==\n{{main|2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United States|2020 coronavirus pandemic in Canada|l2=Canada}}\nThe NBA had been tracking [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|the coronavirus pandemic]] closely, speaking with public health authorities such as the [[Centers for Disease Control and Prevention|Center for Disease Control]] (CDC) on the matter.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite web|first1=Mark|last1=Medina|first2=Jeff|last2=Zillgitt|title=Coronavirus: NBA moving toward banning fans, but still no decision on how to handle games|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/sports/nba/2020/03/11/coronavirus-nba-plan-games-fans/5023870002/|website=USA Today|date=March 11, 2020|accessdate=March 12, 2020}}</ref> The league spoke to the [[National Basketball Players Association|players' union]] on the prospect of playing games without fans. The league held a conference call on March 11, 2020 between [[Adam Silver|Commissioner Adam Silver]] and the 30 owners to reach a consensus on the matter.<ref>{{cite web|first1=Adrian|last1=Wojnarowski|first2=Zach|last2=Lowe|title=Sources: NBA, owners to plot coronavirus plans|url=https://www.espn.com/nba/story/_/id/28872514/sources-nba-books-wednesday-conference-call-discuss-coronavirus-strategy-owners|website=ESPN.com|date=March 9, 2020|accessdate=March 12, 2020}}</ref> They were envisioning a scenario where games were to be played with essential personnel only and no fans in attendance, following suit with the [[National Collegiate Athletic Association|NCAA]].<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nThe NBA's first material measures included limiting locker room access to players, coaches, general managers, and basketball and public relations staff, with the notable exclusion of media. The NBA had told teams they should make plans for the possibility of playing games without fans and with only essential personnel in attendance.<ref>{{cite web|first=Joseph|last=Zucker|title=NBA Will Reportedly Limit Locker Room Access Amid Coronavirus Concerns|url=https://bleacherreport.com/articles/2880015-report-nba-schedules-conference-call-to-talk-coronavirus-leagues-next-steps|website=Bleacher Report|date=March 9, 2020|accessdate=March 12, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Golden State Warriors]] earlier that day said the game the following day between them and the [[Brooklyn Nets]] would be played without fans, offering refunds or exchanges, following [[San Francisco]]'s order prohibiting assemblies larger than 1,000 individuals.<ref>{{cite web|first=Nick|last=Friedell|title=Warriors to play Nets without fans in arena following San Francisco order|url=https://www.espn.com/nba/story/_/id/28884486/warriors-play-home-games-fans-following-san-francisco-order|website=ESPN.com|date=March 11, 2020|accessdate=March 12, 2020}}</ref> The [[Cleveland Cavaliers]] were also going to play home games without fans, due to [[Ohio]] governor [[Mike DeWine]] banning mass gatherings in the state.<ref>{{cite web|first=John|last=Chick|title=Ohio to ban mass gatherings including sporting events|url=https://www.thescore.com/mlb/news/1963809/ohio-to-ban-mass-gatherings-including-sporting-events|website=theScore|date=March 11, 2020|accessdate=March 12, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Suspension==\nThe NBA indefinitely suspended the season for at least 30 days immediately following Utah Jazz center Rudy Gobert testing positive for the coronavirus prior to the tip-off of the Jazz\u2013Thunder game.<ref>{{cite web|first=Dan|last=Feldman|title=Jazz explain coronavirus testing of player (Rudy Gobert)|url=https://nba.nbcsports.com/2020/03/11/jazz-explain-coronavirus-testing-of-player-rudy-gobert/|website=ProBasketballTalk {{!}} NBC Sports|date=March 12, 2020|accessdate=March 12, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=NBA says virus hiatus will likely last 'at least' a month|url=https://www.foxnews.com/sports/nba-says-virus-hiatus-will-likely-last-at-least-a-month.amp|website=Fox News|agency=Associated Press|date=March 13, 2020|accessdate=March 13, 2020}}</ref> Players warming up were told to return to their locker rooms. Attendees were told by the public address announcer that the game was postponed \"due to unforeseen circumstances.\"<ref name=\":1\">{{cite web|first1=Brad|last1=Botkin|first2=Michael|last2=Kaskey-Blomain|title=NBA suspends season after Rudy Gobert tests positive for coronavirus; to reevaluate in 30 days|url=https://www.cbssports.com/nba/news/nba-suspends-season-after-rudy-gobert-tests-positive-for-coronavirus-to-reevaluate-in-30-days/|website=CBS Sports|date=March 11, 2020|accessdate=March 13, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe league asked teams who played the Jazz in the past 10 days to undergo 14 days of [[self-isolation]], including the Cleveland Cavaliers, [[New York Knicks]], [[Boston Celtics]], [[Detroit Pistons]], [[Toronto Raptors]], and the Oklahoma City Thunder.<ref name=\":1\"/> On March 12, 2020, the [[Philadelphia 76ers]] were asked to undergo self-isolation as well.<ref>{{cite web|first=Brian|last=Linder|title=Sixers ask players, staff to self-quarantine after possible coronavirus exposure, reports say|url=https://www.pennlive.com/sports/2020/03/sixers-ask-players-staff-to-self-quarantine-after-possible-coronavirus-exposure-reports-say.html|website=Penn Live|date=March 12, 2020|accessdate=March 13, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe [[NBA G League]] also suspended [[2019\u201320 NBA G League season|their season]].<ref>{{cite news|first=Jack|last=Maloney|title=NBA G League also suspends play indefinitely due to concerns about coronavirus|url=https://www.cbssports.com/nba/news/nba-g-league-also-suspends-play-indefinitely-due-to-concerns-about-coronavirus/|website=CBS Sports|date=March 11, 2020|accessdate=March 12, 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn the midst of the CDC recommending that events of 50 or more persons be cancelled for up to eight weeks, the NBA is looking at being suspended until June 2020, with the season ending in August 2020.<ref name=\"Quinn1\">{{cite web |last1=Quinn |first1=Sam |title=Coronavirus: NBA brass viewing mid-June return as best-case scenario amid new CDC recommendations, per report |url=https://www.cbssports.com/nba/news/coronavirus-nba-brass-viewing-mid-june-return-as-best-case-scenario-amid-new-cdc-recommendations-per-report/ |website=CBS Sports |date=March 15, 2020 |accessdate=March 15, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Subsequent actions===\nOn March 12, the NBA delineated a set of policies that was effective through March 16. These included players being required to remain in the market of their team, no group workouts or practices, and team physicians or trainers talking to each player daily.<ref>{{cite tweet|number=1238227995413921793|user=ShamsCharania|title=The NBA has informed all 30 teams on policies effective immediately and through March 16, including: <nowiki>-</nowiki> All players must remain in market of team <nowiki>-</nowiki> Players remain home as long as possible <nowiki>-</nowiki> NO group workouts, practices <nowiki>-</nowiki> Team physicians/trainers speak to each player once a day|first=Shams|last=Charania|date=March 12, 2020|accessdate=March 13, 2020}}</ref> The following day, the league and the [[National Basketball Players Association]] set a moratorium period until April 10, with players getting their pay in full on March 15.<ref>{{cite tweet|number=1238515375999983617|user=ShamsCharania|title=NBA and players union's moratorium period is planned to be effective March 12 (yesterday) to April 10, then reassess. Players will be paid in full on next check on March 15..|first=Shams|last=Charania|date=March 13, 2020|accessdate=March 13, 2020}}</ref> A memo sent to the NBA teams on March 15 allowed for players to travel out of their market provided they [[quarantine]]d, practiced [[social distancing]], and gave notices of their whereabouts. Teams were encouraged to do health check-ins.<ref>{{Cite tweet|user=ShamsCharania|number=1239377620824981510|title=Sources: Players who travel out of team's market during NBA season hiatus must: Provide whereabouts; remain home, do social distancing. Team permitted to pay for certain travel. Teams also encouraged to establish daily health/basketball check-ins (such as via FaceTime, Skype)..|last=Charania|first=Shams|date=2020-03-15|language=en|access-date=2020-03-19}}</ref>\n\nOn April 6, [[Ernie Johnson Jr.|Ernie Johnson]] from the [[NBA on TNT]] conducted an interview with Silver over [[videotelephony]], which was posted to the league's Twitter account. In it, Silver stated there would be no decision on a restart of the season made before May 1 at the bare minimum, a date that Silver admitted that a decision may not be made, and it could come much later.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.espn.com/nba/story/_/id/29003667/commissioner-adam-silver-does-not-expect-make-decisions-nba-season-least-may|title=Commissioner Adam Silver does not expect to make any decisions on NBA season until at least May|last=Bontemps|first=Tim|date=6 April 2020|publisher=ESPN.com|accessdate=7 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Infected players and personnel==\nThe following is a list of NBA players and personnel from the 2019\u201320 season that are known to have been infected:\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n! No.\n! Name\n! Team\n! Announced\n! Ref.\n|-\n! 1\n| [[Rudy Gobert]]\n| rowspan=\"2\"|[[Utah Jazz]]\n| March 11, 2020\n| <ref>{{cite web|first=Jack|last=Maloney|title=Coronavirus: Infected Jazz star Rudy Gobert issues apology 'to the people that I have endangered'|url=https://www.cbssports.com/nba/news/coronavirus-infected-jazz-star-rudy-gobert-issues-apology-to-the-people-that-i-have-endangered/|website=CBS Sports|date=March 12, 2020|accessdate=March 13, 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n! 2\n| [[Donovan Mitchell]]\n| March 12, 2020\n| <ref>{{cite web|title=Donovan Mitchell tests positive for coronavirus|url=https://www.espn.com/nba/story/_/id/28891354/donovan-mitchell-tests-positive-coronavirus|website=ESPN.com|agency=ESPN News Services|date=March 12, 2020|accessdate=March 12, 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n!3\n|[[Christian Wood]]\n|[[Detroit Pistons]]\n|March 14, 2020\n|<ref>{{cite web|first=Duncan|last=Smith|title=Detroit Pistons Center Christian Wood Tests Positive For Coronavirus|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/duncansmith/2020/03/14/detroit-pistons-center-christian-wood-tests-positive-for-coronavirus/#a5403dc603d0|website=Forbes|date=March 14, 2020|accessdate=March 15, 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n!4\n|[[Kevin Durant]]\n|rowspan=\"4\"|[[Brooklyn Nets]]\n|rowspan=\"4\"|March 17, 2020\n|rowspan=\"4\"|<ref name=Durant>{{cite web|title=Kevin Durant among four Nets players to test positive for coronavirus|url=https://www.espn.com/nba/story/_/id/28917855/four-nets-players-test-positive-coronavirus|website=ESPN.com|date=March 17, 2020|accessdate=March 17, 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n!5\n|rowspan=\"3\"|Undisclosed\n|-\n!6\n|-\n!7\n|-\n!8\n|Undisclosed\n|[[Denver Nuggets]]\n|March 19, 2020\n|rowspan=\"4\"|<ref name=Bontemps>{{cite web|first=Tim|last=Bontemps|title=Members of Philadelphia 76ers and Denver Nuggets test positive for virus|url=https://www.espn.com/nba/story/_/id/28927302/nuggets-say-member-organization-tested-positive-virus|website=ESPN.com|date=March 19, 2020|accessdate=March 22, 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n!9\n|rowspan=\"3\"|Undisclosed\n|rowspan=\"3\"|[[Philadelphia 76ers]]\n|rowspan=\"3\"|March 19, 2020\n|-\n!10\n|-\n!11\n|-\n!12\n|rowspan=\"2\"|Undisclosed\n|rowspan=\"2\"|[[Los Angeles Lakers]]\n|rowspan=\"2\"|March 19, 2020\n|rowspan=\"2\"|<ref name=\":4\">{{cite web|first=Michael|last=Kaskey-Blomain|title=Coronavirus: Lakers announce two players have tested positive for COVID-19|url=https://www.cbssports.com/nba/news/coronavirus-lakers-announce-two-players-have-tested-positive-for-covid-19/|website=CBS Sports|date=March 19, 2020|accessdate=March 22, 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n!13\n|-\n!14\n|[[Marcus Smart]]\n|[[Boston Celtics]]\n|March 19, 2020\n|<ref name=Smart>{{cite tweet|number=1240786953924214793|user=smart_ms3|title=I was tested 5 days ago and the results came back tonight, which were positive. Ive been self quarantined since the test, thank goodness. COVID-19 must be taken w the highest of seriousness. I know it\u2019s a #1 priority for our nations health experts, & we must get more testing ASAP|first=Marcus|last=Smart|date=March 19, 2020|accessdate=March 19, 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n!15\n|Maury Hanks\n|Detroit Pistons\n|March 26, 2020\n|<ref name=Hanks>{{cite web|first1=Ryan|last1=Ford|first2=Chris|last2=Thomas|title=Detroit Pistons scout Maury Hanks hospitalized with coronavirus: Here's what we know|url=https://www.freep.com/story/sports/nba/pistons/2020/03/26/detroit-pistons-scout-maury-hanks-coronavirus/2914039001/|website=Detroit Free Press|date=March 26, 2020|accessdate=March 26, 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n!16\n|[[James L. Dolan|James Dolan]]\n|[[New York Knicks]]\n|March 28, 2020\n|<ref>{{cite web|first=Malika|last=Andrews|title=Knicks owner James Dolan tests positive for coronavirus|url=https://www.espn.com/nba/story/_/id/28966720/knicks-owner-james-dolan-tests-positive-coronavirus|website=ESPN.com|date=March 28, 2020|accessdate=March 30, 2020}}</ref>\n|}\n\nOn March 12, during a special edition of ''[[Inside the NBA]]'', Hall of Fame player and analyst [[Charles Barkley]] revealed he was tested for the coronavirus after suffering from an illness after a recent trip to New York, which was rapidly becoming the worst hit locality of the U.S. pandemic. Barkley self-quarantined in his apartment in Atlanta, away from his wife and daughter. Barkley's test was subsequently negative and he completed his isolation period two weeks later.\n\nOn March 17, the Brooklyn Nets announced that four of their players had tested positive as well, one of whom was forward Kevin Durant.<ref name=Durant/>\n\nOn March 19, the Denver Nuggets announced one of their players tested positive three days earlier. On the same day, the Philadelphia 76ers announced three of their staffers also tested positive,<ref name=Bontemps/> and the Los Angeles Lakers announced two players tested positive.<ref name=\":4\" /> Marcus Smart later went on Twitter to announce that his results came back positive after he was tested five days prior.<ref name=Smart/>\n\nOn March 25, Christian Wood announced he had \"fully recovered\" from the virus.<ref>{{cite web|first=Sam|last=Quinn|title=Coronavirus: Pistons' Christian Wood 'fully recovered' from COVID-19, according to agent|url=https://www.cbssports.com/nba/news/coronavirus-pistons-christian-wood-fully-recovered-from-covid-19-according-to-agent/|website=CBS Sports|date=March 25, 2020|accessdate=March 26, 2020}}</ref> However, on the same day, it was reported that a cameraman who worked the Jazz\u2013Pistons game on March 7 at [[Little Caesars Arena]] had been infected by the virus and was placed in a medically induced coma.<ref>{{cite web|first1=Vincent|last1=Goodwill|first2=Dan|last2=Wetzel|title=Cameraman who worked Jazz-Pistons game diagnosed with coronavirus, in coma|url=https://sports.yahoo.com/cameraman-who-worked-jazz-pistons-game-diagnosed-with-coronavirus-in-coma-033052933.html|website=Yahoo Sports|date=March 25, 2020|accessdate=March 26, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 26, it was announced that Maury Hanks, a Pistons scout, had been hospitalized with the virus.<ref name=Hanks/>\n\nOn March 27, the [[Utah Department of Health]] cleared the Jazz of the virus.<ref>{{cite web|first=Aaron|last=Falk|title=Utah Jazz players, staff cleared by health department after 14 days of COVID-19 quarantine and isolation|url=https://www.nba.com/jazz/news/utah-jazz-players-staff-cleared-health-department-after-14-days-covid-19-quarantine-and|website=NBA.com|date=March 27, 2020|accessdate=March 30, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 27, ESPN NBA analyst [[Doris Burke]] revealed she had tested positive for the virus two weeks earlier. Burke had been experiencing symptoms before calling her scheduled game on March 11 in Dallas. There has been no word on whether or not her colleague, Ryan Ruocco, was either tested or symptomatic following his exposure to Burke.<ref>{{cite web|first=Mike|last=Chiari|title=ESPN NBA Analyst Doris Burke Says She's Tested Positive for COVID-19|url=https://bleacherreport.com/articles/2883400-espn-nba-analyst-doris-burke-says-shes-tested-positive-for-covid-19|website=Bleacher Report|date=March 27, 2020|accessdate=March 29, 2020}}</ref> She is now symptom-free, but was not cleared as of March 30. \n\nOn April 13, the mother of [[Minnesota Timberwolves]] center [[Karl-Anthony Towns]], Jacqueline Towns, died at age 59 of complications of the coronavirus after having previously been placed in a medically-induced coma.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Press|first=The Associated|url=https://www.nytimes.com/aponline/2020/04/13/sports/basketball/ap-bkn-obit-towns-mother.html|title=Mom of T-Wolves Star Karl-Anthony Towns Dies From COVID-19|date=2020-04-13|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-04-14|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\n==Reactions==\n===Players===\nThe suspension drew remarks from several current and former NBA players.<ref>{{cite web|title=NBA players react to league suspending season due to coronavirus|url=https://www.espn.com/nba/story/_/id/28887696/nba-players-react-league-suspending-season-due-coronavirus|website=ESPN.com|date=March 12, 2020|accessdate=March 12, 2020}}</ref> Several players pledged to offer assistance to arena workers across the league who are without work due to the league's response to the coronavirus.<ref name=Love>{{cite web|first=Dave|last=McMenamin|title=Kevin Love kicks off support drive for arena workers with $100K pledge|url=https://www.espn.com/nba/story/_/id/28894232/kevin-love-kicks-support-drive-arena-workers-100k-pledge|website=ESPN.com|date=March 13, 2020|accessdate=March 13, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|first=Nick|last=Schwartz|title=Zion Williamson will pay the salaries of New Orleans arena workers for one month|url=https://ftw.usatoday.com/2020/03/zion-williamson-will-pay-the-salaries-of-new-orleans-arena-workers-for-one-month|website=For the Win|date=March 13, 2020|accessdate=March 13, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|first1=Malika|last1=Andrews|first2=Andrew|last2=Lopez|title=Giannis Antetokounmpo, Zion Williamson among stars aiding arena workers|url=https://www.espn.com/nba/story/_/id/28898869/giannis-antetokounmpo-pledges-100k-help-fiserv-forum-staff|website=ESPN.com|date=March 13, 2020|accessdate=March 14, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|first=Jeff|last=Zillgitt|title=Utah's Rudy Gobert, first NBA player with positive coronavirus test, pledges more than $500,000 for arena employees, others|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/sports/nba/jazz/2020/03/14/jazz-rudy-gobert-giving-over-500-000-coronavirus-relief-funds/5051521002/|website=USA Today|date=March 14, 2020|accessdate=March 15, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Teams and arenas===\nThe [[Dallas Mavericks]], Cleveland Cavaliers, and Detroit Pistons were among the first to announce plans that would pay workers for the days they are missing due to the suspension of the league.<ref name=Love/><ref>{{cite web|first=Dana|last=Gauruder|title=All Detroit Pistons employees, including LCA operations, to be paid during NBA's hiatus|url=https://www.freep.com/story/sports/nba/pistons/2020/03/12/detroit-pistons-news-employees-little-caesars-arena/5039226002/|website=Detroit Free Press|date=March 12, 2020|accessdate=March 13, 2020}}</ref> On March 28, the Pistons announced that they would offer their performance center facility to health officials for use against the virus.<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.tmz.com/2020/03/28/detroit-pistons-nba-new-performance-center-coronavirus-covid-19/|title=DETROIT PISTONS OFFER UP NEW FACILITY FOR COVID-19 ... Testing, Patients, Etc.|date=28 March 2020|work=TMZ Sports|access-date=29 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===National Hockey League===\nOn March 12, 2020, the following day after the NBA suspended the season, the [[National Hockey League|NHL]] suspended [[2019\u201320 NHL season|their 2019\u201320 season]]. In a statement addressing the situation, the NHL included: <blockquote>The NHL has been attempting to follow the mandates of health experts and local authorities, while preparing for any possible developments without taking any premature or unnecessary measures. However, following last night's news that an NBA player has tested positive for the coronavirus \u2013 and given that our leagues share so many facilities and locker rooms and it now seems likely that some member of the NHL community would test positive at some point \u2013 it is no longer appropriate to try to continue to play games at this time.<ref>{{cite web|title=NHL statement on coronavirus|url=https://www.nhl.com/news/nhl-coronavirus-status/c-316155530|website=NHL.com|date=March 12, 2020|accessdate=March 16, 2020}}</ref></blockquote>\n\n==Impact==\nThe suspension is expected to cost the league hundreds of millions of dollars in lost revenue in national television advertisements and lost ticket sales.<ref>{{cite web|first=Thomas|last=Barrabi|title=What coronavirus will cost NCAA, NBA and other US sports leagues|url=https://www.foxbusiness.com/sports/coronavirus-cost-ncaa-nba-mlb-nfl-nhl.amp|website=Fox Business|date=March 13, 2020|accessdate=March 13, 2020}}</ref> With the vast majority of events at stadiums cancelled, down-the-line arena workers are at risk due to lost revenue from unused tickets and effective employment as a result of closed concession stands and surrounding team memorabilia stands and shops, along with surrounding entertainment districts.<ref name=\":0\"/>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic on games and sports]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://cares.nba.com/coronavirus/ Coronavirus Information for NBA Fans] (NBA.com)\n\n{{NBA}}\n{{2019\u201320 NBA season by team}}\n{{2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United States}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Suspension of the 2019-20 NBA season}}\n[[Category:2019\u201320 NBA season]]\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United States]]\n", "name_user": "DrLuigiGamer2001", "label": "safe", "comment": "I made a mistake sorry.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Suspension_of_the_2019%E2%80%9320_NBA_season"}
{"title_page": "Victoria Ransom", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n| name          = Victoria Ransom\n| image         = Victoria Ransom.jpg\n| alt           = \n| caption       = \n| nationality   = [[New Zealanders|New Zealander]] \n| education          = [[Bachelor of Arts]], [[Master of Business Administration]]\n| alma_mater        = [[United World College]], [[Macalester College]], [[Harvard Business School]]\n| occupation    = [[Entrepreneurship|Entrepreneur]]\n| known_for     = Co-founder and CEO of Wildfire Interactive\n| partner = [[Alain Chuard]]\n}}\n\n'''Victoria Ransom''' is a serial entrepreneur from New Zealand. She has developed three companies including [[Wildfire Interactive]], a social marketing [[Software as a service|SaaS]] company, where Ransom was CEO until it was sold to [[Google]] in 2012.<ref name=fortune>{{cite web |url=http://fortune.com/2012/10/19/victoria-ransoms-wild-ride/ |title=Victoria Ransom's wild ride |last1=Coster |first1=Helen |date=October 19, 2012|publisher=TIME Magazine |access-date=September 28, 2015}}</ref><ref name=nytimes>{{cite web |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2013/01/27/business/victoria-ransom-of-wildfire-on-instilling-a-companys-values.html?_r=1 |title=If Supervisors Respect the Values, So Will Everyone Else |last1=Bryant |first1=Adam |date=January 26, 2013 |publisher=New York Times |access-date=September 28, 2015}}</ref> Ransom currently resides in [[Palo Alto]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://blogs.wsj.com/digits/2015/05/12/google-shopping-leader-decamps-for-jawbone/ |title=Google Shopping Leader Decamps for Jawbone |last1=Barr |first1=Alastair |date=May 12, 2015|publisher=Wall Street Journal |access-date=September 28, 2015}}</ref>\n\nRansom was listed as one of [[Fortune (magazine)|''Fortune's'']] [[Fortune Most Powerful Women Entrepreneurs|Most Powerful Women Entrepreneurs]]<ref>{{cite web |url=http://fortune.com/2012/08/31/who-are-the-2012-most-powerful-women-entrepreneurs/ |title=Who are the 2012 Most Powerful Women Entrepreneurs? |last1=Sellers |first1=Patricia |date=August 31, 2012|publisher=Fortune Magazine|access-date=September 28, 2015}}</ref> as well as one of their [[40 under 40 (Fortune magazine)|40 under 40]] in 2012.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://fortune.com/40-under-40/2012/victoria-ransom-19/ |title=40 Under 40 2012|publisher=Fortune Magazine|access-date=September 28, 2015}}</ref> In 2015, she was named a Young Global Leader by the [[World Economic Forum]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.weforum.org/young-global-leaders/victoria-ransom |title=Victoria Ransom Founder and Chief Executive Officer, Wildfire Google|publisher=World Economic Forum |access-date=September 28, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nbr.co.nz/victoria-ransom |title=RANSOM Victoria Technology |publisher=National Business Review |access-date=September 28, 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Education==\nRansom was raised on an asparagus farm in Scotts Ferry, near [[Bulls, New Zealand|Bulls]], New Zealand.<ref>{{Cite news|url = http://www.stuff.co.nz/manawatu-standard/news/8962421/Rangitikei-woman-makes-rich-list|title = Rangitikei woman makes rich list|last = |first = |date = 25 July 2013|work = |access-date = 10 January 2016|via = |newspaper = Manawatu Standard}}</ref> In her final year at [[Whanganui Girls' College]],<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Scherer|first=Karyn|date=1 September 2012|title=A king's ransom|url=http://www.listener.co.nz/current-affairs/profile/a-kings-ransom/|journal=The Listener|doi=|pmid=|access-date=11 April 2012}}</ref> she won a scholarship to attend international high school [[Armand Hammer United World College of the American West|United World College]] in [[New Mexico]].<ref name=ft>{{cite web |url=http://www.ft.com/intl/cms/s/2/1364d1d4-0d5a-11e2-97a1-00144feabdc0.html#axzz3lH4K68S1 |title=Ten Questions: Victoria Ransom |last1=Clarke |first1=Charlotte |date=October 8, 2012 |publisher=The Financial Times Limited |access-date= September 28, 2015}}</ref><ref name=macalester/> She then attended [[Macalester College]], where she earned her [[Bachelor of Arts|BA]] in psychology and graduated ''[[Latin honors#types|summa cum laude]]'' in 1999.<ref name=macalester/> Ransom received her [[Master of Business Administration|MBA]] from [[Harvard Business School]] in 2008.<ref name=ft/>\n\n==Career==\nAfter graduating from Macalester, Ransom  moved to [[London]] where she worked as a business consultant. Later, she moved to [[New York City]] and worked for investment banking firm [[Morgan Stanley]]. She left the company in 2001 and founded Access Trips, an adventure travel company in New Zealand.<ref name=macalester/> Ransom co-ran Access Trips for five years before returning to the US to attend business school.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.sramanamitra.com/2012/03/29/from-new-zealand-to-silicon-valley-victoria-ransoms-wildfire-journey-part-1/ |title=From New Zealand To Silicon Valley: Victoria Ransom\u2019s Wildfire Journey |last1=Mitra |first1=Sramana |date=March 29, 2012 |publisher= sramanamitra.com |access-date=September 28, 2015}}</ref> While at [[Harvard Business School]], Ransom co-developed a distributed booking system for small and medium size travel companies, resulting in a summer at [[Highland Capital Partners]] as an [[Entrepreneur in Residence]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.thenextwomen.com/next-women-list/item/victoria-ransom |title=Next Woman List: Victoria Ransom|publisher=The NextWomen |access-date=September 28, 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn 2008, Ransom founded Wildfire Interactive, a social marketing software company initially developed to help promote Access Trips.<ref name=fortune/> Ransom ran Wildfire as CEO and grew the company to 400 employees in four years.<ref name=macalester>{{cite web |url=http://www.macalester.edu/news/2013/02/the-winding-road-to-wildfire/ |title=The Winding Road To Wildfire |last1=Rebeck |first1=Gene |publisher=Macalester College |access-date=September 28, 2015}}</ref> In 2010, she sold Access Trips.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.entrepreneur.com/article/219911 |title=The Spark That Fuels Wildfire Interactive |last1=Shinal |first1=John |date= June 28, 2011 |publisher=Entrepreneur Magazine |access-date= September 28, 2015}}</ref> In 2012, Google bought Wildfire for a reported $450 million and Ransom became the Director of Product at Google.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.slideshare.net/ovrdrv/google-world-infographic |title=Google World - Facts and Stats|publisher=LinkedIn Corporation |access-date=September 28, 2015}}</ref><ref name=stuff>{{cite web |url=http://www.stuff.co.nz/national/69495285/googles-kiwi-multimillionaire-on-how-she-did-it |title=Google's Kiwi multimillionaire on how she did it |last1=Dudding |first1=Adam |date= June 21, 2015 |publisher=Fairfax New Zealand Limited |access-date=September 28, 2015}}</ref>\n\nShe was named [[Ernst & Young Entrepreneur of the Year Award]] for New Zealand in 2011.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rasmussen.edu/degrees/technology/blog/5-women-who-are-revolutionizing-the-tech-industry/ |title=5 Women Who Are Revolutionizing the Tech Industry |last1=Bird |first1=Kendall |date=March 18, 2013 |publisher=Rasmussen, Inc |access-date=September 28, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://coofwomen.biz/news/entrepreneur-of-the-year/ |title=Entrepreneur of the Year 2012 |publisher=Co.OfWomen |access-date=September 28, 2015}}</ref> In 2013, she was invited to the [[White House]] by [[Barack Obama]] to receive a \"Champion of Change\" award recognizing her contributions as an immigrant entrepreneur.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ibabuzz.com/politics/tag/victoria-ransom/ |title=White House honors local immigrant innovators |date= May 29, 2013 |publisher=MediaNews Group |access-date=September 28, 2015}}</ref> In 2015, she was awarded the World Class New Zealander award along with former New Zealand Prime Minister, [[Helen Clark]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.stuff.co.nz/business/industries/69907501/helen-clark-wins-kea-world-class-new-zealand-award |title=Helen Clark wins Kea World Class New Zealand Award |last1=Anthony |first1=John |date= July 2, 2015 |publisher=Fairfax New Zealand Limited |access-date= September 28, 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nIn college she met [[Alain Chuard]], also a Macalester student and Ransom's future business partner.<ref name=fortune/><ref name=macalester/> The two married in March 2013 and had a daughter in 2014.<ref name=nz>{{cite web |url=http://www.nzherald.co.nz/business/news/article.cfm?c_id=3&objectid=10835387 |title=NZ startups can thrive, says Ransom |last1=Fletcher |first1=Hamish |date=September 21, 2012 |publisher=NZME Publishing Limited |access-date=October 13, 2015}}</ref> <ref name=stuff/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ransom, Victoria}}\n[[Category:New Zealand women chief executives]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Harvard Business School alumni]]\n[[Category:People educated at a United World College]]\n[[Category:Macalester College alumni]]\n[[Category:People educated at Whanganui Girls' College]]\n[[Category:People from Bulls]]\n[[Category:Carnegie Endowment for International Peace]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox person\n| name          = Victoria Ransom\n| image         = Victoria Ransom.jpg\n| alt           = \n| caption       = \n| nationality   = [[New Zealanders|New Zealander]] \n| education          = [[Bachelor of Arts]], [[Master of Business Administration]]\n| alma_mater        = [[United World College]], [[Macalester College]], [[Harvard Business School]]\n| occupation    = [[Entrepreneurship|Entrepreneur]]\n| known_for     = Co-founder and CEO of Wildfire Interactive\n| partner = [[Alain Chuard]]\n}}\n\n'''Victoria Ransom''' is a serial entrepreneur from New Zealand. She has developed three companies including [[Wildfire Interactive]], a social marketing [[Software as a service|SaaS]] company, where Ransom was CEO until it was sold to [[Google]] in 2012.<ref name=